<FIRST>r a PM-CastrationBill     02-24 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Castration Bill,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Castration Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Indiana House committee has approved a
bill that would permit a jail sentence to be suspended for a
convicted rapist, criminal deviate or child molester who undergoes
surgical castration.
   Rep. Richard L. Worden, an investigator for the public defender
in Allen County and a former constable, said he introduced the bill
out of frustration that current criminal sanctions against rapists
and child molesters don't deter criminals from committing those acts
again.
   ``You take the part away from the man that starts the process in
the first place,'' said Worden, a Republican.
   The crimes now carry prison sentences of six to 50 years,
depending on the circumstances.
   The bill, which the House County and Township Committee approved
by a 5-3 vote on Thursday, calls for a convicted rapist, child
molester or criminal deviate to be set free if after sentencing the
person volunteers for surgical castration. The measure now goes to
the full House.
   An opponent of the bill, Democratic Rep. John Gregg, pointed out
that many child molestation cases don't involve intercourse.
Offenders castrated after those crimes might still commit child
molestation again, he said.
   ``I don't think we ought to be setting our policy in Indiana to
follow Islamic countries,'' said Gregg.
   Another opponent, Ruth Peters of the Indiana Civil Liberties
Union, argued that rape often is a crime of violence, not one
motivated by sexual drives. Under Worden's proposal, she said, a
convicted rapist who had been castrated could go free to commit
other violent acts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
