<FIRST>r p PM-Conservatives     02-24 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Conservatives,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Conference Skeptical About Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While President Bush is half a world away, his
supporters are trying to convince skeptical conservatives he is a
worthy successor to their longtime hero Ronald Reagan.
   ``Ronald Reagan started the revolution,'' former Rep. Jack Kemp
told Thursday's opening session of the Conservative Political Action
Conference. ``I'll bet you right here and now today that George
Bush, President Bush, will consolidate it, strengthen it, broaden
it, broaden its appeal.''
   Long a conservative favorite, Kemp now is housing secretary in
the Bush Cabinet.
   Lee Atwater, Bush's hand-picked chairman of the Republican Party,
cited his involvement in three Reagan presidential campaigns and
then said, ``Another hero of mine is George Bush.''
   Confronted by an openly critical delegate from Young Americans
for Freedom, Atwater said that ``there is something to criticize
about any president'' but conservatives were ``not going to get a
better conservative elected the rest of this century than George
Bush.''
   YAF delegates from California issued a ``report card'' on the
Bush presidency and said he ``has walked away from his conservative
campaign promises that won him the election.''
   The group gave Bush an ``F'' on aid to the Nicaraguan Contra
rebels. ``It is well known that the Bush administration will refuse
to seek military aid to the freedom fighters,'' they said.
   When Jeffrey E. Wright, the chairman of the California YAF
chapter, confronted the party chairman after the speech, Atwater
said, ``There's nobody who feels stronger about freedom fighters
across this globe than George Bush.''
   ``I would not judge things quite this early if I were you and I
wouldn't be too harsh on him until you see what happens,'' said
Atwater.
   ``I have to judge him, sorry,'' said Wright.
   ``I'm sorry, too,'' said Atwater.
   Bush is used to criticism from delegates to this annual meeting.
   Two years ago, as the fight for the 1988 Republican presidential
nomination was heating up, Bush outraged many conservatives by
declining an invitation to address C-PAC.
   His six rivals appeared at the conference.
   Despite opposition from many conservative activists, Bush easily
won the GOP nomination and a little more than a month ago succeeded
Reagan in the White House.
   Reagan was a regular participant at C-PAC meetings, and his
retirement cast a long shadow on the current one.
   David Keene, chairman of the American Conservative Union, one of
the principal sponsors of the conference, noted that Reagan had
participated in 13 of the 16 C-PAC meetings, including all those
held while he was president.
   ``His absence this year really is symbolic of another change
within the movement, the Reagan era, for all of its importance ...
has ended,'' said Keene.
   Sergio Picchio, national chairman of Young Americans for Freedom,
said the retirement of Reagan meant ``we don't really have a leader
that unifies the whole movement.''
   When he and Keene were asked to identify likely successors to
Reagan as the leader of the conservative movement, the names they
cited included Kemp, Sens. Phil Gramm of Texas and Trent Lott of
Mississippi, and columnist and former White House aide Pat Buchanan.
   No one suggested Bush might succeed Reagan as the conservative
hero.
</TEXT>
