<FIRST>r w PM-IndianInvestigation     02-24 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indian Investigation,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Ask Bush to Take Initiative on Indian Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush should begin correcting ``the
deplorable conditions on most Indian reservations'' by putting a
someone in the White House in charge of issues affecting native
Americans, say three senators who have been investigating those
conditions.
   ``We urge you to consider our call for active and coordinated
policy-making at all levels of the government, most notably at the
White House, the Office of Management and Budget, and the
departments of Interior and Justice,'' said Sens. Dennis DeConcini,
D-Ariz., John McCain, R-Ariz., and Thomas Daschle, D-S.D., in a
letter Thursday to Bush.
   By putting someone at the White House in charge of Indian issues,
Bush would ``send a signal throughout the Indian communities of your
dedication to America's first inhabitants,'' they said.
   The senators are members of the Senate Select Committee on Indian
Affairs and have been conducting special investigative hearings on a
wide range of problems on reservations and within government
agencies doing business with them.
   They said they wanted to meet as soon as possible with whomever
Bush designates.
   The senators said their hearings will likely produce legislative
proposals for correcting longtime deficiencies in government
policies toward Indians.
   The White House could, in the meantime, get reform started, they
said.
   In their letter, the senators said testimony before their
committee casts doubt on whether the federal government is meeting
its responsibility to protecting the rights of American Indians to
their land, water, forest, hunting, fishing and mineral resources.
   ``As we are sure you will agree, legal representation is at the
very core of the federal government's trust responsibility to
American Indians,'' they said. ``The inherent conflicts facing the
federal trustee arise not only in legal matters, but also in policy
decisions.''
   The president was in Japan Thursday for the funeral of the late
Emperor Hirohito. There was no immediate response to the senators'
letter from the White House.
</TEXT>
