<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Japan-AircraftTechnology     02-24 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Aircraft Technology,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>FSX Deal Prompts Call for Putting Commerce Secretary in NSC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The handling of a controversial aircraft
technology deal with Japan has prompted a California congressman to
call for making the secretary of commerce a statutory member of the
National Security Council.
   ``I strongly feel the United States must give more weight to
long-term commercial interests in its national security
decision-making,'' Democrat Mel Levine told a House panel Thursday,
explaining why he plans to introduce legislation next week.
   Critics of the deal involving Japan's proposed FSX warplane _ to
be built using technology developed for the U.S. F-16 fighter _
contend it was negotiated by State and Defense department officials
without participation by the Commerce Department, U.S. Trade
Representative and other agencies.
   The Bush administration, faced with mounting concern on Capitol
Hill, has asked the Defense Department and Commerce Department to
review the strategic, commercial and technological aspects of the
project and submit a combined report to the NSC by March 10.
   Levine testified at a hearing of the House Energy and Commerce
subcommittee on commerce, consumer protection and competitiveness.
   The panel's chairman, Rep. James J. Florio, D-N.J., voiced
serious concern over the FSX deal, under which St. Louis-based
General Dynamics would join forces with Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy
Industries to co-develop and co-produce the next-generation fighter.
   ``While this proposal may sound innocent, it could be troubling
as far as our long-range national security is concerned,'' he said.
   ``Today, President Bush is in Japan, paying his respects on the
death of of the emperor,'' he said. ``That is something he should
do. But making massive amounts of sophisticated aircraft technology
available to Japan, or anyone, is something that, quite possibly,
the president should not do.''
   Under current law, the NSC's permanent membership comprises the
president, vice president, secretary of state and secretary of
defense. Frequently, however, presidents designate other people as
temporary members to participate in meetings on particular issues.
   Two former Pentagon officials, testifying before the panel, took
differing positions on the advisability of going forward with the
FSX deal.
   James E. Auer, now director of the Center for U.S.-Japan Studies
and Cooperation at Vanderbilt University in Nashville, Tenn., argued
that Japan needs technologically superior fighters to help offset
the threat posed by the Soviet Union's Far East force of 2,000
aircraft.
   Auer, who in 1979-88 served in the office of the assistant
secretary of defense for international security affairs, also said
the United States stands to benefit from the FSX because
``state-of-the-art Japanese technology may well make the F-16 a
better aircraft.''
   Frank J. Gaffney Jr., director of the Center for Security Policy,
a Washington-based think tank, said he saw no new Japanese
technology from which the United States should benefit.
   ``I, for one, am not persuaded that the co-cured composite wings
and phased array radar technologies identified for `flow-back' to
the United States under the FSX deal meet that test,'' said Gaffney,
former deputy assistant secretary of defense for nuclear forces and
arms control policy.
</TEXT>
