<FIRST>r w PM-Congress-FarEast     02-24 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-Far East,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Say Japanese Should Pay More</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's trip to Japan is leading to
renewed calls in Congress for the island nation to share more of the
burden for regional defense in the Pacific.
   ``Our defense effort is 9.2 times greater than the Japanese
effort, based upon the share of our respective gross national
products we devote to defense,'' Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., said
Thursday. ``The American taxpayer is wondering whether this division
of effort is fair any longer.''
   D'Amato said Defense Department figures showed that the United
States spent $3.7 billion to maintain forces in Japan in fiscal year
1985, and $5 billion the following. Those figures were the latest
available, though costs have undoubtedly risen, he said.
   While the Japanese have announced their 1989 defense budget will
increase by $1.56 billion to $31.6 billion over the previous year,
D'Amato said expenditures are actually declining as a proportion of
Japan's GNP.
   Bush was in Tokyo for the funeral of Emperor Hirohito on
Thursday. He has stepped gingerly when addressing the military
spending issue, saying that Japan is making adequate contributions
to regional defense but that any moves to do more will be welcomed
by the United States.
   Adm. Huntington Hardisty, head of the U.S. Pacific Command, said
the Japanese are ``well on their way'' to building up a force
capable of defending the sea lanes out to 1,000 miles.
   But Tokyo's military is no match for the Soviets, who ``operate
literally in Japan's back yard,'' he said.
   Although the Japanese have done much to increase defense
spending, ``I believe they can and should do more,'' he said.
   Sen. James McClure, R-Idaho, was more outspoken.
   ``I'm getting sick of everyone trying to soak Uncle Sam,'' he
said, describing the United States as ``guarantor of stability
throughout the world.''
   McClure said the American military presence is vital to Japan's
security, yet Washington bears many additional expenses in the
Pacific including those of maintaining 44,000 troops in Korea and
military bases in the Philippines.
   McClure said he thinks the United States should be given space
for overseas bases rent-free so long as Washington provides the
troops and supplies.
   Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., questioned the need to keep U.S.
troops in Korea, hinting that some might be withdrawn if the Senate
faces tough budget choices.
   ``I haven't figured out what the 44,000 troops are there for,''
he said.
   But Hardisty said a reduction of troops ``at this time would be
premature'' in light of the continued threat from North Korea.
</TEXT>
