<FIRST>r w PM-Tower-Debate     02-24 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tower-Debate,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Members Debate Perception, Process in Wake of Tower Defeat</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tower Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midway through an extraordinary 2{-hour Armed
Services Committee session, Sen. Alan Dixon, D-Ill., said ``there
may not be a smoking gun, but there's an abundance of smoke'' where
Defense Secretary-designate John Tower is concerned.
   Within moments, Wyoming's Malcolm Wallop uttered the scornful
Republican reply: ``There may not be a smoking gun, but there's
plenty of smoke. That's a strange standard, my friends.''
   Added the most junior senator on the committee, Republican Dan
Coats of Indiana: ``We are establishing a new standard ... that the
weight of allegations, or of public perception, carries more weight
than the facts.''
   By the time the Democratic-controlled panel assembled in a packed
Senate hearing room late Thursday, the outcome was already clear:
Tower's nomination would be sent to the floor with a recommendation
against confirmation, with the full Senate to decide its fate next
week.
   But that didn't stop all 20 members of the Armed Services
Committee from participating in an exercise in speechmaking Thursday
night as they struggled to explain their decisions.
   Republicans voiced alarm at a process in which so many lawmakers
could read the same FBI investigation files on Tower's alleged
drinking, womanizing and financial conflicts of interest, and come
to diametrically opposite conclusions along party lines.
   ``It seems that these things were orchestrated by somebody,''
said an exasperated Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., his voice rising.
   ``It is perception that is frightening this committee, it's not
the truth,'' Thurmond said. ``This committee ought to have the
courage to do what is right. Perception should not control this
committee... It ought to be the truth.''
   Committee chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga., listened intently, reminding
the members that it was President Bush himself who ``put ethics at
the center of his agenda,'' and he said the decision on Tower had
``genuinely torn'' members of the panel.
   But ultimately, said Nunn, stories of Tower's drinking were too
serious to ignore.
   ``I have searched in vain for several weeks for the point in time
when the nominee himself acknowledged this problem and dealt with it
decisively,'' he said. ``The nominee made it very clear that he has
never sought medical assistance for his drinking problem.''
   Other Democrats put different emphasis on the various allegations
against Tower, but all said the end result was that they could not
comfortably vote to put him in the chain of command over the
nation's military and nuclear forces.
   They pointed to the FBI reports, saying the documents indicated
Tower's acknowledged heavy drinking in the 1970s had extended into
more recent times and that the evidence included first-person
accounts.
   ``We should look elsewhere for a secretary of defense,'' said
Sen. James Exon, D-Neb., acknowledging that the confirmation process
had been personally painful to Tower. ``The system may not always be
fair, but it works.''
   Several Republicans, however, sounded a common theme: that in
Tower's 24 years in the Senate, none of his legislative colleagues
ever saw him out of control, even in all-night sessions and on long
overseas trips.
   ``I suppose John Tower might have been able to conceal a
problem'' from his colleagues, said Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine.
``But it's highly unlikely.''
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, the committee's senior Republican,
said he had interviewed every current senator who had served with
Tower. ``Not one single U.S. senator ... can ever recall a single
instance where any of his personal habits interfered with his
duty,'' Warner said.
   Republicans also emphasized Bush's right to select his Cabinet
nominees, and said they gave a heavier weight to the new president's
wishes. Only eight presidential nominees for Cabinet positions have
been rejected by the Senate in the nation's history.
   GOP committee members also suggested it was hypocritical for
senators to reject a former colleague over his drinking habits. ``I
wonder how many of us in this room would admit to the same
proclivity, to have a social drink?'' asked Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss.
``This is not a canonization.''
   Emerging from the hearing room after the vote, Republicans warned
that the debate, at least, was not over.
   ``This is probably worth discussing and debating on the floor,''
said Cohen. ``There is a man here whose reputation has been dragged
through the mire, and Republicans feel strongly about it... I think
it's a bad storm rising.''
</TEXT>
