<FIRST>u i AM-BushRdp 7thLd-Writethru a0840 02-24 1209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Rdp, 7th Ld-Writethru, a0840,1180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Attends Hirohito Funeral; Vows to Stand by Tower</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new 14th graf with explosion report, Bush already back
at hotel at time; picks up 14th graf pvs: In a xxx</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush attended Emperor Hirohito's funeral
Friday, taking a front-row seat as the Japanese waived protocol
rules to give him a prominent position at the solemn Shinjuku
Imperial Garden ceremony.
   In the hours preceding the funeral, Bush's attention was diverted
by the continuing problems of Defense Secretary-designate John
Tower. The White House, despite heavy overseas calling, was unable
to get the former Texas senator approved by the Senate Armed
Services Committee in Washington. It voted 11-9 to reject his
nomination.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater told reporters that
Bush was sticking by Tower, no matter how the committee vote went.
``The next step is to consider it on the floor, and that's what we
will do,'' he said.
   A steady rain fell and the weather was chilly as Bush and
dignitaries from some 160 countries gathered for the funeral
ceremony.
   Bush was shot down by Japanese anti-aircraft fire in World War
II, but said coming to the funeral was ``the right thing to do'' and
that he didn't want to look back.
   Wearing dark mourning clothes and a black overcoat with the
collar raised, Bush was seated with his wife, Barbara, on his right
and West German President Richard von Weizsacker on his left.
   The floor below them was heated with electrical coils, and a
brown wool blanket was placed on each chair.
   En route to the funeral site, Bush's motorcade crossed an
overpass just as the funeral procession containing Hirohito's hearse
proceeded immediately below.
   During the briefing at the White House press filing center,
Fitzwater said that U.S. officials hoped the Japanese would not be
offended by Bush's preoccupation with the Tower problem in
Washington.
   Fitzwater said Bush's attention to his embattled Cabinet
secretary should not be construed by the Japanese as showing
disrepect for their country on a national day of mourning.
   ``The timing is dictated by the work of the committee, not events
over here,'' the press secretary said.
   More than 10,000 invited mourners from Japan and abroad were
assembled at the Shinjuku Imperial Garden. Bush unexpectedly was
given a front-row seat as Japanese officials overrode protocol that
would have seated the president on the basis of his time in office _
just a little over a month.
   Hirohito, the last of the World War II era world leaders, died
Jan. 7 of cancer at age 87 after reigning for six decades.
   After the funeral, Bush returned to his hotel and was there when
an explosion damaged a highway along which the emperor's hearse was
due to be taken after the cermony. Police speculated that radicals
opposed to the emperor system were responsible for the blast.
   In a meeting with Japan's Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita on
Thursday, Bush ``began by expressing the condolences of the American
people'' upon Hirohito's death, White House press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater said.
   Absent from the public ceremonies was Empress Dowager Nagako,
Hirohito's 85-year-old wife, who is said to be ailing with chronic
back and hip problems. The Kyodo News Agency said she paid her last
respects during the palace ceremonies.
   Bush and his wife walked together to the site of Hirohito's
coffin and bowed in paying last respects, just before leaving the
funeral grounds.
   No disturbances were reported during the initial stages of
Friday's funeral, but a police official in the southern city of
Nagasaki said a letter containing a bullet and a death threat was
sent to city mayor Hitoshi Motoshima, who had earlier charged that
Hirohito bore some responsiblity for World War II.
   During the news briefing earlier, Fitzwater denied that Bush and
White House chief of staff John Sununu had discussed finding another
candidate for the top Pentagon job.
   ``I can flatly say that. I do flatly say that,'' he said. ``I've
talked to the president about that several times, including just 10
minutes ago. There's no consideration of alternative candidates.
There's no alternate list _ bar none.''
   Bush on Thursday held talks with three Mideast leaders, while
Secretary of State James A. Baker III challenged the Soviet Union to
pitch in with deeds instead of ``simply rhetorical exercises.''
   Bush's fast-paced diplomacy on the day of his arrival here
involved meetings with a succession of world leaders including
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Israeli President Chaim Herzog and
Jordan's King Hussein.
   After Bush's round of meetings, Baker suggested the Soviets
should contribute to the peace process in a ``concrete way'' by
establishing full diplomatic relations with Israel, using its
influence in Syria and denouncing ``radical countries'' such as
Libya.
   Baker said a ``new dynamic'' for peace existed in the area and
that Bush hoped to nurture it. The president's sessions with Mideast
leaders provided a counterpoint to Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze's 10-day tour through the region, where he attempted to
advance Moscow's role.
   First lady Barbara Bush, meanwhile, donned a tailored black suit
and an elegant strand of pearls to pay a visit Naoko Takeshita, the
wife of the Japanese prime minister.
   The two women sipped tea at Takeshita's official residence, with
Mrs. Bush expressing sympathy over Hirohito's death and the Mrs.
Takeshita offering congratulations on Bush's election as president.
   Bush's focus on the Middle East during his first overseas trip _
a five-day visit to three Asian capitals _ appeared to be an effort
to steal some of the spotlight from Shevardnadze's journey to the
area.
   Baker, briefing reporters after Bush's full day of meetings with
world leaders, said Soviet overtures to participate in a Middle East
peace were ``healthy, quite frankly.''
   But, he added, ``I suppose we would want to know that there were
concrete contributions that they had in mind, rather than simply
rhetorical exercises.''
   He said he would have a better idea of what the Soviets intend
when he meets with Shevardnadze in March in Vienna.
   Baker said contributing to the new dynamics for peace were talks
between the United States and the Palestine Liberation Organization
and statements by PLO leader Yasser Arafat denouncing terrorism.
   He said the United States intended to be active in the peace
process.
   However, he said ultimately a settlement would have to flow from
``direct negotiations between the Palestinians and the Israelis.''
   ``We are concerned that if we act too precipitously we might
preempt promising possibilities that could surface if we adopted a
more reasoned and measured approach,'' Baker added.
   Earlier, Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, said the subject
of a Middle East peace settlement also came up in a lunch with
French President Francois Mitterrand.
   ``We think there are some opportunities to move the (peace)
process forward,'' Fitzwater said. ``We want to be methodical and
deliberate in our approach.''
   On Cambodia, Bush voiced concern that the withdrawal of
Vietnamese there was proceeding ``at a slower pace than we would
like to see,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``President Bush also emphasized that we would like to see a
government in Cambodia that would involve Prince Sihanouk and would
not see a return to the power of the Khmer Rouge,'' the spokesman
said.
</TEXT>
