<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Explosion 2ndLd-Writethru   02-24 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Explosion, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0432,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blast Reported On Highway Along Hirohito's Funeral Procession</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hirohito Funeral, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with description of minor damage.
Picks up graf 7 pvs, `Several radical ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion Friday on a roadside embankment spilled
dirt and debris on a highway in suburban Tokyo shortly before the
motorcade carrying the body of Emperor Hirohito and the imperial
family was to pass, police said.
   The incident did not stop the funeral motorcade, which passed the
site later en route to the imperial mausoleums outside Tokyo where
the emperor was to be buried, said an official of the Metropolitan
Police Department.
   Japan Broadcasting Corp. showed workers sweeping dirt off a
section of six-line divided expressway in the western suburb of
Chofu where the highway runs below ground level.
   The police official said the blast occurred about 15 minutes
after the imperial motorcade left the funeral site in west-central
Tokyo. It was not immediately clear how far away the motorcade was
when the blast occurred.
   Police had mounted the biggest security operation ever in Japan
to protect the grand state funeral and about 9,000 mourners,
including President Bush and leaders from 162 other nations,
attending the funeral.
   The police official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said he
suspected radical guerrillas opposed to the imperial system were
responsible for the blast.
   Several radical groups had vowed to disrupt the funeral.
   In 1986, about 30,000 police on duty during the seven-nation
economic summit were unable to prevent guerrillas from firing two
homemade projectiles at the Tokyo summit site. No damage or injuries
resulted, but the attack seriously embarrassed the police.
   On Tuesday police said they found two projectile-launchers
connected to timers in a forest near Narita Airport, 35 miles north
of Tokyo, where many foreign dignitaries arrived to attend the
funeral.
</TEXT>
