<FIRST>r a PM-HomeLeveled     02-24 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Home Leveled,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contractor Levels Yard, Plus Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Harvell is so angry he would raise the roof
if he had one.
   The trouble is, someone razed his house, and now he says he can't
find the contractor who reduced the home to a pile of rubble.
   Harvell said he hired an Arizona contractor simply to level the
dirt around his house and push a fence down. Instead, his house,
valued at $80,000 to $90,000, was demolished recently by the errant
contractor.
   When he found out his house was being leveled, he ran to the man
doing the work, Harvell said.
   ``The smell of liquor on his breath almost knocked me down,''
Harvell said. ``The man just kept saying `I'm leveling, I'm
leveling.'
   ``He was drunk and said `All right, there is no problem. I'll get
my business partner and insurance papers and I'll be back in 15
minutes.' I never saw him again.''
   Harvell has yet to find the contractor, and police can't locate
him.
   Now he has retained an attorney and hired a private investigator
to track down the contractor.
   Harvell wanted the lawn leveled so he could put in a sprinkling
system and a new lawn.
   Rick Muchmore, who lives in the house, said he left to get some
groceries and returned to find a heap.
   He said when he left ``the tractor was out front but the house
was fine and all three doors were locked. When we returned the house
was gone.''
   A next-door neighbor, Carol Garcia, said she saw the house being
mowed down.
   ``I knew that the owner owned a business and since this area is
becoming a business district, we thought the owner was going to turn
it into a construction yard or something,'' she said. ``But then I
saw a bed and I thought something strange was going on.''
</TEXT>
