<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CFTCProbe     02-24 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CFTC Probe,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Official Says Sanctions Don't Necessarily Indicate Degree of
Abuse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge jump in disciplinary actions at the
Chicago Board of Trade and Chicago Mercantile Exchange does not
necessarily indicate the degree of abuse by commodities traders, a
General Accounting Office official told Congress.
   Richard Fogel, assistant comptroller general at the GAO, an
agency that is an investigating and auditing arm of Congress, said
results of an FBI investigation into commodities trading may give a
better idea of abuse at the board and the exchange.
   The testimony came Thursday at the first Senate oversight hearing
of the year on the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, a federal
agency which faces reauthorization by Congress.
   The GAO says the number of contracts traded at the Mercantile
Exchange grew from 40 million in 1984 to 80 million in 1988, and at
the Board of Trade from 80 million to 140 million during the same
period.
   In that same period, the number of traders sanctioned for
violations on the floor of the Mercantile Exchange went from 13 to
105, while sanctions at the Board of Trade went from a low of eight
in 1985 to a high of 32 in 1986. In 1988, the Board of Trade
sanctioned 13 floor participants.
   Fogel said that from 1984 to 1988, Mercantile Exchange fines for
trade practice abuses were a total $3.6 million. For the same
period, comparable Board of Trade fines were $811,000.
   Fogel told the Senate Agriculture Committee that the figures
could mean that an oversight system is working well, or that it
needs improvement because it is not finding abuses or punishing
offenders severely enough.
   But Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., called the number of sanctions taken
against traders ``pitiful'' compared to the volume of trading.
   The number of members expelled on both exchanges averaged about
two a year, Fogel said. He said that according to exchange
officials, permanent expulsion or lengthy suspensions are viewed as
more severe than fines because they deprive members of their
livelihood.
   Fogel said commission officials told the GAO that they could not
comment on their involvement in identifying or investigating alleged
abuses until after any indictments stemming from the FBI probe are
issued.
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., chairman of the committee, said that
over the coming months his panel will review dual trading, the role
of brokers and broker associations, the adequacy of exchange floor
monitoring, compliance and discipline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0146EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-HirohitoFuneral 7thLd-Writethru   02-24 1106</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito Funeral, 7th Ld-Writethru,a0844,1143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan, World Bid Farewell To Hirohito; Explosion On Funeral Route</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with explosion along funeral route.
Picks up graf 9 pvs, `After the ...' EDITS to trim and conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hirohito, the emperor-god made mortal by a
disastrous war, was honored Friday at a tradition-steeped state
funeral attended by the largest number of world leaders gathered
together in modern times.
   An explosion on a roadside embankment marred the day, spilling
dirt and debris on a highway shortly before the motorcade carrying
the emperor's body and the imperial family was to pass, police said.
   The motorcade, bound on a chilly, rainy day for the imperial
burial site west of Tokyo, passed the area where the blast occurred
without incident.
   Police said they suspected radicals who oppose the imperial
system were responsible. Several such groups had vowed to disrupt
the funeral, for which Japan's police mounted their biggest security
operation ever.
   At the funeral service, 51 black-robed bearers carried atop a
one-ton bier the body of the emperor who died in January at age 87
after a reign of 62 years that spanned Japan's rise to militarism,
its defeat in World War II and its ascent as a world economic power.
   ``The people will remember him forever,'' said his son and the
new emperor, Akihito, in a eulogy before leaders of 163 nations,
including President Bush.
   A deep-voiced male chorus sang a solemn song, a poem was read and
members of the imperial family went individually before the coffin
and bowed slowly.
   After the eulogies, Bush and his wife, Barbara, stepped to the
front of the hall, paused and made a slight bow before the coffin.
   The capital, a sprawling metropolis of 12 million people, came to
a standstill as 32,000 police were deployed to protect the
dignitaries.
   Police said the highway blast occurred about 15 minutes after the
imperial motorcade left the funeral site in west-central Tokyo. It
was not immediately clear how far away the motorcade was at the time
of the blast.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility.
   Early in the day, a black hearse carrying the emperor's
lace-draped coffin drove at 6 mph through central Tokyo along a
four-mile route from the moated Imperial Palace to the funeral site
at Shinjuku Imperial Garden.
   Police said about 210,000 people lined the streets. Some people
cried as the motorcade passed, and others held their palms together
in prayer.
   Members of the royal family carried umbrellas in the streaming
rain and wind.
   Trailing the coffin, a chamberlain dressed in white carried a
platter with a pair of white shoes that tradition says the deceased
monarch will wear to heaven.
   Mourners filled the two huge tents built at the garden for the
funeral.
   Officials overrode protocol to give Bush a front-row seat,
although tradition would have put him toward the back because of his
short time in office.
   Bush was shot down by Japanese anti-aircraft fire in World War
II, but said he decided to come to the funeral because it was the
right thing to do because Japan and the United States are allies.
   Also bowing before the coffin was Britain's Prince Philip, a
Royal Navy veteran of World War II, who was present at Japan's
surrender ceremony in 1945.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said in his eulogy that Japan
``will continue to strive mightily to ensure that Japan is open to
the rest of the world, full of vigor, and culturally rich, and will
further promote the cause of world peace and human welfare.''
   He described Hirohito's reign as ``eventful and turbulent times
for Japan, including the calamities of that deplorable war, the
struggle to reconstruct itself from the ruins amid confusion and
dire poverty and to regain its full independence.''
   About 400 demonstrators from three leftist groups gathered
peacefully at a park in west-central Tokyo, carrying banners
denouncing the funeral and branding Hirohito a ``war criminal.''
   ``Hirohito's war responsibility is great. He died without ever
resolving it,'' said a 30-year-old woman wearing a mask and
sunglasses at the rally.
   Historians generally agree that most of the decisions about the
war were made by Japan's military leaders and that Hirohito was
largely powerless. He relinquished his divine status under the
constitution imposed by the United States after the war.
   Hirohito was to be buried near the grave of his father, Emperor
Taisho, about 30 miles outside the city.
   Akihito, in a black tailcoat, black gloves and gray trousers, and
a black-veiled Empress Michiko were shielded by umbrellas as they
left the palace for the funeral motorcade.
   A 21-gun salute boomed from howitzers, mingling with ancient
court music played on pipes and drums. Crowds up to 10 deep watched
the motorcade as it pulled out of the main gate of the palace, moved
across the moat and along its route.
   The 13 hours of funeral ceremonies began with two hours of
private Shinto ceremonies presided over by the Akihito, 55, who
ascended the Chrysanthemum Throne after his father's death.
   The body of Hirohito, who died of cancer Jan. 7, was encased in
an inner wooden coffin and an outer one of metal.
   Before the procession, officers joining the largest security
operation in Japanese history checked cars and patrolled streets.
   Absent from the public ceremonies was Empress Dowager Nagako,
Hirohito's 85-year-old wife, said to be ailing with back and hip
problems. The Kyodo News Agency said she paid her last respects
during the palace ceremonies.
   Stores in the Ginza shopping district covered their advertising
signs and display windows. Most businesses along the procession
route were closed.
   Many of the dignitaries used Thursday for mini-summit meetings.
They included Bush, who is on his first trip overseas as U.S. chief
executive.
   The government proclaimed Friday a holiday, asking Japanese to
``suitably mourn'' Hirohito and observe a minute of silence at noon.
   To mark the funeral, the government pardoned 30,000 people
convicted of minor criminal offenses.
   The pardons allow an additional 11 million people to recover such
civil rights as the right to vote and run for public office, which
they had lost as a punishment for their offenses.
   A 72-year-old farmer, Morie Hiroki, tried to commit suicide by
ritual disembowelment, or harakiri, in Kyushu in southern Japan,
police spokesman Kennosuke Kumae said by telephone.
   He said Hiroki, who slashed his abdomen with a kitchen knife, was
in serious condition in the hospital. The spokesman said Hiroki had
served in China in World War II and left a note saying he felt he
had to follow the emperor in death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
