<FIRST>r a PM-HUAC-Wilkinson     02-24 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUAC-Wilkinson,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Activist Says FBI Improperly Investigated Him for 30 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil rights activist who was one of the
last Americans to serve prison time for contempt of Congress during
the McCarthy era has moved to overturn his conviction, based on an
uncovered FBI memo.
   A petition filed in U.S. District Court in Atlanta Thursday asks
that Frank Wilkinson's contempt-of-Congress conviction be set aside.
Wilkinson's lawyers argue that the government deliberately concealed
evidence that a crucial witness who testified against Wilkinson was
considered unreliable.
   Wilkinson, now 74, first came to the attention of the FBI during
the 1940s when he led a move to integrate public housing in Los
Angeles. He and fellow integrationist Carl Braden were the last of
36 Americans sent to jail for clashing with the House Committee on
Un-American Activities.
   A newly released FBI memo, which remained classified until last
year, shows the FBI knew in 1961 that Anita Edith Schneider, the
woman who accused Wilkinson of being a Communist, had ``exhibited
emotional instability'' at a 1955 hearing.
   Therefore, the 1961 memo said, information on Wilkinson's alleged
Communist Party membership ``comes from sources not considered
advisable to use as government witnesses.''
   Nonetheless, the Supreme Court used Ms. Schneider's testimony
that she knew Wilkinson as a fellow Communist party member in
rejecting an appeal by Wilkinson on a 5-4 vote.
   Wilkinson eventually served nine months of a one-year prison term
for refusing to answer the questions of the house committee.
   ``We have a government which had in its possession information
that clearly related to the reliability, the credibility, of the
only witness whose testimony was used to convict Frank Wilkinson of
contempt of Congress,'' said Wilkinson's attorney, Douglas E. Mirell
of Los Angeles.
   ``We believe that in fact a fraud was perpetrated by the
government upon the judicial system,'' Mirell said.
   Wilkinson's court petition invokes a procedure used when new
evidence comes to light following a conviction. It was filed by the
American Civil Liberties Union and the Los Angeles law firm of Loeb
&amp; Loeb.
   He obtained the memo about Ms. Schneider as part of the
settlement of his 15-year-old lawsuit against the FBI, seeking
information the agency had gathered about him and his group, the
National Committee Against Repressive Legislation.
   ``The whole course of First Amendment law has been affected by
it,'' said Paul Hoffman, legal director of the ACLU Foundation of
Southern California. ``What we have here is the government, by its
affirmative misrepresentation, in fact distorting the whole course
of constitutional history.''
</TEXT>
