<NOTE>Congressman Says Substantial Non-Federal Funding Available for SSC</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India has already agreed to spend $50 million
toward construction of the super collider and U.S. officials have
discussed cost-sharing options for the $5.9 billion high-energy
physics project, a congressman said.
   Rep. Joe Barton, R-Texas, told the House subcommittee on energy
research and development Thursday that non-federal sources can
provide a ``substantial'' chunk of the cost of the superconducting
super collider.
   Barton, whose district includes the super collider site, said
officials of Japan, Taiwan, Korea and several Western European
nations have held preliminary cost-sharing discussions with U.S.
officials.
   President Bush has endorsed the superconducting super collider
and recommended $250 million be appropriated in next year's budget
toward initial construction of what would be the largest scientific
instrument ever built.
