<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Institutes of Health will
immediately treat its workers who are accidentally exposed to the
AIDS virus with zidovudine, the only drug now approved for treatment
of the viral disease.
   In a notice posted late Thursday to NIH employees, an AIDS
advisory group announced that NIH director James B. Wyngaarden had
approved the emergency use of the drug, also known as AZT, for
research and clinical workers exposed to the AIDS virus in
laboratory or hospital settings.
   The AIDS virus is being studied at a number of laboratories at
the NIH, and there also are patients treated at the NIH clinics.
Elaborate laboratory procedures are in effect to contain and control
the virus, but there have been a number of health care workers
exposed through needle sticks or other accidents.
   At least one medical worker in the U.S. has developed AIDS after
such an accident.
