<HEAD>Elizabeth Taylor Receives America's Hope Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM DESERT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elizabeth Taylor was hailed as one of
Hollywood's last true legends during an all-star tribute to her
philanthropic works.
   The actress, who turns 57 Monday, was the recipient of America's
Hope Award at the Bob Hope Cultural Center in Palm Desert, an
exclusive resort 120 miles east of Los Angeles. The show was taped
for an hourlong ABC-TV special to be broadcast on March 9.
   The award acknowledged her charity work, including the
establishment of the American Foundation for AIDS Research.
   ``I thought that she looked just tremendous, absolutely regal,
like a princess,'' said Mickey Rooney, Miss Taylor's co-star in the
1945 classic, ``National Velvet.'' ``Elizabeth Taylor is one of the
last in the genre known as a real star. There are few people today
who are stars.''
   Stevie Wonder, Carol Burnett, June Allyson, Kenny Rogers, Bob
Hope and former President Gerald Ford were among the other
celebrants in attendance. Miss Taylor was escorted by Malcolm
Forbes, the publisher.
   Miss Taylor waved, smiled and welled up in tears during the
program, which featured personal tributes and excerpts from her
films.
   The actress, who has raised $14 million for various charities,
called upon others to help society.
   ``As human beings we must strive to remember that we are all
human beings. We must give of ourselves a compassion, a commitment
and our love,'' she said.
   Miss Taylor's appearance after a monthlong seclusion put to rest
speculation that she has gained weight and undergone treatment for
drug or alcohol abuse.
</TEXT>
