<FIRST>r i PM-Reporter'sNotebook     02-24 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Reporter's Notebook,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Japanese Ritual in American Eyes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American crowd at an American state funeral would
have been different. Americans would have come equipped with
binoculars. Americans would have made some noise. Americans would
have brought the children.
   Americans would have gotten acquainted with their neighbors and
chatted about the cold rain, saying they wished they had worn long
underwear.
   No American crowd would have been so capable of sitting so still
as long the Japanese did today at the funeral for their emperor. The
visiting American dignitary, President Bush, was surrounded by 9,800
Japanese, oblivious to him and demonstrating in every way the
differences between their two societies.
   In this nasty, wet cold, Americans would have clapped their hands
together to warm up, dabbed handkerchiefs to runny noses and stomped
their feet. The Japanese did none of that, sitting motionless in
silence for four hours or more, talking in whispers if they talked
at all.
   Americans would have huddled under the brown, furry blankets that
were provided for every Japanese guest at the funeral.
   The Japanese used the blankets as tidy lap robes. In their hands
some of them held little bags filled with a chemical. When the bags
are shaken, they emit a small amount of heat, enough to warm a hand.
One Japanese woman shook her bag and slipped it into her shoe.
   The crowd at the Imperial Garden assembled under two enormous
open-sided white tents. Most were too far away to see the
proceedings, but still able to watch seven giant television screens
that carried a fuzzy picture of what was going on before them.
   Here was Japan's elite: members of the parliament, of the
national and local governments, leaders of the giant corporations
that are household names around the world.
   Over and over, bows were exchanged. A person taking his seat
would first bow to those he recognized in his row. These were deep
bows, from the waist straight down, nothing held back, nothing
merely symbolic about them.
   Many acquaintances would bow upon seeing each other, shake hands,
bow again. Those who arrived early and took their seats rubbernecked
at the late arrivals. Latecomers offered bows and were bowed to in
return. Those already in their seats often bowed without rising.
   No public tears were shed here. The crowd was somber, stoic, not
grief-stricken.
   But nothing prepared an American visitor for the change in mood
around the corner. Some of the mourners slipped away to another wing
of the tent for a paper cupful of tea, served by young women in
black suits, for a smoke, for conversation, for a break.
   The air was dense with cigarette smoke, noisy with chatter. Men _
few women ventured in _ stood around tables which carried only one
thing: an ashtray. The visitors huddled around gas stoves to warm up
for a few minutes.
   The atmosphere was almost like that of a political convention,
but with the eternal bow substituting for backslaps.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0405EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LukensIndictment     02-24 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lukens Indictment,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Denies Wrongdoing In Sex Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEITH ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Donald Lukens denied any wrongdoing
after being indicted on a misdemeanor charge that he had sex with a
teen-age girl.
   Lukens, a Republican, was indicted Thursday by a Franklin County
grand jury on a charge of contributing to the unruliness and
delinquency of a child. The first-degree misdemeanor carries a
maximum jail term of 180 days and a $1,000 fine.
   The charge resulted from an investigation prompted by a secretly
videotaped meeting last November between Lukens and the girl's
mother, who contended Lukens paid for sexual relations with her
daughter on two occasions. One of those times allegedly was four
years ago when the girl was 13.
   The grand jury accused Lukens of having sexual intercourse with
the girl on Nov. 6, when she was 16, in his Columbus apartment.
   ``I do categorically deny that I contributed to the delinquency
and unruliness of a minor at any time, and I further categorically
deny the accuracy of the alleged facts upon which the charge was
apparently based,'' Lukens said from his Washington office. ``I am
innocent of the charge brought forth today.''
   Lukens, 58 and divorced, said his attorney had advised him
against commenting on the allegations beyond his brief statement.
   Lukens did not testify before the grand jury, which did not ask
him to appear, Franklin County Prosecutor Michael Miller said.
   No date for an initial court appearance was set for Lukens.
   The House Ethics Committee, which has jurisdiction over
allegations of wrongdoing by lawmakers, typically waits for the
outcome before taking any action in cases where members have been
charged in court.
   A criminal conviction does not automatically bar a legislator
from sitting in Congress.
   Columbus television station WSYX on Feb. 1 broadcast a videotape
that shows Lukens apparently offering a job to Anna Coffman after
she asked him why he was ``messing around'' with her daughter. The
station said it videotaped the Nov. 11 meeting between Lukens and
Ms. Coffman at a fast-food restaurant in Columbus.
   But the FBI and prosecutors reviewed the tape and said they found
no evidence of bribery.
   The grand jury heard testimony from the girl, Ms. Coffman and at
least two women who said they saw Lukens with the girl in his
apartment.
   Ms. Coffman, interviewed by WDTN-TV of Dayton following the
indictment, said she had hoped the grand jury would have returned a
more serious charge.
   ``I expected more because this is a very serious matter,'' Ms.
Coffman said. ``What kind of impression does it have on our
children, our future?''
   Mrs. Coffman's daughter said she thinks an appropriate penalty
would be to see Lukens go to jail and no longer be a congressman.
   ``It's like a hurt right underneath my heart,'' the daughter said.
   Lukens was first elected to Congress in 1966 and served two
terms. He lost a bid for governor in the 1970 Republican primary.
   After that race, he was barred from seeking public office for
five years for not filing campaign reports on time. That campaign
law was changed before the five-year period expired, and he was
appointed to the state Senate in 1971 to fill an unexpired term. He
returned to Congress in 1986.
</TEXT>
