<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador-Massacre     02-24 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Massacre,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Church Says Army Massacred Medical Staff, Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A female doctor and a
14-year-old girl may have been raped before they were killed in an
army massacre at a rebel field hospital, a human rights group says.
   Ten people, included wounded rebels, were slain in the Feb. 13
attack on the hospital by an elite army battalion, the Roman
Catholic Church's Legal Aid office said Thursday.
   The office, a highly respected human rights organization in El
Salvador, said the doctor's body bore 10 bullet wounds and the
teen-ager's body six. It said both were severely bruised on the
inner thighs and breasts.
   Radio Venceremos, the guerrillas' clandestine station, reported
on Feb. 15 that troops of the Atlacatl Battalion attacked and
destroyed the field hospital two days earlier.
   It said six people, three medical workers and three wounded
guerrillas, were killed.
   Both the Legal Aid office and the rebel radio identified the
female victims as Alejandra Bravo Betancourt, a 35-year-old Mexican
physician; and Rosibel Dubon, 14, a paramedic's aide. Their bodies
were exhumed and examined Feb. 17 by the Legal Aid office.
   The alleged massacre took place outside the village of Los
Encuentros near the Sumpul River that forms El Salvador's northern
border with Honduras.
   The northern province of Chalatenango, where Los Encuentros is
located, is a stronghold of leftist rebels waging a 9-year civil war
against the U.S.-backed government.
   Col. Ciro Lopez Roque, military commander of Chalatenango, told
reporters Thursday there was no field hospital near Los Encuentros.
But he said Atlacatl troopers killed several guerrillas, including
the Mexican doctor, in combat Feb. 13.
   ``They were treating one wounded subversive,'' said Lopez Roque.
``But it was not a field hospital. There wasn't even a hut there.''
   Legal Aid concluded a field hospital was in fact installed near
Los Encuentros, and that Atlacatl troops ``attacked and destroyed
the field hospital and killed war wounded and the medical personnel
present.''
   Legal Aid said in addition to the doctor and girl, five wounded
guerrillas and three other medical aides were killed in the Atlacatl
attack.
   ``Because the bodies of the two women were completely nude and
both were bruised around the breasts and on the inside of the
thighs, rape or attempted rape is presumed,'' the report said.
   The church office called the attack ``a flagrant violation'' of
the Salvadoran Constitution and of the 1949 Geneva Conventions.
   The alleged massacre took place 10 days after a visit to El
Salvador by Vice President Dan Quayle. Quayle delivered what he
called a very emphatic message to the effect that Washington
expected the Salvadoran armed forces to improve their human rights
record.
</TEXT>
