<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--France-Auction     02-24 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--France-Auction,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beethovan's Furniture Goes On Auction Block</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A living room set that graced Ludwig van Beethoven's
salon goes on the auction block next month.
   Dorotheum of Vienna and French auctioneer Jacques Tajan are
collaborating on a March 6-7 sale of 19th and 20th-century Austrian
art objects at the Drouot-Montaigne house in Paris. It includes
paintings, drawings and etchings by masters Gustav Klimt, Egon
Schiele and Oskar Kokoschka.
   The furniture set was owned by Beethoven until his death in 1827
and was part of his estate.
   Executed by the German Biedermeier school, the set includes a
love seat with a curved back and arms in solid walnut, three
fan-backed walnut chairs covered in green felt and a small laminated
table.
   The set is estimated to sell for at least $10,000.
</TEXT>
