<FIRST>r i PM-India-Sikhs     02-24 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Sikhs,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Militants Kill Five In Sikh Farming Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh gunmen crept into a Sikh farming
family's sleeping quarters near Amritsar and killed a father and his
four sons, a senior police official said today.
   Police blamed the same group of six separatists for a second
attack Thursday night in a nearby village in which another Sikh was
killed.
   More than 300 people have been killed so far this year by Sikh
extremists, who have for seven years waged a bloody guerrilla war
against the predominantly Hindu government for a separate homeland.
   The gunmen forced their way into the house of Amrik Singh, 65,
and opened fire on the male members with Chinese assault rifles,
Police Superintendent G.S. Mann said.
   Singh's wife and the wives of two of his sons were herded into
the next room during the shooting, Mann said. He said the attack
occurred in Rampur Thera village, about 25 miles north of Amritsar.
   Police said the six militants also killed Hajara Singh in Dhup
Sari village about 3 miles from Rampur Thera.
   Moderate Sikhs opposed to the violent campaign for a separate
state have been frequent targets of Sikh militants, who also kill
Hindus.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's population but are a slight
majority in Punjab. Militants among them claim they are
discriminated against by Hindus, who comprise more than 82 percent
of India's 880 million people.
</TEXT>
