<HEAD>First Private College Opens In Vietnam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first privately funded college in
Communist-ruled Vietnam opened this week in the capital Hanoi, the
country's official news agency reported.
   The Thang Long College opened Tuesday with a mathematics course
for 75 students, the Vietnam News Agency said in a report monitored
in Bangkok. It said the college would offer numerous courses and
issue diplomas recognized by the state.
   Vice Premier Vo Nguyen Giap was among those attending the opening
ceremony, said the report.
   Since coming to power in late 1986, Communist Party chief Nguyen
Van Linh has eased state and party control over education and many
other aspects of Vietnamese life.
   The main aim has been to develop the economy, one of the world's
poorest.
