<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0548EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     02-24 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City councilors who asked the city's
Law Department how to go about driving snakes from this heavily
Irish city got an answer harking back to the old sod.
   ``We have thought of suggesting you hire a consultant but the
only person we are aware of who successfully drove snakes out of an
area apparently retired a long time ago,'' city lawyers said in a
recent unsigned memo, referring to the legend of St. Patrick driving
the snakes from Ireland.
   The councilors made the request a few weeks ago because of
complaints about a pet python on the loose in a residential
neighborhood. The nine-foot python disappeared three months ago and
hasn't been seen since.
   The city lawyers' went on to suggest in their memo that the
councilors visit the St. Patrick's Day Parade in neighboring
Holyoke. The march, which annually attracts more than 225,000
people, ``is regarded as being most conducive to the thoughtful
discussion and consideration of driving snakes from places,'' they
said.
   The last known fatality from a snake bite in Massachusetts
occurred outside Springfield in 1761 when Timothy Mireck was struck
by a rattlesnake. The song ``On Springfield Mountain,'' considered
one of America's first folk tunes, commemorates Mireck's encounter
with the ``pesky sarpent.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coffee dispute is brewing at City Hall.
   George Jacoby, an aide to Mayor Sophie Masloff, says he's
steaming over a decision by City Controller Tom Flaherty to
challenge a $177.60 bill submitted for coffee supplied to the
mayor's office.
   ``The vast majority of the coffee consumed in the mayor's suite
is by visitors. We have very little hospitality to offer other than
a cup of coffee,'' he said.
   Gil Martinez, a contracts supervisor for Flaherty, recently wrote
a memo to the mayor challenging the bill and claiming the mayor
failed to follow proper procedures for procuring the percolating
perk. He said a contract must be awarded for a coffee service.
   ``The more important question is how can you justify using tax
dollars to purchase coffee for your office?'' Martinez said.
   Flaherty and Masloff are among several Democrats running for
mayor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city is spending $125,000 to install a toilet
for a bridge tender staffing the University Bridge, and the issue is
creating a stink among neighbors who say the hang-down plumbing is
an eyesore.
   A water-supply pipe has already been installed, at a cost of
$40,000, for the north tower toilet on the drawbridge.
   But work on the sewer pipe has been stopped for the present in
response to complaints from neighbors and the city Engineering
Department's own surprise at how ugly the 4-inch cast-iron sewer
line looks hanging from rods under the bridge, said Jim Bodoia,
project engineer.
   Critics have suggested a pump system, which would allow the
plumbing to be hidden under the bridge deck. Bodoia said that would
be more expensive, as would a holding tank arrangement that was
considered by the city.
   However, Bodoia said that with the complaints, a decision still
has to be made on whether to go ahead with the unsightly
installation or an alternative.
   Why not just have the bridge tender walk to the south tower
toilet when nature calls?
   That would require a walk of about a block each way, and the
Engineering Department's Ed Engel said the Coast Guard frowns on the
operator leaving the tower, in case boat traffic approaches.
</TEXT>
