<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Spacemeals     02-24 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Spacemeals,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cosmonauts Dine In Style</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What do you feed a hungry cosmonaut?
   The Soviet news agency Tass suggests the fare aboard the Mir
space station is so out-of-this-world that it would bring water to
the mouths of earthbound gourmets.
   ``Some dishes are so exquisite that lovers of gourmet food on
Earth would be glad to have them,'' the news agency said Thursday.
``These include chicken paste with plums, sturgeon with jellied
sauce, processed fruit and all kinds of juices.''
   For the anniversary of the Soviet army and navy Thursday,
cosmonauts Alexander Volkov, Sergei Krikalev and Valery Polyakov
dined on pickled cucumbers, lemons, fresh fruit and Russian bee
honey, Tass said.
   Tass said such delicacies are part of a space diet that includes
about 70 dishes, including meat, fish and dairy products. Some
Soviet spacemen spend months in orbit.
   Alas, cosmonauts must forgo the bubbly, according to Tass:
``Cosmonauts are not allowed to have alcholic drinks even on the
most solemn occasions.''
</TEXT>
