<DOCNO> AP890224-0051 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos     02-24 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos,0649</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Marks Third Anniversary of Exile in Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the Philippine and U.S. governments
consider the fate of Ferdinand E. Marcos, doctors say his exile here
may soon end without a struggle _ in death.
   Sunday is the third anniversary of the deposed Philippine
president's arrival in exile, and he will probably mark the occasion
from his hospital bed, where he has spent most of 1989. Doctors say
he appears tired and defeated.
   ``It's very hard to describe why a patient is so lethargic, why
they don't move around in bed or try to stand,'' said Dr. George
Druger, a lung specialist who has treated the 71-year-old Marcos for
the past six weeks at St. Francis Medical Center.
   ``It's almost as though he's lost his will to live. He's trying,
but he's not fighting like he used to,'' Druger said.
   Druger, one of a team of doctors treating the former president,
said Marcos has only a 50 percent chance of ever leaving the
hospital and a 10 percent chance of living another year.
   Marcos' ill health has prevented him from being arraigned in New
York on federal racketeering charges. He and his wife, Imelda, are
accused of stealing more than $100 million from their homeland and
stashing it in the United States.
   After their indictment Oct. 21, Mrs. Marcos flew to New York to
plead innocent and was freed on $5 million bail.
   Although the Philippine government claims Marcos stole billions
of dollars during his 20-year rule, it has never charged him with
fraud.
   U.S. District Judge John F. Keenan is scheduled to resume a
hearing March 6 on whether Marcos is well enough to be arraigned in
New York. His attorneys argue Marcos should be granted a ``medical
severance,'' meaning prosecution against him would not proceed
unless he recovers. Prosecutors have said it is too early to
determine Marcos' long-term prognosis.
   Aides said Marcos' spirits were buoyed Thursday by a visit from
Cardinal Ricardo J. Vidal, the archbishop of the central Philippine
city of Cebu, who performed Mass at Marcos' bedside and gave
Communion to Marcos and his wife.
   ``This is a pastoral and spiritual visit to a very sick man,''
Vidal said. ``It is the only reason I came to Hawaii. I'm not acting
as an emissary.''
   Marcos remains in guarded condition in the hospital's intensive
care unit. Druger said Marcos improved slightly in the past week,
relying on a respirator only while sleeping and speaking clearly for
the first time in three weeks.
   Marcos, who arrived in Hawaii on Feb. 26, 1986, after being
ousted in a popular uprising, has been hospitalized since Jan. 15
for treatment of pneumonia and bronchial asthma.
   Earlier, he was hospitalized with congestive heart failure; he
also suffers from kidney problems.
   A few weeks ago Marcos aides said it was the leader's dying wish
that he be allowed to return to his homeland. Philippine President
Corazon Aquino has banned his return, saying it would threaten
national security.
   Mrs. Marcos has visited her husband daily during his hospital
stay while maintaining her whirlwind social life. The 59-year-old
former beauty queen is often sighted at Honolulu's most expensive
restaurants and popular nightclubs.
   While her husband lies in the hospital, Mrs. Marcos' outings are
tracked by FBI agents and reported in local gossip columns.
   ``Sometimes she sees the FBI guys sitting at the other end of the
restaurant and she invites them over,'' said Gemmo Trinidad, a
family spokesman. ``Some things (in the news media) hurt her
feelings, but the general public is nice to her, people even ask for
her autograph. She says their friendliness helps restore her faith
in America. And she still has hope that she and the president will
be cleared.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
