<FIRST>r a PM-RockwellPaintings     02-24 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rockwell Paintings,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockwell Paintings Returned Steel Company after Court Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST MIDDLESEX, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirteen Norman Rockwell paintings,
tucked away in a Florida corporate office for 20 years, were
returned to the steel company that commissioned them thanks to an
out-of-court settlement with its estranged chairman.
   The 23-by-30-inch paintings, commissioned by Sharon Steel Corp.
and produced by the renowned artist in 1966, were recently returned
to the steelmaker by the company's now powerless chairman, Victor
Posner.
   Sharon Steel executives and guests, including three retired
steelworkers who modeled for Rockwell, paid $50 a ticket for charity
Thursday night at a black-tie viewing of the oil paintings, which
depict workers involved in various steelmaking operations.
   ``It looks better each time I look at it,'' said George
Petropulos, a 29-year veteran of Sharon Steel who posed for one of
the paintings.
   He said another steelworker was originally chosen to be a subject
for the painting.
   ``But Mrs. Rockwell saw me at the company and thought I was more
mature for the picture than the other person,'' Petropulos recalled.
   After taking control of the steelmaker in 1969, Posner ordered
the paintings moved to his corporate offices in Miami Beach, Fla.
   Sharon Steel, which is operating under Chapter 11 bankruptcy
protection, had to file suit against Posner last July after he first
refused to return the paintings. Posner agreed to relinquish the
paintings in an out-of-court settlement.
   ``You never know, we may be forced to sell them in the future by
events beyond our control,'' said Franklin ``Bill'' Agnew, who was
recently appointed by bankruptcy court to oversee the company's
reorganization. ``But I hope they stay in the community for a long
time to come.''
   Roger Reed, owner of Illustration House Inc. of New York, said he
had viewed copies of the paintings in a Rockwell catalogue and
believed each was worth $20,000.
   A mystery of sorts surrounds one painting. The company
commissioned 14 paintings, but only 13 were shipped to Posner's
offices 20 years ago. The one painting has never been found.
   That irks John Reichert, who posed for the missing painting.
   ``How can somebody walk in an office and take it away without
anyone knowing,'' Reichert said. ``Somebody knows where it is.''
   Company executives said they are at a loss as to where the
painting may be.
   ``The painting could have been given to one of our customers. But
who knows,'' said Walter Sieckman, chief operating officer for
Sharon Steel.
   He noted that when the paintings were first completed they
weren't considered exceptionally valuable.
   ``It was considered part of our advertising program at the
time,'' Sieckman said.
   Rockwell worked with his third wife, Molly, over a four-day
period in photographing the men who were subjects in the 14
paintings. He later put the images to canvas at his studio in
Stockbridge, Mass.
   ``He made you so at ease so quickly,'' recalls Robert Addicott, a
43-year veteran of Sharon Steel. ``He was a quiet man but he had a
sense of humor.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
