<FIRST>r a PM-Woolworth'sGuns     02-24 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Woolworth's Guns,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Councilor Objects To Gun Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the F.W. Woolworth Co. store downtown, an M-1
semi-automatic carbine is for sale for $199.99 as the ``gun of the
month,'' and that does not sit well with City Councilor David
Scondras.
   ``It's obscene to have a store that represents what is wholesome
in America ... to sell these weapons,'' Scondras said. ``They
shouldn't sell guns.''
   He wants such weapons as the M-1, which was used during World War
II, banned.
   A gun rack in the upstairs sporting goods department of the
downtown Woolworth's includes a gun rack stocked with rifles, among
which is a semi-automatic equipped with a steel bayonet.
   ``Guns with bayonets don't appeal to sportsmanship. They appeal
to Rambo,'' said Scondras. ``Why do hunters need a bayonet, to
skewer a squirrel? Give me a break.''
   The manager of the store referred questions to Woolworth's
headquarters in New York; a secretary there said no one from the
company would comment.
   Scondras said he would write to Woolworth's asking the chain to
stop selling guns.
   ``It sends a very bad message out to kids. Every kid in the world
knows about going to Woolworth's for toys and candy,'' he said. ``I
don't think their parents want them thinking about going there for
guns.''
</TEXT>
