<FIRST>r i PM-Honduras-Bombings     02-24 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras-Bombings,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Find 85 Tons Of Explosives, Four Bombings In Less Than
A Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities found in an abandoned
house 85 tons of explosives that subversives intended to use for
more terrorist bombings, a military commander said.
   Four bombs have gone off in Honduras in less than a week.
   The explosives were found by police and soldiers Thursday in La
Ceiba, where the latest bombing occurred, in an abandoned house near
Hector Caraccioli Air Base, said Col. Erick Sanchez, chief of the
4th Infantry Batallion.
   ``These materials were to be used by subversive groups to
continue the chain of terrorist acts that lately have unleashed
panic in Honduras,'' he said.
   The cache included dynamite, detonators, liquid explosives, and
other explosives used in the construction industry, said Sanchez.
   No suspects were detained.
   Before dawn on Thursday, the offices of the Standard Fruit Co., a
subsidiary of the New York-based Castle &amp; Cook, were attacked in La
Ceiba, which is about 250 miles north of Tegucigalpa.
   On Tuesday, a bomb ripped through City Hall in Tegucigalpa,
injuring 10 people. Another bomb exploded Monday in a building
housing offices of the Interior Ministry in the capital. No injuries
were reported.
   On Saturday, a crude bomb thrown at the back of a bus carrying
U.S. soldiers north of Tegucigalpa injured three soldiers and two
Honduran civilians.
   No one has claimed responsibility for any of the attacks.
   Honduran leftists have protested the presence of U.S. soldiers
conducting maneuvers with the Honduran military.
</TEXT>
