<FIRST>r a PM-Meredith-Duke     02-24 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Meredith-Duke,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Pioneer Meredith Says He Agrees With David Duke On Many
Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights pioneer James H. Meredith is
unfazed by the election of a former Ku Klux Klan leader to the
Louisiana Legislature and said he even agrees with him on numerous
issues.
   ``There's nothing wrong with his English,'' Meredith said of
David Duke. ``I understand what he's saying and a lot of it is the
same thing I've been saying.''
   Meredith, 55, a self-described conservative who was in New
Orleans Thursday to speak about a federal order to desegregate
Louisiana's colleges, said he found Duke more believable than many
other politicians.
   ``People say `he used to be a Klan leader' and he used to be this
or that, well, I'm a Christian and I believe people can change,''
Meredith said.
   Meredith, who had to be escorted into the University of
Mississippi by U.S. marshals in 1962 and who still bears the scars
of three shotgun blasts from an assassination attempt in 1966, said
before his speech that he and Duke agree on many things.
   ``We agree on equal opportunity. I am also against ...
affirmative action programs,'' he said. ``But it really shouldn't
get to that. Under our Constitution the people of a district elect
the person they want to represent them. And a if majority of those
people select a candidate, no one has a right to question it.''
   In Baton Rouge meantime, Duke said he was pleased with his
assignments on the state House of Representatives' Judiciary
Committee and Health and Welfare panel.
   ``That's what I wanted,'' Duke said. ``I want health and welfare
because obviously welfare reform is one of the most important parts
of my program. Judiciary, I'm concerned about our courts and law
enforcement.''
   Meredith, who like Duke is a Republican, echoed the former Klan
grand wizard in other areas.
   ``I'm against abortion. I'm against handing out diplomas to black
Americans who have not been taught what those diplomas represent,''
he said. ``I don't believe in paying welfare to able-bodied men and
women.
   ``I think those things are wrong and bad for us as a people. They
are the way the liberal establishment keeps power over people.''
</TEXT>
