<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     02-24 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Along East Coast; Cold Sweeps Through South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Carolinas were digging out from a storm today that dumped up
to 7 inches of snow in some areas, and the outlook for much of the
East Coast was for more of the same.
   A low pressure area off the North Carolina coast continued
producing snow from eastern Georgia across the Carolinas and along
the Atlantic Coast. The storm center was to move northeast and
produce wintry weather in New England late tonight.
   Snowfall was heaviest in North Carolina, where 7 inches fell in
Lincoln County. Charlotte reported 5 inches. Driving conditions were
hazardous and numerous accidents were reported due to freezing snow
and ice on roads.
   Snowfall in South Carolina Thursday night included 5 inches at
Greenwood, and 3 to 5 inches in Rock Hill.
   Heavy snow also fell in Georgia, but was diminishing as the storm
system moved north.
   The snow was to spread up the Atlantic Coast to much of New
England today.
   An arctic air mass plunged as far south as Florida this morning,
and the 34-degree temperature at Orlando was lower than the 37
degrees Minot, N.D., posted.
   Wind chill readings in Georgia were in the single digits early
today.
   The nation's high temperature Thursday was 92 degrees at Santee,
Calif.
   Today's forecast called for snow in North Carolina, the Middle
Atlantic States and New England; snow squalls in northwest New York
and northeast Minnesota; and rain showers in the Pacific Northwest.
   Temperatures were to reach the teens and the 20s in inland New
England, the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes; and the 30s and 40s in
coastal New England, the Middle Atlantic States, Florida, the Gulf
Coast, the Tennessee Valley, the Mississippi Valley, parts of the
Plains, northern Rockies and the Pacific Northwest.
   The mercury was to approach 70 degrees over the southern tip of
Texas and climb into the 80s in southern New Mexico, Arizona and
parts of California. High temperatures in Florida were to be in the
low 50s, with 60s in the remainder of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 8
degrees below zero at Lansing, Mich., to 67 at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 19 windy; Boston 28 windy; Buffalo 7 partly
cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 31 snow; Cincinnati 15 snow; Cleveland 12
snow; Detroit 08 fair; Miami 43 windy; New York 26 windy;
Philadelphia 28 windy; Pittsburgh 11 snow; Portland, Maine 17 fair;
Washington 26 wind.
   _Central: Bismarck 31 fair; Chicago 10 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 34
fair; Denver 38 fair; Des Moines 13 cloudy; Indianapolis 12 fair;
Kansas City 23 cloudy; Nashville 19 fair; New Orleans 30 fair; St.
Louis 14 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 45 fair; Anchorage 16 cloudy; Las Vegas 56
fair; Los Angeles 60 partly cloudy; Phoenix 65 partly cloudy; Salt
Lake City 31 foggy; San Diego 61 partly cloudy; San Francisco 48
partly cloudy; Seattle 37 fair.
   _Canada: Toronto 1 fair.
</TEXT>
