<DOCNO> AP890224-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0636EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SovietTrade     02-24 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Trade,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Seek High Tech Joint Ventures With U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is posing the $25,000
Question, offering a prize in that amount to anyone who can figure
out the best way to convert the ruble into dollars, the top Soviet
economist says.
   A warning, though, to would-be entrants: Some Western economists
think the question may be unanswerable.
   Abel Aganbegyan, chief economic adviser to Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev, mentioned the $25,000 prize Thursday in a speech to a
group of international bankers and businessmen.
   Aganbegyan said the Soviets are planning the contest jointly with
California's Esalen Institute, once better known for its encounter
sessions and other experiments in radical psychology.
   The Soviets have increasingly discussed the possibility of making
the ruble ``convertible'' so that it can be traded on world markets.
Because their currency cannot be traded for Western currency, it has
no intrinsic value on other markets. That severely limits the
Soviets' ability to buy foreign goods.
   In his San Francisco speech, Aganbegyan spoke of the
possibilities of converting the ruble to hard currency over the next
seven to 10 years or the creation of free trade zones in the country
with a second currency that would be semiconvertible.
   ``This semiconvertible currency would be backed by gold and
export goods,'' he said.
   The Soviet Union is aware that the official rate of the ruble is
``not realistic'' at $1.60, he said, adding that it might eventually
be devalued to half that amount. Black market rates for rubles in
the Soviet Union are 25 cents to 30 cents.
   In the meantime, he said, ``we plan to double internal prices for
raw materials and fuels ... to bring them closer to world prices.''
   Some Western economists scoff at the notion of the Soviets making
the ruble convertible, saying such a move would require a wholesale
transformation of the nation's economy.
   Asked about the idea last December, Val Zabijaka, an economist on
the Soviet desk at the U.S. Commerce Department, said, ``You
probably believe in Santa Claus, too.''
   In another speech in Silicon Valley, Aganbegyan told 200
executives of high-tech companies that the Soviet Union wants to
encourage joint ventures with U.S. firms to commercialize Soviet
technology.
   The Soviet Union recently abolished requirements that joint
ventures with companies from other countries had to be at least 51
percent Soviet-controlled.
   Jack Wilson, vice president of Dataquest Inc., a San Jose market
research firm that sponsored the speech to high-tech leaders, said
the relaxation of restrictions on joint ventures was welcomed in
Silicon Valley.
   ``There may be real prospects for technology deals,'' Wilson
said. ``But it's still a long march to develop any kind of a market
there. These deals are hard to put together.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
