<DOCNO> AP890224-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BombScare     02-24 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bomb Scare,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline's Fake Explosives Kit Sparks Airport Bomb Scare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suitcase filled with dummy weapons used to train
security personnel triggered a real-life emergency drill at Miami
International Airport as a jumbo jet was ordered off a runway and a
busy terminal was evacuated.
   ``It looked like a normal suitcase,'' airport spokeswoman Amalia
Fernandez said Thursday. ``There were two imitation hand grenades
and a fake firearm, like a pistol. There was also a fake explosive
device complete with a detonator and tubes.''
   The suitcase, a demonstration kit belonging to a London-based
security manager for Pan American World Airways, originally cleared
customs in London and was supposed to be loaded onto Pan Am Flight
445 to Caracas, Venezuela, said Pan Am spokeswoman Pamela Hanlon in
New York.
   Airport security spotted the bag after it was left behind by
mistake, and immediately called the Pan Am Airbus A-300 off the
runway for a security check, delaying the flight by an hour, Ms.
Hanlon said.
   They also closed the airport's international flight terminal for
about 30 minutes, causing minor flight delays but no cancellations,
said Ms. Fernandez.
   ``Normally, we would hear from airline somehow,'' Ms. Fernandez
said. ``We were not notified of this ... and, of course, when you
see that in our security screening system, it looks like the real
thing.''
   Pan Am's London security office was supposed to send a message to
the airlines' Miami office and to security personnel at the airport
warning them of the kit, Ms. Hanlon said.
   ``We believe it was sent, but somehow it was not received,'' she
said. ``It's one of those miscommunications that are unfortunate.''
   Security seminars held throughout the Pan Am system have used the
fake weapons kits for some time, Ms. Hanlon said.
   She said the anti-terrorism classes were routine long before a
bomb exploded on Pan Am's Flight 103 from London last December,
killing all 259 people aboard in a crash in Lockerbie, Scotland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
