<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0642EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0834 02-24 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0834,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tony Lo Bianco Stars as ``Hizzoner!'' on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs of other reviews; no PMs planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the exclamation point, there's not much
to cheer in ``Hizzoner!'' _ a one-man show based on the life of
Fiorello H. LaGuardia.
   The play, which opened Thursday at Broadway's Longacre Theater,
seems like a textbook recitation about one of New York's most famous
and colorful mayors. Little of that color comes through in
playwright Paul Shyre's theatrical biography which smacks of
extensive research but little imagination.
   Shyre sets his play in 1945 on the mayor's last day in office.
While LaGuardia is cleaning out his desk, he also dusts off his
memories, giving the audience a dry, rather straightforward
accounting of his life. Shyre makes it sound like a resume.
   There are no surprises and very little insight into the man who
not only was mayor of New York for 12 years but also a congressman,
a clerk in the U.S. foreign service, an Army pilot and a tireless
champion of the underdog.
   Whatever heart the evening has comes from the hard work of actor
Tony Lo Bianco who invests the play with an energy that rarely
flags. Lo Bianco has to work doubly hard, too. During a preview last
week, he broke an ankle sliding down a fire pole. He continued with
the performance but now wears a black foot cast.
   The cast hasn't hampered the actor's movement around designer
Eldon Elder's credible recreation of the mayor's City Hall office.
In fact, it adds to the performance, giving Lo Bianco a jaunty gait
as he makes his way back and forth across the stage.
   The actor's physical resemblance to LaGuardia is amazing. His
bulldog frame suggests the great man's height and weight, and he has
down pat that peculiar way the mayor scrunched up his face when he
got excited. For the most part, he also captures LaGuardia's voice,
a high-pitched, almost squeaky way of talking.
   Lo Bianco is at his best in several of the imaginary press
conferences he holds with newspaper reporters. The mayor's banter
doesn't stop and neither does Lo Bianco in his efforts to get the
last bit of humor out of each joke.
   Famous names _ Eleanor Roosevelt, Robert Moses, Jimmy Walker,
Gypsy Rose Lee, Calvin Coolidge, Dorothy Parker _ are dropped into
the evening at regular intervals, but their associations with
LaGuardia are not as interesting as the mayor's personal revelations
about the death of his first wife and child, his father's Army
career or occasional thoughts about being mayor of New York.
   The best moment in the play occurs near the end when LaGuardia
muses on the price of progress. He worries about the homeless men
bulldozed into oblivion when their shacks near the Hudson River are
torn down to start construction of the Henry Hudson Parkway. Was the
project worth the human cost?
   But that introspection is rare in ``Hizzoner!'' The play is more
concerned with events, presented in the most prosaic way possible.
LaGuardia's various political campaigns _ successful and
unsuccessful _ are related in often confusing detail and eventually
blur together. Director John Going hasn't found a way to separate
them on stage.
   Other famous moments are glossed over. When LaGuardia reads the
comics over the radio during a newspaper strike, it falls flat. The
incident is well-known, but seems an afterthought to the meandering
second act which repeats many of the devices _ press conferences,
radio programs _ used in Act 1.
   LaGuardia's life certainly had enough drama for a theater piece.
The creators of ``Fiorello!'' captured it 30 years ago in the
Pulitzer Prize-winning musical. ``Hizzoner!'' hasn't. It has put the
biographical facts but not the man himself on stage.
   In other reviews:
   The New York Post's Clive Barnes says Lo Bianco ``cuts an
engaging and persuasive figure as LaGuardia.'' But, he says, the
play's ``basic trouble is that its sole character appears to be
running for office as much as appearing in a play.''
   Howard Kissel in the Daily News wrote that: ```Hizzoner!' has the
faults of most one-person shows based on famous people. It quickly
becomes a history lesson.'' Kissel says Lo Bianco ``gives LaGuardia
a vulgarity, a buffoonishness that diminishes the Little Flower
unfairly.''
   In The New York Times, Mel Gussow wrote that the LaGuardia
presented in the play, ``would win few votes either as a candidate
or as a comedian.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0068 </DOCNO>
