<SECOND>PM-Korea-Hirohito,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean Protesters Burn Japanese Flags To Denounce Hirohito</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hirohito-Funeral, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters denouncing Emperor Hirohito
as ``mankind's biggest war criminal'' burned Japanese flags in two
cities today and riot police blocked demonstrators from marching on
the Japanese Embassy.
   Riot police with shields dispersed about 70 protesters who tried
to march to the embassy after 200 people held an anti-Japanese rally
in a park and burned a flag to denounce Japanese war crimes. Police
took 10 marchers into custody.
   ``Japan must apologize!'' and ``Let's drive out U.S. and Japanese
influence!'' protesters shouted.
   In the southern city of Pusan, about 60 protesters burned a
Japanese flag near the Japanese consulate and demanded Japan
apologize for war atrocities, according to Yonhap, the South Korean
news agency.
   Protesters in Seoul tried to march to the Japanese Embassy to
demand an apology for Japan's harsh treatment of South Korea under
the colonial rule of Hirohito, whose funeral was held today in Tokyo.
   Japan occupied Korea from 1910 to 1945.
   ``Hirohito was mankind's biggest war criminal and our national
foe,'' said a statement by protesters. ``Japan has never made a
formal apology to the Koreans for their wrongdoings.''
   Moon Il-kwan, one of the backers of the nation's largest
dissident alliance, was among those detained by police in Seoul.
   Protesters in Seoul also shouted anti-American slogans and
denounced the scheduled visit Monday of President Bush. Radicals
have called for protests Saturday and Monday to protest the Bush
trip.
   Police said a security alert was in effect from noon today until
midnight Monday to block any protests against Bush. Riot police
squads were posted at intersections, government buildings and some
embassies today in Seoul.
   Radical students staged anti-government protests today at three
Seoul colleges to denounce the government and the United States.
   In minor clashes, protesters at Sungshil and Sejong universities
hurled firebombs and rocks at riot police.
   At Seoul National University, about 100 students held a peaceful
anti-U.S. rally to demand Bush cancel his stop in Seoul and burned a
paper effigy that students said represented the U.S. and South
Korean governments.
   Radical students and dissidents have said weekend protestes will
also be aimed at the government of South Korean President Roh
Tae-woo, which celebrates its first anniversary Saturday.
   Radicals claim the Roh government is a military dictatorship
propped up by the United States and demand the 42,000 U.S. troops in
the country under a mutual defense treaty be removed.
   The radicals have little popular support, but authorities have
expressed concern about their threat to hold violent protests.
</TEXT>
