<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia     02-24 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fighting In Cambodia Escalates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting between guerrillas and
Vietnamese forces in Cambodia is escalating as the two sides try to
bolster their positions prior to a political settlement, a Thai
military spokesman said today.
   The two sides have ``renewed battles to extend areas of
influence, particularly in anticipation of Vietnam's troop
withdrawal from Cambodia and cessation of all aid to warring
parties,'' said the spokesman, Lt. Gen. Naruedol Dejpradiyuth.
   ``The combatants are competing for territory, seeking ways to
maximize their advantage before a political settlement is reached,''
he said at a monthly news conference.
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in late 1978 and ended nearly four years
of rule by the brutal Khmer Rouge during which an estimated 2
million of Cambodia's 8 million people died from Khmer Rouge
executions, famine and civil unrest.
   Vietnamese forces and troops of the Vietnamese-installed
government are now opposed by the Khmer Rouge and two other less
powerful guerrilla groups, all three of which receive sanctuary in
Thailand.
   Naruedol said the fighting escalated during the peace talks that
ended Tuesday in Jakarta, Indonesia.
   The talks ended without any new agreements, but the issue goes to
other forums in the coming months and all sides say the momentum is
toward a negotiated settlement. Naruedol noted the summit in May
between the Soviet Union, which arms Vietnam, and China, which arms
the guerrillas.
   The Vietnamese have pledged to withdraw from Cambodia next year.
   Renewed clashes during the Jakarta talks have been reported
between the Vietnamese and the Khmer Rouge in the Phnom Malai area
on the central sector of the Thai-Cambodian border.
   Further south, the Vietnamese have fired 302 artillery rounds of
artillery into the Borai area the past month, said Capt. Patana
Jiranant of the Thai military.
</TEXT>
