<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in moderate European trading early
today, its gradual slide this week halted by signs of rising U.S.
interest rates. Gold and silver prices fell in Europe.
   Dealers said trading was subdued by the closure of financial
markets in Tokyo for the funeral of Emperor Hirohito. They said the
dollar made ground when the U.S. Federal Reserve Board sent
short-term interest rates higher and two U.S. banks raised their
prime interest rates Thursday.
   Selected dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8288 West German marks, up from 1.8215
   _1.5585 Swiss francs, up from 1.5535
   _6.2330 French francs, up from 6.2125
   _2.0610 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0590
   _1,347.00 Italian lire, up from 1,344.50
   _1.1977 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1958
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7575 from $1.7595 late
Thursday.
   The dollar was quoted in London at 126.60 Japanese yen, up from
126.29 yen in Tokyo at Thursday's close.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $389.75 a troy ounce,
down from $391.50 bid late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $389.25.
