<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0707EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-U.N.     02-24 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-U.N.,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Soldier Killed By Israeli-Backed Militiamen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish soldier with the United Nations
peacekeeping force in south Lebanon was killed today by ``unprovoked
fire'' from Israeli-allied militiamen, a U.N. spokesman said.
   Timur Goksel, spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in south
Lebanon, UNIFIL, said the peacekeeper was shot in the chest by
machine gun fire from a South Lebanon Army position overlooking an
Irish post in the southern village of Hadatta.
   The predominantly Christian SLA, trained and financed by Israel,
assists the 1,000 Israeli troops in patrolling Israel's
self-designated ``security zone'' in south Lebanon.
   Israel established the 8-to-10 mile security zone along the
border in 1985 after withdrawing most of its troops from Lebanon.
   ``Death was instantanous,'' said Goksel. ``The fire was not
provoked.''
   Tension escalated recently between the two groups, with two
Scandanavian soldiers wounded earlier this month.
   The 5,800-strong UNIFIL, comprising contingents from nine
nations, has been deployed in south Lebanon under a peacekeeping
mandate from the United Nations since 1978.
   A total of 160 peacekeepers have been killed in south Lebanon the
past 11 years.
   Today's killing brought the overall death toll of the 700-strong
Irish batallion in Lebanon to 27.
</TEXT>
