<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-UtilityBankruptcy     02-24 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Utility Bankruptcy,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Owner Of Seabrook Doubts Plant Will Operate For Two Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Seabrook nuclear power plant won't
operate commercially for another two years, if at all, one owner
told the lead owner's bankruptcy judge.
   ``I think it is more likely than not that Seabrook will run. But
it is still a very uncertain situation. It changes on a daily
basis,'' said Robert Busch, a Northeast Utilities senior vice
president.
   Testifying at a Public Service Co. of New Hampshire bankruptcy
hearing Thursday, Busch said Northeast's proposed acquisition of
Public Service _ which would spin off that utility's Seabrook
investment into a separate company _ assumes Seabrook will operate
by mid-1991.
   Other Northeast and Seabrook officials stressed that the
company's estimate of May 1991 is for financial-planning purposes
and may be conservative.
   It is 16 months later than the estimate used by Public Service.
   The $5.8 billion plant, finished in 1986, remains idle for lack
of a federal operating license.
   Rob Williams, spokesman for New Hampshire Yankee, Public
Service's Seabrook management division, played down the Northeast
projection. He said financial-planning estimates, used in dealings
with utility regulators and lenders, are by their nature ``very
conservative.''
   ``It appears to us that the licensing process will be completed
by the end of the year,'' Williams said.
   Commercial operation should follow soon afterward, he added.
   Public Service spokesman Nicholas Ashooh said he was concerned
that differences in owners' financial-planning estimates on Seabrook
may be perceived as meaning that ``Seabrook has slipped again.''
   ``That is really not accurate,'' Ashooh said.
   ``Some (owners) are more conservative than others,'' Ashooh said.
   Meantime, Public Service said it will make a new offer to state
officials next month on electricity rate increases it seeks to
emerge from bankruptcy protection.
   Public Service's chief financial officer, Charles Bayless, made
the disclosure Thursday as he tried to show a federal bankruptcy
judge that there still are prospects for a reorganization settlement
that would avert lengthy, expensive litigation.
   The state, the utility and its creditors have been locked in
dispute over a key issue in the reorganization _ what rates Public
Service will be able to charge for its 36 percent share of the
completed but stalled Seabrook plant.
   The company also announced it had settled a securities-fraud
lawsuit brought by holders of company stock warrants and bonds that
helped pay for completing the Seabrook nuclear power plant.
   Northeast, New England's largest power company, wants to buy
Public Service's non-Seabrook assets, and has made a bid that it
says is worth about $2 billion if Seabrook operates.
   Northeast is stressing its experience with nuclear plants, having
built the three-reactor Millstone project in Connecticut. Busch was
project manager for Millstone 3, which he said began commercial
operation about two weeks ahead of schedule in April 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
