<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0729EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Hirohito-Ceremony     02-24 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hirohito-Ceremony,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ancient Ritual and Modern State Ceremony Mingled at Funeral</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hirohito Funeral, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONIKA JAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although careful to separate religion and the modern
democratic state, organizers of today's grand funeral for Emperor
Hirohito drew deeply from Japan's Shinto rites and ancient
traditions.
   Court music was played, classical poetry read and costumes of
another era worn although government officials said the funeral
ceremony was pared down in length and pomp to ``conform to the
times.''
   The funeral lasted more than 13 hours; the 1927 funeral of
Hirohito's father, Emperor Taisho, took a day and a half and
mourners dared not even look at the hearse bearing Taisho's body.
   Japanese today snapped photographs of the funeral procession, and
Hirohito's son Emperor Akihito carried his own umbrella.
   He delivered a eulogy in common speech, rather than the elaborate
courtly language used for such events in the past.
   But the main funeral ceremony at the Shinjuku Imperial Gardens,
led by the new emperor, was still steeped in the rituals of Shinto,
the indigenous religion which predates yet still co-exists with
Buddhism.
   Sensitive to Japan's postwar constitution, which insists on
separation of religion and state and relegates the emperor to a
figurehead role, the funeral organizers stressed such a duality in
the ceremonies.
   An actual curtain of black color was drawn after the completion
of the Shinto ceremony at the gardens and reopened before the start
of the state funeral. The curtain separated some 9,800 invited
mourners and the imperial family from the hall where Hirohito's body
lay.
   The sound of flutes and ancient court music heralded the start of
the elaborate procession led by Akihito into the funeral grounds.
Empress Michiko, in a flowing black dress and matching veil,
followed a few steps behind.
   Dignitaries, representing 163 nations, were bundled up in dark,
woolen blankets at their seats in a large tent.
   Once Hirohito's coffin was in place in the funeral hall,
specially constructed of Japanese cypress, ritualists made
offerings, including silk and food, to Hirohito, marking the start
of the Shinto ceremonies.
   Dressed in mourning black with a top hat and gloves clutched in
his left hand, a solemn Akihito entered the hall through the
traditional Shinto `torii' gate and bowed deeply. Stepping up to the
altar, he read from a speech handed to him by a chamberlain and bid
a final farewell to his father.
   After he left, Empress Michiko entered the hall, where she
offered a sacred `sakaki' branch to the late emperor.
   Ancient myths hold that gods dwell in the sakaki, or evergreen
trees, which are often used in Shinto rituals as offerings to
deities.
   Chamberlains later removed the offerings from the hall and the
black curtain was drawn to signal the end of the 47-minute Shinto
ceremony.
   By the start of the state funeral a short while later, the
`torii' gate and small tables at the altar had been removed. A
speech by chief Cabinet Secretary Keizo Obuchi signaled the
beginning.
   Imperial family members again walked up to the funeral hall and
bowed. Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and other government
representatives offered short eulogies.
   The one-hour state funeral concluded with the visiting foreign
dignitaries stepping up to the hall and bowing to the late emperor
and his family.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0737EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Funeral-Protests 1stLd-Writethru   02-24 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Funeral-Protests, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0512,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>To Protesters, The Pomp Is A Reminder Of A System They Reject</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hirohito Funeral, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To ADD background on imperial system's links to militarism and
repression, INSERTS two grafs after 4th graf, `Under the ... his name.'
Picks up 5th pvs, `Civil servants.'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many Japanese bid an affectionate farewell today to
the emperor who led them through a devastating war and into great
prosperity. But for others, the funeral was an occasion to denounce
the system he represented.
   ``Hirohito is the greatest of war criminals during World War II
with Hitler and Mussolini,'' said a 36-year-old high school teacher
among about 400 demonstrators who gathered at one Tokyo park.
   Protesters from three leftist groups displayed banners denouncing
the $74 million funeral and attacking Hirohito for his role as
titular leader during Japan's World War II aggression.
   ``Under the name of Hirohito, our mothers and fathers were
mobilized for war in Asia and thousands of people were massacred,''
said the teacher, who refused to give his name.
   Opponents of the imperial system associate it with militarism and
remind their countrymen that the emperor's name was used to rally
support for Japan's invasion of much of Asia during World War II.
   Until the end of the war, the emperor also stood at the head of
the state Shinto religion, which was used to justify strong central
control by the government and the suppression of human and religious
rights.
   Civil servants at a municipal office in Japan's southwestern
prefecture of Okinawa voted to come to work today despite the
government's designation of the day as a special national holiday in
Hirohito's honor.
   Resentment against Hirohito remains strong on the island, where
about 210,000 Japanese civilians and soldiers died in the fiercest
fighting on apanese territory of World War II.
   About 210,000 people lined the route taken by a funeral motorcade.
   Most appeared curious, braving a cold drizzle to crane their
necks at the cortege, eagerly snapping pictures as the slow-moving
hearse and its imperial motorcycle escort came into view. A few shed
tears.
   But at 11 other locations in Tokyo, about 4,300 people took part
in anti-emperor demonstrations, police said, including about 800 who
shouted slogans through loudspeakers as they marched 2{ miles.
   Authorities arrested five people, including two who broke through
police lines and ran into a street along the funeral route.
   National police said they had no figures on demonstrations
elsewhere in Japan. But in Hiroshima, about 30 people staged a
sit-in in front of the Atomic Dome, the remnants of a domed building
gutted by an atomic bomb in August 1945.
   Shortly after the United States dropped the bomb, Hirohito
announced Japan's surrender.
   For some mourners in Tokyo it proved an emotional sendoff as they
lined up many rows deep and bowed their heads as Hirohito's coffin
passed by.
   Eitaro Ohya, 77, recalled watching the 1927 funeral procession
for Emperor Taisho, Hirohito's father.
   ``I remember keeping my head bowed so low because the emperor was
considered a god that I saw nothing,'' Ohya recalled. ``But this
time I watched. It is a great honor to witness two emperors'
funerals.''
   Others were bitter. Kazumasa Miyamoto, 70, said, ``I was forced
to do construction work in China in the name of Emperor Hirohito and
had a hard time. We should not spend money for such a funeral.''
   The holiday kept department stores, restaurants, movie theaters
and other places of entertainment shut down. Large sections of the
city were blocked off to traffic and most residents stayed home or
headed out of Tokyo.
   Across the capital only a few small stores and restaurants
remained open.
   In the Nakano district, where Marxists staged a protest, many of
the demonstrators had lunch at the only eatery open: a Kentucky
Fried Chicken outlet where the staff wore black mourning ribbons.
</TEXT>
