<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0818EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Cocaine-Jewelry     02-24 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine-Jewelry,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocaine Money-Laundering Network Too Big To Eliminate, Prosecutor
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors played videotapes of jewelers
counting money stacked to the ceiling as they argued against bail
for gem store employees arrested in a $1 billion cocaine
money-laundering network.
   Three of the defendants were ordered held without bail Thursday.
But U.S. Magistrate Ralph J. Geffen allowed $1.25 million bail for
Rita Sorfazian as well as $50,000 bail each for two gem store clerks.
   In arguing against bail for Mrs. Sorfazian, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Russell Hayman said the government ``does not have the
resources'' to wipe out the sophisticated money-laundering network
attacked Wednesday with arrests of dozens of people at the downtown
jewelry district and other locations worldwide.
   ``If we let her out, are we letting her out to work for one of
the jewelers we know are still doing this?'' he asked.
   Ms. Sorfazian has yet to post bail.
   Thirty-seven people were charged Wednesday with taking in at
least $1 billion through merchants in Los Angeles, Texas, Florida
and New York, then sending the laundered cash to Colombian drug
lords.
   The defendants also were charged with aiding and abetting the
distribution of 640 pounds of cocaine seized during the
investigation.
   Hayman alleged the network may have been involved with importing
as much as 44,000 pounds of the drug.
   U.S. Magistrate John R. Kronenberg agreed to postpone a bail
hearing for two key figures in the case, Nazareth and Vahe Andonian,
until Monday. The men had asked for time to hire lawyers.
   The Andonian brothers and Wanis ``Joseph'' Koyomejian, 47, owner
of the Ropex Corp., have been identified by authorities as leaders
in the operation. Koyomejian and another alleged ring leader, Sergio
Hochman, were ordered held without bail.
   Hayman argued that Mrs. Sorfazian was responsible at Ropex for
making almost daily wire transfers of cash to New York, Panama and
elsewhere.
   Defense attorney Denise Meyer claimed her client was a secretary
at Ropex Corp. who took home $215 a week. Mrs. Sorfazian thought she
was working for a gold bullion exchange house that legitimately
converted cash to gold, Ms. Meyer said.
   The prosecutor showed a surveillance videotape in which Mrs.
Sorfazian and three other defendants were seen feeding money into
two high-speed counting machines. Hayman said that at times during
the government surveillance, the bills ``were literally stacked to
the ceiling.''
   Joyce and Zephur Moroyan, Lebanese-born sisters who worked as
clerks for the Andonians, were granted $50,000 bail each.
   Other defendants in the case were ordered held without bail:
Bedros Akpulat, 30, owner of Fancy Jewelry in downtown Los Angeles;
Dalida Avakian, who is Mrs. Sorfazian's sister; and Agop Koyomejian,
Wanis Koyomejian's brother.
</TEXT>
