<FIRST>r w PM-WJRAwards     02-24 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-WJR Awards,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC Dominates Journalism Magazine Broadcast Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC News staff members and programs won three
of the five ``Best in the Business'' broadcast awards given annually
by readers of the Washington Journalism Review.
   There were no similar multiple awards in the magazine's nine
print categories.
   The awards, announced this week, were based on responses by 800
readers who filled out ballots in the October issue. The magazine
claims a circulation of about 30,000.
   ABC's Sam Donaldson was honored as best network correspondent,
Peter Jennings was named best network TV anchor and ``This Week With
David Brinkley'' was chosen best national TV news
interview-discussion program.
   Charles Osgood of CBS News was named best radio reporter and the
MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour on the Public Broadcasting Service was
chosen best national TV news program.
   The ``Best in the Business'' print awards:
   _Newspaper or magazine political reporter, David Broder of the
Washington Post.
   _Humor columnist, Dave Barry, Miami Herald.
   _Editorial cartoonist, Jeff MacNelly, Chicago Tribune.
   _Magazine writer, Frank Deford, Sports Illustrated.
   _Newspaper for news, The New York Times.
   _Newspaper for features, The Washington Post.
   _Newspaper for business, The Wall Street Journal.
   _Newspaper for sports, USA Today.
   _Magazine for 1988 polical coverage, Newsweek.
   The readers also judged Allen H. Neuharth, chairman of Gannett
Co. Inc, the ``individual with the most impact on print news in the
past 10 years.'' Under Neuharth, Gannett began publishing the
national daily USA Today.
   Former President Reagan was judged the ``individual with the most
impact on television news in the past 10 years.''
</TEXT>
