<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0834EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Shevardnadze     02-24 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shevardnadze,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Discusses Stalemated Iran-Iraq Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
opened talks with his Iraqi counterpart today aimed at breaking a
deadlock in Persian Gulf peace talks and finding a solution to the
Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Shevardnadze arrived late Thursday for a two-day visit, saying he
was concerned about lack of progress in the Iraq-Iran peace
negotiations. He has also been using his 10-day regional tour to
promote Soviet proposals for peace between Israeli and Arab
neighbors.
   The Soviet official started his talks today with Iraqi Foreign
Minister Tariq Aziz. He also was to meet with President Saddam
Hussein.
   The Soviet minister leaves for Tehran on Saturday, where he has
been granted a rare audience with Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   East bloc diplomats say Shevardnadze is expected to press Iraqi
and Iranian leaders to work toward a peace treaty in the
negotiations being conducted under the auspices of the United
Nations. The Iran-Iraq war ended in a cease-fire in August, but the
two sides have made little progress in peace talks since then.
   Shevardnadze arrived in Baghdad from Cairo, where he said
Thursday that Israel must agree to talk with the Palestine
Liberation Organization and agree to take part in an international
peace conference under U.N. auspices if the Kremlin is to restore
diplomatic ties with the Jewish state.
   Israel opposes a U.N.-organized conference but has said it would
go to one under the auspices of the United States and the Soviet
Union. But the Israelis vow never to talk with the PLO, which they
consider a terrorist organization.
   Shevardnadze met separately with PLO chairman Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens in Cairo on Wednesday. Arafat
said the Soviets are providing him an indirect channel to the
Israelis through increased contacts set up this week in Cairo.
</TEXT>
