<DOCNO> AP890224-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0845EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GunBill     02-24 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gun Bill,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia Legislators Send Gun Bill to Governor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governor has promised to sign a bill
passed by the General Assembly that would make Virginia the first
state in the nation to require instant criminal checks on buyers of
some handguns and assault rifles.
   The bill, passed Thursday by the Senate and the House of
Delegates, requires criminal background checks of residents buying
handguns with barrels shorter than 5 inches or assault rifles with
ammunition clips of more than 20 rounds.
   State police told legislators a computerized search for records
of felony convictions could be made during the course of a phone
call.
   Out-of-state residents would have to submit to a more complicated
background check that could delay a purchase up to a week.
   Representatives of the NRA, the Virginia Rifle and Revolver
Association and Handgun Control Inc. all have said they could live
with the bill.
   ``The NRA is holding their noses and saying, `We don't oppose
it,''' said Del. William T. Wilson, who fought the measure. ``But I
assure you, they don't like it.''
   Wilson said the bill would inconvenience gun dealers and their
customers and would not accomplish its purpose of keeping guns away
from criminals.
   Gov. Gerald L. Baliles said the bill would change Virginia's
reputation as a major East Coast exporter of crime weapons.
</TEXT>
