<FIRST>u i PM-BushRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0533 02-24 1192</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush Rdp, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0533,1150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Pays Last Respects to Hirohito, Vows Fight for Tower Nomination</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS pvs 11th graf bgng, Apart from, to CORRECT spelling of
Seko in Zaire president's name.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bundled against the cold, President Bush bowed in
final respects to Emperor Hirohito at a rain-drenched funeral today
and later vowed to fight on his return to Washington to salvage the
troubled nomination of John Tower as secretary of defense.
   As Bush joined 9,800 mourners under tents at the Shinjuku
Imperial Garden ceremony, Tower's nomination was rejected in
Washington by the Senate Armed Services Committee. The vote was
11-9, split along party lines with the Democrats in the majority.
   The vote _ the first such committee rejection of a president's
Cabinet choice in 44 years _ was a major setback for Bush on his
first trip overseas as president, and came as he mingled with
leaders of more than 160 countries.
   ``I am going to strongly continue to back Sen. Tower, and I don't
believe he's going down the drain,'' Bush told reporters after the
funeral as he emerged from talks with foreign leaders at the U.S.
ambassador's residence.
   He said he had no intention of withdrawing Tower's name in favor
of a new, less controversial nominee. ``I haven't considered any
options,'' he said. ``I stand strongly with John Tower.''
   Added Bush: ``He knows that when I get back, and I will be back
before the (Senate) vote, he knows I will do whatever I can to talk
to individual members and have them know how strongly I feel about
it, and hopefully to persuade some who have looked at evidence so
far and may have a different opinion.''
   Despite the setback, Bush said he considers his honeymoon with
Congress is ``still going fine.'' But inasmuch as he wants Tower
confirmed, he said, ``I can't say it's a pat on the back.''
   Although he appeared tired from the rigors of his journey, Bush
said he felt like ``a spring colt ready to charge.''
   After paying a courtesy call on Hirohito's son, Emperor Akihito,
on Saturday morning, Bush flies to Beijing for two days of talks
with Chinese leaders. He will visit South Korea briefly on Monday en
route home to Washington.
   Earlier, leaving the three-hour funeral, Bush had shown no sign
of distress over the Senate committee's vote. He gave a thumbs-up
sign and smiled as his armored limousine _ flown in specially from
Washington _ brought him back to the American ambassador's residence
   Apart from the funeral, Bush held separate meetings with
Philippine President Corazon Aquino, King Baudouin of Belgium, Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan, West German President Richard
von Weizsaecker, Singapore Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew, Prime
Minister Turgut Ozal of Turkey, Italian President Francesco Cossiga
and President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire. Bush had a private dinner
with King Juan Carlos of Spain.
   Fitzwater said Bush assured Mrs. Aquino of U.S. support and noted
that the administration is seeking $200 million in aid for the
Philippines.
   Recognizing that Tower's nomination suddenly was in deep trouble,
White House chief of staff John Sununu was up most of the night on
long-distance telephone calls to Senate Republicans and others, said
White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   Fitzwater said Sununu called Tower by telephone this afternoon to
inform him of Bush's continued support. ``Sen. Tower said he knew it
would be a difficult fight but he's ready to move forward,''
Fitzwater said.
   For the first time, Fitzwater said it ``would probably be
helpful'' for the nomination to release the 140-page report on the
FBI investigation of Tower's personal life. However, he said, ``I'm
not at all sure that that can happen or that it should happen'' out
of concern for those who were interviewed.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, in a CBS television
interview, said Bush had not been hurt by the Tower vote. ``I don't
think it's a loss until it goes down the tubes on the floor,'' he
said, adding that he was not predicting that the nomination was lost.
   Separately, Baker said in an NBC-TV interview that ``it is not in
the best interest of the foreign policy of the United States to have
a nomination hang fire for this long.''
   Fitzwater said there was no consideration of any replacement for
Tower, ``period, bar none.''
   Bush had begun his day with calls to Washington with Senate
Minority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., and other senators about Tower's
nomination. But even before the committee voted, Bush had to put the
matter aside to attend Hirohito's funeral.
   For the occasion, Bush had rented a morning coat in Washington,
including grey stripe pants, black vest, black tie and black cutaway
jacket with tails.
   Accompanied by his wife, Barbara, Bush was given a front-row,
center seat in one of two huge open-sided tents at the state
funeral. To give him a place of prominence, Japanese officials had
to waive protocol rules that would have put Bush toward the back
because of his short tenure in office.
   One by one, world leaders approached Hirohito's coffin to pay
respects after the formal eulogies.
   When their turn came, Bush and his wife paused in front of the
coffin and lowered their heads in a slight bow. A pelting rain and
stiff wind made the chilly day in Tokyo seem even colder.
   Bush wore a black overcoat and turned up his collar against the
wind. Along with many other mourners, Bush and his wife covered
their laps with wool and cashmere blankets placed on each seat.
   There were electrical heating coils beneath the floor and a
heater in the low wall directly in front of the president.
   Hirohito, the last of the World War II-era world leaders, died of
cancer at age 87 on Jan. 7 after reigning for six decades.
   Bush issued a statement thanking Japanese officials ``who managed
this complicated logistics and put on a marvelous pageant in honor
of the late emperor _ beautifully staged and beautifully carried
off, on schedule, working against the elements, but nevertheless
with a dignity and a ceremony that was appropriate.''
   He said he had ``great respect for what they did and the way in
which they did it, and I am proud to have represented the United
States of America here today.''
   Bush, a Navy combat pilot in World War II who was shot down by
Japanese gunners during a bombing run, said attending the funeral
was the right thing to do because Japan and the United States are
allies.
   The gesture was appreciated by the Japanese, particularly because
of lingering resentment in some quarters about Hirohito's role as a
leader during the war. Some U.S. veterans were among those who
objected to Bush's decision.
   Bush was unaffected by the only significant security incident
involving the emperor's funeral. A bomb damaged a highway along
which the emperor's hearse was due to be taken after the ceremony,
but Bush was already back at his hotel at the time. Police
speculated that radicals opposed to the emperor system were
responsible for the blast.
</TEXT>
