<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hirohito-HongKong     02-24 0172</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hirohito-Hong Kong,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veterans Protest Funeral of Hirohito</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hirohito Funeral, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 World War II veterans, including
former prisoners of war, today rallied at a downtown war memorial
and denounced Emperor Hirohito of Japan on the day of his funeral.
   They also laid wreaths to commemorate their dead comrades in a
20-minute ceremony, which was held this morning to coincide with the
Tokyo funeral of Hirohito.
   Hong Kong, a British colony on the southern coast of China, was
occupied by the Japanese during World War II.
   The veterans, many wearing medals from the war, and some younger
people later marched around the stone monument with banners reading
``Hirohito was a war criminal'' and ``Down with Japanese
imperialism.''
   Some participants decried the attendance of world leaders such as
President Bush and Prince Philip of Great Britain at Hirohito's
funeral.
   Earlier today, more than a dozen youths chanting slogans opposing
what they view as Japanese militarism marched downtown and handed a
petition to the Japanese Consulate.
</TEXT>
