<FIRST>r a PM-PrisonBribe     02-24 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Bribe,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputy Prison Warden Charged With Bribery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state prison warden accepted $10,000 to arrange
the transfer of an inmate from a maximum-security prison to a
medium-security prison, authorities say.
   Deputy Warden Wayne Jackson of the State Prison of Southern
Michigan was freed on $10,000 bond after being arraigned Thursday on
two counts of bribery and two counts of conspiracy to bribe before
District Court Judge Robert Crary Jr.
   He also was suspended without pay, Corrections Department
spokesman Lou Chappell said.
   Jackson, who was second in command at the prison, was accused of
accepting $7,500 in cash and a lithograph valued at $2,500 to
arrange a transfer of Stephen McCreary from the maximum-security
prison to the medium-security Western Wayne Correctional Facility at
Plymouth, state and federal authorities said.
   McCreary escaped in mid-December after being transferred again to
a minimum-security work camp. McCreary had been sentenced to life in
prison for second-degree murder in a 1977 drug-related killing in
Detroit.
   Jackson 40, faces similar federal charges and will be arraigned
later in federal court, said Attorney General Frank Kelley.
   Jackson's lawyer, James Dudus, said Jackson had no statement.
   Jackson faces up to 10 years in prison and $20,000 in fines if
convicted on the state charges. He faces up to 10 years and $250,000
in fines if convicted of the federal charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
