<DOCNO> AP890224-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cuba-HumanRights     02-24 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba-Human Rights,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban Inmates Tell U.N. They Were Tortured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In its first report on human rights in Cuba, the
United Nations said today that Cuban prisoners complained they were
tortured but that the government denied their claims.
   The 400-page report was compiled by a six-member team that
visited Cuba for 10 days in September at the invitation of the
government.
   The U.N. Human Rights Commission, made up of representatives from
43 nations, will begin discussing the report Tuesday.
   The investigating team said it received more than 1,600 human
rights complaints, including 137 of torture, cruel, inhuman or
degrading treatment.
   The allegations of torture were in a letter signed by 22
political detainees and handed to two U.N. representatives who
visited Havana's Combinado del Este prison.
   ``The Cuban tormentors, advised by experts in political
repression, mainly Russians and Czechs, inflict all kinds of
torture,'' the letter said.
   The report said Cuba's interior minister, Gen. Jose Abrantes,
told the U.N. representatives that ``a number of detainees or
prisoners had in the past been beaten'' but that those responsible
had been punished.
   ``He said there are no cases of torture,'' according to the
report.
   Most of the complaints, 1,183 of them, came from Cubans who said
it was ``difficult to leave the country either temporarily or
permanently,'' according to the report.
   Cuba has said that under an agreement with the United States,
20,000 Cubans would be allowed to leave for the United States each
year.
   During the first nine months of last year only 5,932 had left,
and Vice President Carlos Rafael Rodriguez was cited in the report
as blaming U.S. ``non-compliance with the agreement.''
   A considerable part of the report was devoted to statistics
suggesting a vast improvement in education and health care under
President Fidel Castro. It also quoted prominent cultural figures as
praising the government's literacy campaign and promotion of
cultural life.
   The U.N. team was headed by Ambassador Alioune Sene of Senegal
and included diplomats from Bulgaria, Ireland, Colombia, Nigeria and
The Philippines.
   The United States has charged that Cuba and North Korea are the
world's worst human rights offenders, and says the United Nations
should send investigators to Cuba once a year as it does with other
countries, including Chile, South Africa and El Salvado.
   The Cuban government, however, has said it will not allow another
visit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
