<FIRST>u i PM-SatanicVerses 3rdLd-Writethru   02-24 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Satanic Verses, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0549,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>Friends Say Author Well Despite Death Threat, Thankful For Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Alienation, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Foreign Secretary reportedly asking
Soviets to state view to Khomeini, Finnish investigation into death threat.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite being forced underground by an Iranian
death order, the author of ``The Satanic Verses'' is not in bad
spirits and is grateful for the support he has received _ especially
from Moslems, his friends say.
   The death toll from protests related to Salman Rushdie's book
increased to 17 today when police opened fire on protesting Moslems
in Bombay, India, killing at least 10.
   Seven other people have died in demonstrations in Pakistan and
India.
   In Iran, Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani said Iran can't be
held responsible if a Moslem kills Rushdie, who was born into a
Moslem family. He also demanded that Western nations say whether
they agree with what ``The Satanic Verses'' says about Islam.
   Sources in Britain's Foreign Office said today Foreign Secretary
Geoffrey Howe sent a letter to his Soviet counterpart, Eduard
Shevardnadze, urging him to ``make clear that the Soviet Union
shares the ... wish to see Iran respect international obligations
and renounce the use of violence.''
   Shevardnadze, on a Middle East tour, has been granted a rare
audience with Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Rushdie has been in hiding since Feb. 14, when Khomeini told
Moslems to kill the British author. Some say his book insults Islam.
   Moslem clerics in Iran backed Khomeini's threat by offering up to
$5.2 million for the death of Rushdie.
   Indian news agencies reported anti-Rushdie protests in several
cities today.
   Police in Bombay said about 5,000 Moslems set fire to buses and
began attacking police officers. They said at least 10 people were
killed and 25 injured when police opened fire.
   The New York Times reported today that only Rushdie's sister,
literary agent and a few close friends know exactly where he is or
have spoken with him since he went underground.
   One friend, writer Tariq Ali, was quoted as telling the Times
that Rushdie ``is bearing up well, he is in relatively good spirits
and is very gratified at all the support that he has received.''
   He was quoted as saying Rushdie ``is also very aware that there
are many, many devout Muslims all over the world who do not agree
with Khomeini.''
   Ali was quoted as saying the novelist ``does not feel under great
strain or pressure ... but it is going to be very difficult for him
now. He will be constantly haunted by the specter of death.''
   Blake Morrison, literary editor of London's weekly newspaper The
Observer, said Thursday he had talked with Rushdie and the
41-year-old writer sounded ``all right.''
   In Canada, External Affairs Minister Joe Clark was put under
24-hour police guard, the Toronto Sun newspaper reported today. It
quoted aide Christian Sarrazin as saying the security was imposed as
a precaution after Canada withdrew its envoy from Tehran in protest
Tuesday.
   Another Canadian official, Revenue Minister Otto Jelinek, was
given police protection this week after receiving death threats for
refusing to ban imports of the novel.
   Police in Finland said today they had begun investigating a death
threat against Rushdie by Altaf Mohammed, vice-chairman of the
Finland-Pakistan Society.
   Mohammed told a leading newspaper, Uusi Suomi, on Thursday that
members of the society ``are prepared to kill Rushdie if he comes to
Finland.''
   In Norway, the governing Labor Party is considering whether to
expel Syed Bokhari, a Pakistani-born councilman in Skedsmo, for
saying in news interviews he would kill Rushdie if given the chance,
local party chairman Tor Erik Gulbrandsen said today.
   Detractors say the book insults Islam by portraying the prophet
Mohammed's wives as prostitutes and suggesting he wrote the Koran
rather than receiving it from God.
   Rafsanjani, speaking at weekly prayers in Tehran, told Western
nations: ``Moslems believe that you are a partner in its
publication...If not, say so.'' Moslems want to know how Western
governments stand on the book so they know their ``duty,'' he said,
without elaborating.
   The Danish newspaper Weekendavisen today published excerpts of
``The Satanic Verses.'' The newspaper also reported that Denmark
planned to go ahead with a $100 million business deal with Tehran.
   The editors said in a commentary they printed the excerpts to
satisfy ``the public's right to form an opinion about the case, and
to show solidarity with the author and the publishers.''
   It said the state-run oil and natural gas company DONG and MD
Foods are about to tie up a deal in which Denmark would broker a
million tons of Iranian oil. In exchange, Iran would use the
proceeds to buy Danish cheese and other products.
</TEXT>
