<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionLawsuit     02-24 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Lawsuit,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>ACLU Files Lawsuit Challenging Medicaid Abortion Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRETEL WIKLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit
challenging the state's new ban on Medicaid-funded abortions, saying
it punishes a 15-year-old girl who became pregnant after being
gang-raped.
   A hearing on the lawsuit, filed Thursday in Wayne County Circuit
Court, was scheduled today before Judge John Hausner.
   ``The law is imposing a double punishment on this person,'' said
Howard Simon, executive director of the Michigan chapter of the ACLU.
   The girl faces ``not only the punishment of being a victim of
rape itself, but being essentially consigned to the lifetime
consequences,'' Simon said.
   Hausner could issue a temporary restraining order and ultimately
a preliminary injunction clearing the way for a state-funded
abortion. The ACLU lawsuit, also filed on behalf of the girl's
mother, is the first to challenge the ban passed by voters last
November.
   According to the lawsuit, the girl, whose name is being withheld,
was raped last month by three men. The Wayne County prosecutor's
office said two men were in jail awaiting trial on second-degree
criminal sexual conduct charges in the case.
   The teen-ager, who is five weeks pregnant, wanted an abortion but
was unable to afford the procedure because her family is on welfare,
the lawsuit said.
   Elizabeth Gleicher and William H. Goodman, the lawyers
representing the girl, said the abortion ban should be overturned
because it denies poor women equal access to health care.
   Courts in Connecticut, Vermont, New Jersey and California have
overturned similar abortion bans, allowing poor women in those
states to again seek Medicaid-paid abortions, Gleicher said.
   Before Medicaid-funded abortions were banned in Michigan, the
state spent about $6 million a year for some 18,500 abortions for
poor women.
</TEXT>
