<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionDoctor 1stLd-Writethru a0511 02-24 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Doctor, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0511,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctor's License Temporarily Suspended</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Two women ...' to CORRECT Collins' hometown
to Anderson sted Madison; SUBS 5th graf, `Thakkar, 38...' to ADD doctor's
town of practice; SUBS 8th graf, `Ms. Hertziner ...' to CLARIFY when drugs
were administered. Note contents.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI D. SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A physician was ordered to surrender his
license and submit to a comprehensive psychiatric examination after
12 former female patients accused him of sexual and ethical
misconduct.
   In suspending Dr. Pravin D. Thakkar's medical license for 90
days, the Indiana Medical Licensing Board said Thursday that he
presented a ``clear and immediate danger to the public health and
safety'' and had engaged in ``immoral conduct.''
   Two women have filed lawsuits against Thakkar contending he got
them pregnant, then performed abortions without their knowledge.
Carmen Brutchen Hertzinger and Kathy Collins, both of Anderson, were
the first to testify at a three-hour hearing that led to the board's
action.
   Several women then came forward and said Thakkar asked to perform
pelvic exams on them despite their medical condition. One woman said
Thakkar wanted to perform a pelvic examination on her when she
sought help for a strep throat.
   Thakkar, 38, an obstetrician-gynecologist who has a family
practice in Frankton, did not attend the hearing.
   ``We know a lot of these allegations are lies and false. We'll
get a chance to present our evidence to the licensing board soon and
I'll be exonerated,'' Thakkar said in a telephone interview Thursday
night.
   The board pointed out that the 90-day suspension was the most
severe action that could be taken before a formal complaint is filed
and a final hearing is scheduled.
   Ms. Hertzinger claims she became pregnant with Thakkar's child in
February 1983 after they became romantically involved. Thakkar is
accused of administering drugs to Ms. Hertzinger eight months later,
causing her to deliver the fetus at his home. He told her the baby
was stillborn and he had taken care of it, Ms. Hertzinger said.
   However, Ms. Hertzinger claims that she was conscious during part
of the procedure and heard a baby's cry.
   Asked later if she regretted not coming forward with her
disclosures earlier, Ms. Hertzinger said, ``It took all the numbers
that we had here today to convince them of the severity and the
danger that Doctor Thakkar was causing.''
   Ms. Collins claims Thakkar fathered her unborn child and then
aborted the fetus with a medical instrument Jan. 9, 1988.
   After reviewing Thakkar's educational training and background,
board member Dr. Deanna Porte-Keene expressed concern over the
doctor's qualifications to practice as an obstetrician.
   ``I'd be interested to know how this doctor even advertises
himself as an obstetrician,'' she said. ``I'm certainly raising a
lot of questions as to what his qualifications are as a physician,
let alone his personal conduct, which is appalling.''
   Ms. Hertzinger and Ms. Collins have taped a segment of the
television talk show ``Geraldo'' that is scheduled to air March 7.
   A third woman, Susan Bickel, 34, a former employee of Thakkar's,
said she went to him for an examination in August 1982 when she
suspected she had become pregnant by her husband.
   She said Thakkar examined her with medical instruments and told
her she wasn't pregnant. She said she experienced pain during the
exam and later began bleeding.
   Mrs. Bickel said she went to another doctor who examined her and
told her she had undergone an abortion.
   Mrs. Bickel said Thakkar eventually told her ``that he thought if
I'd had a child by anyone else, I wouldn't want him.''
   Telling similar stories, almost all of the women testified that
Thakkar told them they were beautiful, asked questions about their
sex lives and asked them for dates while under his care.
   Dr. John Hinton called the allegations ``probably the worst abuse
of physician-patient trust that I've seen since I've been on the
board.''
</TEXT>
