<FIRST>u i PM-Yugoslavia     02-24 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schools, Shops Close In Support Of Striking Miners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people held a rally in
southern Kosovo province today to support miners who are striking to
protest ethnic discrimination and to demand the resignation of a
Communist Party chief.
   Yugoslav leaders rushed to Pristina, the provincial capital, to
prevent possible ethnic clashes between the Albanian majority and
Slav minority.
   More than 1,300 ethnic Albanian miners, some on a hunger strike,
have refused to leave their pits at the Trepca lead and zinc mines
since Monday.
   Tens of thousands of people have joined sympathy rallies and
strikes across the province of Serbia, one of six Yugoslav
republics. Most private shops and some schools in Kosovo closed
today.
   About 3,000 university students and their professors today spent
a second night in a Pristina sports hall to show solidarity.
   Yugoslav Communist Party leader Stipe Suvar and the Serbian
republic's party boss, Slobodan Milosevic, arrived in Pristina and
met with Kosovo Communist Party chief Rahman Morina, whose
resignation the strikers demand.
   The miners consider Morina an ally of Milosevic, who is trying to
gain greater Serbian control over Kosovo.
   The mainly Moslem Albanians make up more than 85 percent of the
province's population, and they claim his move would result in
discrimination against them by Serbs, who are predominantly
Christian.
   Since the mine action began, 150 strikers have asked for medical
help and 16 have been hospitalized, the Tanjug news agency said.
   A provincial spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, today
denied reports published Thursday that 17 people had already been
hospitalized. He said a medical facility had been set up at the site.
   In Belgrade Thursday, the Serbian Parliament approved proposed
changes in the republic's constitution that would give Serbia
sovereignty over its provinces, Kosovo and Vojvodina, and increase
the republic's powers over defense and state security, Tanjug
reported.
   However, the ammendments must also be approved by the assemblies
of Kosovo and Vojvodina before they can be enforced.
   On Thursday, Yugoslav Raif Dizdarevic was quoted by Tanjug as
saying that constitutional changes would not ``endanger'' any
nationality in Yugoslavia.
   Dizdarevic met Thursday evening with representatives of the
striking miners and appealed to them to leave the pits and begin
talks with authorities over their demands.
</TEXT>
