<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0452 02-24 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0452,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Leader Calls For Recognition Of Interim Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with guerrilla leader calling for recognition
of interim government, Iranian-based rebels reject government. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan guerrilla leader today
called on other countries to recognize the interim government the
insurgents formed for Afghanistan and predicted the Soviet-backed
rulers in Kabul will be overthrown.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, who was recently elected president of the
interim government, also offered an amnesty for Afghanistan's
communist government troops if they switch sides in the 10-year-old
civil war.
   Fellow guerrilla fighters based in Iran today reportedly rejected
the interim government the insurgents hope will take over if
President Najib's communist government falls in Kabul.
   At a news conference ending a stormy three-week meeting of
Pakistan-based guerrillas, Mojaddidi said the guerrilla government
would become functional inside Afghanistan within a month, ``God
willing.''
   He asked foreign countries to recognize the proposed government
and for the United Nations to give it a General Assembly seat.
   The religious and political strains among the guerrillas were
evident when their council elected Mojaddidi, considered a moderate
among the Moslem guerrillas, as president and and Rasul Sayyaf, a
fundamentalist from the Ittehad-e-Islami guerrilla group, as
premier. Fundamentalist factions advocate a strict Moslem system,
and moderates have favored a broad-based government in Afghanistan
embracing Islam as its official religion.
   Afghan Shiite guerrillas, most of whom are in Iran, boycotted the
440-delegate council after the Pakistan-based guerrillas, the
majority of whom are Sunni Moslem, refused to give them the
representation they sought.
   Tehran radio reported today that leaders of the smaller
Iran-based resistance rejected the appointment of the interim
government, saying they were denied representation to the council.
   The radio quoted Mohammad Karim Khalili, spokesman for the
Iran-based alliance, as saying: ``We consider the formation of the
interim government as one sided, and cannot recognize it.'' The
report was monitored in Cyprus.
   The Shiites, Afghanistan's largest minority, represent only 17
percent of Afghanistan's population of 15 million but make up 40
percent of the 5 million refugees who have fled to Pakistan and Iran.
   Moslem guerrillas have fought the government in Kabul since the
communists seized power in a violent 1978 coup. Soviet forces
intervened in December 1979.
   Moscow withdrew its troops by Feb. 15 under a U.N.-mediated
accord.
   Guerrilla and Western observers have predicted Kabul will fall
within months in the absence of Soviet forces, but Najib says his
army is strong enough to withstand a guerrilla assault.
   A Western diplomatic source, speaking in Islamabad on condition
he not be further identified, said: ``I think it's too early to talk
about recognition. Their first test will be to get a capital.''
   He said the first movement toward the world's acceptance of the
guerrilla government might be a ``de-recognition of Kabul.''
   Communist forces, heavily armed by the departing Red Army, hold
the capital and Afghanistan's key cities but insurgents, backed
mainly by Pakistan and the United States, reportedly control about
90 percent of the countryside.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
