<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Police     02-24 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Police,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Police Official Under U.S. Indictment Resigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Mexico City police official under
indictment in the United States in connection with a car theft ring
has resigned, a police spokeswoman said today.
   Miguel Nazar Haro resigned late Thursday, said spokeswoman
Carmela Gutierrez. She did not give a reason for Nazar Haro's
resignation and said she didn't know if it had been accepted.
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari appointed Nazar Haro head of
Mexico City's police intelligence unit shortly after he took office
in December.
   Nazar Haro, 60, spent 20 years with Mexico's now-defunct
Directorate of Federal Security, the equivalent of the FBI. He
resigned on Jan. 13, 1982, when he was indicted in San Diego in
connection with the $8.4 million international car theft ring.
   The ring was smashed in 1981 by the FBI and California police.
   FBI agents arrested Nazar Haro in 1982 after he gave testimomy to
a federal grand jury investigating the case. He was released after
posting $200,000 cash on $1 million bail, and he fled to Mexico.
   In 1983, a U.S. district court judge threw out an $11 million
libel suit filed by Nazar Haro against Time magazine. A story in the
magazine alleged the U.S. government protected Nazar Haro from
prosecution as a car smuggler, saying he had been the CIA's most
important intelligence source in Mexico.
   Nazar Haro has said he cooperated with U.S. officials in criminal
matters but denied being a paid informant for the CIA.
   Mexican human rights activists, including Rosario Ibarra de
Piedra, leader of the Revolutionary Workers' Party, have alleged
Nazar Haro was responsible for disappearances and the torture of a
number of detainees when he served as the head of the Directorate of
Federal Security.
   Nazar Haro has denied the charges.
</TEXT>
