<FIRST>r w PM-Governors-Women     02-24 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Governors-Women,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women Named to State-Level Cabinet Positions Increased More Than
15 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of women appointed to state-level
cabinet positions by governors has increased more than 15 percent in
two years, the National Women's Political Caucus said today.
   The group released its study of governors' appointments and said
that since 1981, the number of women appointed to such posts has
increased 114 percent.
   ``Our new study confirms that the message of women's abilities
and political savvy is being heard by goverors of both parties and
in all regions of the country,'' said Irene Natividad, head of the
bipartisan women's political organization.
   The survey rated the 50 governors based on the percentage of
women appointed to their cabinets. Ranked first was Virginia's
Democratic Gov. Gerald Baliles, whose 7 cabinet posts include three
women, or 43 percent.
   Ranked last was Missouri's Republican Gov. John H. Ashcroft, who
has no women in his cabinet.
   Natividad said Ashcroft ``is out of synch'' with the rest of the
states and has not recognized the political and leadership talents
of women.
   The group said 150 women hold the state jobs in 1989, up from 70
in 1981 and 130 in 1987.
   She said there appeared to be no difference between Republican
and Democratic governors in appointing women. Four of the top 10
governors in the group's rankings were Republicans.
   After Baliles, the governors with the most appointed women in
cabinet jobs were: Maryland Gov. William D. Schaefer, Arkansas Gov.
Bill Clinton, Wisconsin Gov. Tommy G. Thompson, Vermont Gov.
Madeleine Kunin, Illinois Gov. James R. Thompson, New Jersey Gov.
Thomas H. Kean, Oklahoma Gov. Henry Bellmon, Louisiana Gov. Buddy
Roemer, and Ohio Gov. Richard F. Celeste. Tommy Thompson, James
Thompson, Kean and Bellmon are Republicans.
</TEXT>
