<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-UN 1stLd-Writethru   02-24 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-UN, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0519,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Soldier Killed By Israeli-Backed Militiamen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with name of dead soldier and comment
from commander of U.N. forces. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish soldier with the United Nations
peacekeeping force in southern Lebanon was killed today by
unprovoked gunfire from Israeli-allied militiamen, a U.N. spokesman
said.
   Timur Goksel, spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in southern
Lebanon, said Pvt. Michael McNeela, 21, of Dundalk, was shot in the
chest by machine gun fire from a South Lebanon Army position
overlooking an Irish post in the village of Hadatta.
   ``Death was instantaneous,'' said Goksel. ``The fire was not
provoked.''
   Lars-Eric Wahlgren, commander of the U.N. force, visited the
village later in the day and told reporters: ``I condemn the
senseless killing of one of my soldiers.''
   Most members of the South Lebanon Army are Christians. Israel
trains and finances the militia, which helps 1,000 Israeli troops
patrol the Jewish state's self-designated ``security zone'' in
southern Lebanon.
   Israel established the eight-to-10 mile zone in 1985 after
withdrawing most of its troops from Lebanon.
   Tension increased recently between the militia and the U.N.
force, and two Scandanavian soldiers were wounded earlier this month.
   The 5,800-member U.N. force, made up of contingents from nine
nations, was deployed in southern Lebanon in 1978 under a U.N.
peacekeeping mandate. Since then, 160 peacekeepers have been killed.
   Today's killing brought to 27 the number of Irish soldiers
killed. That nation's batallion has 700 troops.
</TEXT>
