<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BadBirth     02-24 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bad Birth,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debate Storms Over Treatment Of 11-Year-Old Pregnant Girl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 11-year-old pregnant girl was
transferred from one hospital to another with her legs taped
together to delay delivery, but both her premature twins died,
authorities said.
   The Florida Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services has
investigated the case and found that no laws were broken.
   But despite the finding, Duncan Moore, president and chief
executive officer at Tallahassee Memorial Regional Medical Center,
said Thursday that he believed the treatment of the girl violated
state and federal laws.
   Officials at Tallahassee Community Hospital said doctors at their
hospital taped the girl's legs to protect her because she was not
willing or able to keep her legs together, as complications of her
pregnancy required.
   They then put her in an ambulance and sent her to Memorial, which
has more advanced facilities for neo-natal care.
   One of the girl's babies was born dead at 6 ounces and the other
died soon after birth at 9 ounces. The girl had been 21 to 24 weeks
pregnant.
   Community's administrator, Nick Carbone, accused Memorial
hospital officials of pulling ``a stunt'' to try to discredit his
hospital.
   ``This was absolutely the best medical thing you could do,'' said
Rheb Harbison, spokesman for Community Hospital. ``They're trying to
sensationalize this case.''
   But Community officials acknowledged that the girl should not
have been sent alone in the ambulance on Jan. 9 from their hospital
to Memorial, and said that a nurse will accompany any patients
transferred in the future.
   The two hospitals also disagreed on whether the girl was in
active labor when Community sent her to Memorial. Doctors at the
state Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services, a
physicians' peer-review organization, and officials at the federal
Health Care Financing Administration all found she was not, Harbison
said.
   ``But even if she had been, we still could have transferred her
if the benefits outweighed the risks,'' he said.
   Moore, however, said it was obvious that the girl had been in
labor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
