<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--UNICEFCards     02-24 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--UNICEF Cards,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNICEF Cards Post Record Sales in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UNICEF sold a record 135 million of its greeting
cards last year, earning the agency about $40 million to help the
world's children, the United Nations said Friday.
   West Germany accounted for the most sales in 1988, 15 million,
followed by the United States with 14 million and France with 12
million, a U.N. news release said.
   UNICEF, the U.N. Children's Fund, said it has sold more than 2.5
billion cards since the agency was founded in 1949, mostly through
volunteers.
   Artists such as Joan Miro, Pablo Picasso, Salvador Dali, Marc
Chagall and Paul Klee have allowed their works to be printed on
UNICEF cards without asking copyright fees.
   The $40 million profit is about twice the amount it spends in
Bangladesh in two years, UNICEF said.
</TEXT>
