<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--SpaceStrike     02-24 0127</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Space Strike,0130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike at European Space Center Threatens Rocket Launching</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by workers at the European Space Center
launch site in French Guiana has threatened the blastoff of a rocket
carrying Europe's first meteorological satellite into orbit.
   The Ariane 4 rocket, scheduled for launch Tuesday night, also
will carry Japan's first commercial telecommunications satellite.
   Officials of the European consortium Arianespace will meet
Saturday in Kourou, French Guiana to determine if the launch should
be postponed, said Arianespace spokesman Claude Sanchez.
   On Wednesday, 230 workers at the space station on the northern
coast of South America went on strike demanding higher wages.
   About 70 of them are technicians manning radar controls,
operating computers or performing other tasks necessary for takeoff,
Sanchez said.
</TEXT>
