<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Siegal     02-24 0128</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Siegal,0133</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra Concertmaster Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fritz Siegal, retired concertmaster of the
Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra, has died of liver cancer at age 71.
   Siegal's ``music making and his legacy will long be remembered by
those who benefited from his presence in our city,'' said Lorin
Maazel, symphony director.
   Siegal died Wednesday in Chicago at the home of his daughter,
Karen Toppel.
   Until he became ill in July, Siegal had been living in Raleigh,
N.C., where he was concertmaster of the North Carolina Symphony
Orchestra.
   As concertmaster for 20 years beginning in 1967, he led the
Pittsburgh symphony's first violin section and often served as
assistant to the conductor.
   The native of Vienna also served with orchestras in Chicago,
Seattle, Baltimore and Indianapolis.
</TEXT>
