<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Notebook 1stLd-Writethru a0619 02-24 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Notebook, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tower Overtowers the American Contingent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT reference to Senate Armed Services
Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it suits his purposes, George Bush can be as
talkative as the next guy. The president simply turns a photo ``op''
into a press ``availability.''
   Reporters crowded around the president Friday evening, looking
for his reaction to the 11-9 Senate Armed Services Committee vote to
reject John Tower as secretary of defense.
   Bush acted undecided about whether he would answer their
questions.
   ``I've got to get a ruling on whether this is a _ this is not a
photo op,'' the president started out.
   He has declared that he won't entertain reporters' questions
during photo-taking sessions, dubbed ``photo ops'' by White House
aides.
   Then, standing in the evening dark by his limousine, its engine
running, aides Marlin Fitzwater and John Sununu at his side, Bush
decided he could indeed field a few questions.
   ``This is what we call a press availability,'' he declared.
   The president's availability lasted 10 minutes, dealing almost
exclusively with Tower's fate.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   ``I don't believe he is going down the drain,'' the president
declared.
   But it was the tubes, not the drain, that Secretary of State
James A. Baker III said Tower might or might not go down.
   ``I don't think it's a loss until it goes down the tubes on the
(Senate) floor,'' Baker told a television interviewer.
   He said he was in no position to predict the outcome: ``I'm over
here doing other things than politics ...''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Tower was Topic A among the American contingent visiting Japan
for the funeral of Emperor Hirohito.
   Bush and Senate Minority Leader Robert Dole, R-Kan., talked about
the Tower nomination by telephone, the president assuring the
senator that he was ready to fight for his choice. And Chief of
Staff John Sununu was on the line to Tower after the vote, assuring
him Bush was still behind him, according to presidential spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   If John Tower was Topic A, George Bush's stamina was Topic B.
   Bush has put himself through a punishing regimen during his
three-day visit to Japan.
   Before his departure for China, and another round of meetings
there, he arranged to see 19 presidents, kings and prime ministers
and one emperor, Akhito, son of Hirohito and 125th emperor in an
unbroken line of rule.
   Bush sat through a long funeral in bone-chilling weather, had
lunch with the president of France and dinner with the king of
Spain. And, of course, he had to keep up with the Tower matter.
   But was he tired?
   No, he insisted.
   ``I thought I'd be more tired,'' said the president in that
curbside Q-and-A session. ``I feel like a spring colt, ready to
charge.''
   And, while Bush posed for photographs before a quick meeting with
President Mobuto Sese Seko of Zaire, a reporter called out, ``You
look tired, Mr. President.''
   Bush turned to Mobuto: ``They say you look tired, Mr. President.''
   Mobuto looked startled, not tired.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
