<FIRST>r a AM-People-Bond     02-24 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Bond,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Julian Bond: Rights Movement Needs Individuals, Not Charismatic Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Civil rights activist Julian Bond says
the fight for equal rights must rely on individuals working within
their communities and not on charismatic leaders.
   ``People must seize control of their lives,'' said Bond,
president of the Atlanta chapter of the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People. ``Today, we wait for others to
sanction our politics.''
   Bond's speech Thursday at Drake University, ``Sins Against the
People,'' was part of the observance of Black History Month.
   Today's black movement must regain the victories won by the civil
rights movement of the 1960s, Bond said.
   ``Despite gains, in a very real way in 1989, we find our
condition unchanged,'' Bond said.
   In 1986, he said, the wealth of the average white family was 12
times that of the average black family. In 1987, Bond added, 42
percent of racial minorities were living below the poverty level.
</TEXT>
