<FIRST>r w AM-Governors-Women     02-24 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors-Women,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Appointing More Women to State Cabinets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governors are appointing record numbers of
women to their state cabinets, more than doubling the total of eight
years ago, a women's political group said Friday.
   The National Women's Political Caucus called for the federal
government to follow suit.
   The group said its survey of the 50 states found 150 women in top
appointed posts, with gains for women coming in all regions and
among governors of both parties.
   It credited the governors with taking the lead in the appointment
of women and said in a report, ``Clearly this is an area in which
the federal government can learn a great deal from the states.''
Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole is the only woman heading one of the
Bush administration's 14 Cabinet departments.
   The number of women in state cabinet posts is up from 70 in 1981
and 130 in 1987, the group said. Women now hold 21 percent of all
state cabinet jobs nationwide.
   ``No doubt about it _ the nation's governors, with few exceptions
are recognizing that qualified, savvy and experienced women have
joined the poitical landscape,'' Irene Natividad, head of the
bipartisan women's political group, said at a news conference.
   But, she added, ``We look forward to the time when such studies
as this are no longer needed.''
   The survey, released a ppeared to be no difference between Republican
and Democratic governors in appointing women. Four of the top 10
governors in the group's rankings were Republicans.
   After Baliles, the governors with the most appointed women in
cabinet jobs were: William D. Schaefer of Maryland, Bill Clinton of
Arkansas, Tommy G. Thompson of Wisconsin, Madeleine Kunin of
Vermont, James R. Thompson of Illinois, Thomas H. Kean of New
Jersey, Henry Bellmon of Oklahoma, Buddy Roemer of Louisiana and
Richard F. Celeste of Ohio. Tommy Thompson, James Thompson, Kean and
Bellmon are Republicans. The others are Democrats.
   Noting the high ranking of several Southern governors, Natividad
said, ``I think we can safely say that the old stereotype that
Southern politicians are resistant to change has effectively been
broken.''
   She also said that while women first made gains by appointment to
administrative or health-related posts, they now are increasingly
being appointed to jobs formerly associated with men, including
those dealing with water, energy and natural resources, she said.
   Natividad suggested the group's survey, which it has released in
past years, with providing ``pressure by comparision'' on governors.
The study commended New Mexico Gov. Garey Carruthers, a Republican
with only one woman cabinet appointee in 1987, for recruiting two
additional women to his cabinet since then.
</TEXT>
