<FIRST>r w AM-USDACutbacks     02-24 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USDA Cutbacks,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says Cutback Decisions Not Yet Made</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No decison has been made on how to squeeze $2
billion out of farm programs to meet federal spending goals, but
analysts are looking at all possibilities, Agriculture Secretary
Clayton Yeutter said Friday.
   ``We'll find a way to do so, because that's a requirement of the
(budget) process,'' Yeutter told reporters. ``Agriculture will have
to play its part in that process.''
   He added: ``We'll look everywhere, obviously ... it'll have to be
done on the basis of economic analysis. We're not going to do it in
an arbitrary or capricious way, and that means analyzing all the
options and combinations of options.''
   About $2 billion will have to be whittled from programs in the
fiscal year that begins Oct. 1. Those cuts were not specified in the
budget proposals submitted by the outgoing Reagan administration in
January and were left open to be negotiated with Congress.
   Yeutter served for 3{ years as U.S. trade representative in the
Reagan administration before President Bush tapped him to be
secretary of agriculture.
   No senior aides to Yeutter at the Agriculture Department have yet
been announced by the White House, and key jobs are still being
carried out by holdovers from the Reagan administration.
   However, Yeutter said at a news conference that he was hopeful an
announcement would be made soon on the No. 2 post of deputy
secretary, probably ``within the next few days.''
   Reports circulated last week that Yeutter and some presidential
aides had been bickering over filling the deputy secretary job, with
Yeutter favoring Jack Parnell, the California agricultural
commissioner, or Sam Hollis, a cotton warehouseman from Memphis,
Tenn.
   But there were claims that White House pressure had developed for
former Kentucky governor Louie Nunn, who told The Associated Press
that he had been interviewed by Yeutter several weeks earlier.
   Yeutter said that the reports of his bickering with the White
House were ``completely false'' and that there had been no
disagreement whatsoever with the White House.
   Options for cutting USDA farm program spending include further
reductions in target prices for major crops, including wheat, corn
and cotton. Those are prices used in a formula to help determine
federal subsidies to farmers who participate in annual crop programs.
</TEXT>
