<FIRST>r i AM-FuneralDiplomacy     02-24 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Funeral Diplomacy,0773</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funeral Accompanied by Flurry of Mini-Summits</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hirohito Funeral, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They came to mourn Emperor Hirohito, but world
leaders used the gathering for a flurry of mini-summits on issues
ranging from Middle East peace and the furor over ``The Satanic
Verses'' to just getting acquainted.
   ``With Japan turning out to be the stage for funeral diplomacy,
the world's attention converged on Tokyo,'' the liberal-leaning
Asahi Shimbun said in an editorial, saying Japan should ``strive to
enhance our international trust.''
   The agreement between China and Indonesia to normalize relations,
suspended 22 years ago, was the biggest result of the Tokyo talks.
It came from a meeting Thursday between President Suharto of
Indonesia and Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen. The long freeze
had resulted from Indonesian allegations that China backed a 1965
communist coup attempt against the Jakarta government.
   The Middle East figured in President Bush's meetings with
Jordan's King Hussein, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Israeli
President Chaim Herzog and French President Francois Mitterrand.
   White House officials said Bush's meetings in Tokyo, most lasting
no more than 30 minutes, mainly were general discussions and were
not intended to delve into detail. But U.S. Secretary of State James
A. Baker III said ``there are perhaps some opportunities out there
with respect to the Middle East peace process that haven't existed
before.''
   Mubarak and Hussein, who had conferred at home with Soviet
Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze on Middle East peace efforts,
met in Tokyo. Spokesmen said they also agreed that recent diplomatic
efforts have brought the Middle East closer to peace.
   Mubarak conferred with Herzog, but they reportedly were unable to
reduce differences over a proposed international peace conference.
   There were delegations from 163 nations at Friday's funeral, and
the Soviets were among the first to arrive. They quickly took up
efforts to improve relations with Tokyo, which insists that any
substantial warming must await the return of a group of islands off
northern Japan occupied by the Soviets since the end of World War II.
   British Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe sought Japan's
support for his country's condemnation of Iran's death threat
against Salman Rushdie, the author of ``The Satanic Verses,'' a
Japanese Foreign Ministry official said. Japan Foreign Minister
Sousuke Uno opposed any international leader advocating murder, but
said Japan had no plans to withdraw its ambassador in Iran.
   Howe dined Friday with the Chinese foreign minister for
discussions on Hong Kong, the British colony that is to return to
Chinese rule in 1997.
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita had meetings set with at
least three dozen foreign dignitaries, and an unscheduled talk
Friday with China's Qian, who also met with Uno.
   Foreign Ministry officials said that Qian and Uno discussed
Takeshita's remarks last week that it would be up to historians to
decide whether Japan was an aggressor in World War II. Qian did not
discuss the issue with Takeshita.
   ``No distortion should take place regarding the past because that
would hurt the feelings of the Chinese people and should be
avoided,'' one official quoted Qian as telling Uno.
   Uno told Qian that Takeshita's real intention was misunderstood,
the officials said. After earlier protests in China, Japanese
officials said Japan was not trying to deny the suffering it had
inflicted on its neighbors.
   Bush met with Philippine President Corazon Aquino and assured her
of U.S. support and noted that his administration is asking Congress
for $200 million in aid for her country, White House press secretary
Marlin Fitzwater said.
   Aid also figured in Takeshita's talks with Brazilian President
Jose Sarney. Foreign Ministry sources said Takeshita promised to
send a mission to Brazil to consider its request for new credits
that could total more than $1 billion.
   On Friday, Uno and Baker took up the U.S.-Japan agreement on
joint development of Japan's next fighter plane, which some American
congressmen say would mean transferring sophisticated U.S.
technology to potential competitors in Japan. Japan denies that.
   Bush also met Friday with King Baudouin of Belgium, Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto of Pakistan, West German President Richard
von Weizsaecker, Singapore Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew, Prime
Minister Turgut Ozal of Turkey, Italian President Francesco Cossiga
and President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire. Bush had a private dinner
with King Juan Carlos of Spain.
   Fitzwater said Bush thanked Ms. Bhutto ``for Pakistan's
courageous efforts to help Afghanistan.''
   Ms. Bhutto also met with Mrs. Aquino, and they agreed to
cooperate in agriculture. Mrs. Aquino promised to help develop
Pakistan's industry.
</TEXT>
