<DOCNO> AP890224-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-NuclearCleanup     02-24 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Cleanup,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Foresees New Rise In Environmental Cleanup Cost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of cleaning up radioactive and toxic
wastes at the government's 12-state nuclear weapons complex is
likely to exceed the official $63 billion estimate, a senior Energy
Department official told Congress on Friday.
   Raymond P. Berube, deputy assistant secretary for environment,
said a firm estimate for cleanup costs was not yet possible because
the department is uncertain how badly the environment has been
damaged at many of the weapons plants.
   ``There's a strong chance that these costs will go higher'' than
$63 billion, he said, adding that projected costs are likely to
escalate as more detailed information is learned about the extent of
the soil and groundwater contamination.
   ``There's a lot of uncertainty at this point,'' he told a House
Armed Services subcommittee.
   Berube said that while contamination at some sites could be
cleaned up in two or three years, work at the most polluted plants
``will require decades to complete.''
   He cited the Pinellas Plant, near Largo, Fla., which makes
electronic components for nuclear weapons, as a likely candidate for
speedy cleanup, in part because the vinyl chloride contamination
there is less far flung and is not radioactive.
   Among the most difficult cleanup jobs will be at the Hanford
Reservation, near Richland, Wash., which Berube said is the most
polluted site in the entire complex, and the Savannah River Plant,
near Aiken, S.C., which produces a highly radioactive gas. There has
been extensive contamination of soil and groundwater at these sites,
dating back to the early years of operation in the 1950s.
   Key elements of the weapons complex, including parts of Savannah
River, Hanford and the Rocky Flats plutonium processing plant in
Colorado, have been closed down by the Energy Department in recent
months because of safety and technical problems.
   An Energy Department report issued last month said it would cost
$52 billion to modernize the weapons complex, and another $29
billion to clean it up, over the next 21 years. The department has
said the cleanup cost eventually would range up to $63 billion, plus
another $2 billion to $4 billion for decommissioning and
decontaminating parts of the complex that are permanently shut down.
   An official of the General Accounting Office, the investigating
arm of Congress, reiterated the GAO's position that some of the
weapons plants are so badly polluted that they may never be cleaned
up. He did not specify these plants.
   ``In the final analysis, some areas within the complex may be
irreversibly contaminated,'' J. Dexter Peach, GAO's assistant
comptroller general, told the House panel. As a result, he said,
these sites may simply be sealed off and never used again.
   Rep. David E. Skaggs, D-Colo., said sealing off sites would
amount to creating ``national sacrifice zones,'' which he called
``utterly unacceptable.''
   Skaggs, whose district includes the Rocky Flats weapons plant,
called on the Energy Department to ``speed up dramatically'' its
efforts to identify all the contamination problems and to clean them
up.
   ``Our national defense and the future of the nuclear weapons
complex itself will be very much at risk if that full cleanup is not
undertaken,'' he said.
   Peach also criticized the Energy Department for having failed to
develop a comprehensive plan for cleaning up the nuclear waste
despite having been urged by the GAO to do so three years ago.
   ``Recent DOE plans and reports have shed considerable light on
the problems DOE faces; however, none of them taken individually or
collectively provide an overall comprehensive environmental
strategy,'' Peach said.
   Berube told the hearing that President Bush's designated energy
secretary, James D. Watkins, was intent on moving quickly to develop
a five-year action plan, based on currently available information,
for cleaning up and modernizing the weapons complex.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1416EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-HirohitoFuneral Bjt   02-24 0861</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito Funeral, Bjt,0883</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Buries Era with Hirohito</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos TOK6,11,42,83</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flutes wailed in a misty forest Friday as Japan
buried Emperor Hirohito, who reigned for 62 years through
militarism, ruin and the undreamed prosperity that sprang from it.
   Kings, leaders or representatives of 163 countries were present
to pay their respects, making the $74 million funeral of the
87-year-old emperor the largest international gathering in modern
history.
   Black-robed court musicians and attendants carrying shields,
pikes and banners of yellow and white preceded the emperor's coffin
to the mausoleum at Hachioji, 30 miles west of Tokyo, in the rites
that marked the end of an era.
   An official carried white shoes that tradition says the emperor
will wear to heaven. Hirohito was considered divine when he became
emperor, descended like his ancestors from the sun goddess, but he
renounced divinity after the crushing defeat of World War II.
   His coffin was placed on a cart, pulled 100 feet up a slope,
lowered into a stone tomb dug into the hillside and sealed in with
concrete. By flickering torchlight in the evening mist, the imperial
family made offerings to his spirit.
   The newspaper Yomiuri said objects buried with the emperor
included the microscope he used in 50 years of research as a
respected marine biologist and a list of rankings of wrestlers in
the traditional sport of sumo, of which he was an avid fan. Palace
officials would not confirm the report.
   Kyodo news service said Hirohito was laid to rest in a white silk
kimono but that a Western suit and tie, his customary dress, were
buried with him.
   A 72-year-old farmer slashed his abdomen with a kitchen knife in
an attempt at ritual suicide beside a war memorial on the southern
island of Kyushu, leaving a note that he wanted to follow his
emperor in death. He was reported in serious condition.
   Mayor Hitoshi Motoshima of Nagasaki, one of two Japanese cities
on which atomic bombs were dropped, said the orations at Hirohito's
funeral ``sounded as if they were avoiding reality. The impression
was that he existed only after the war.''
   Nagasaki police said a letter containing a bullet and a death
threat was delivered to Motoshima on Wednesday after he said the
emperor bore some responsibility for World War II.
   A bomb exploded in an embankment about 20 minutes before the
funeral motorcade passed on its way to the burial ground, scattering
dirt on the road but injuring no one. It was the only violent
incident reported in a day of ceremonies guarded by 32,000 police
officers.
   Earlier in the day, 51 men in the court robes and headgear of
ancient Japan carried Hirohito's coffin on a bamboo-screened litter
to a funeral hall of unvarnished cypress wood in the Shinjuku
Imperial Gardens. Musicians played a dirge on pipes, flutes, drum
and gong.
   After several eulogies, President Bush and other foreign
dignitaries walked to the coffin and bowed slightly to pay final
respects.
   ``For the more than 60 years of your reign ... you shared in the
people's joys and sorrows,'' Emperor Akihito said in a farewell
address to his father, who died of cancer Jan. 7.
   Akihito, 55, was dressed in black tie, tails and a black silk top
hat. He marched in the procession in a near-freezing rain carrying
his own umbrella, as did Empress Michiko, 54; Crown Prince Naruhito,
29, and other members of the imperial family.
   During a 13-hour day of funeral rites, the foreign dignitaries
attended three hours of ceremonies in the gardens. They joined more
than 9,000 Japanese political and business leaders, artists and
athletes in two immense, heated white tents on either side of the
path to the funeral hall.
   Hiroshi Arakawa, spokesman for the National Police Agency, said
about 5,190 people were involved in 71 demonstrations across the
country against the imperial system and 12 people were arrested.
   He said said seven of the arrests were made in Tokyo, including
two people who broke through police lines and ran into a street on
the funeral route.
   Funeral organizers divided the Shinto and lay rites at the
Shinjuku gardens, drawing and reopening a black curtain between the
two parts, because of demands that the constitutional separation of
state and religion be upheld.
   Several members of the opposition Socialist Party skipped the
Shinto ceremony and attended only the part at which government
leaders expressed condolences.
   The Communist Party boycotted the entire funeral, contending the
religious and state-sponsored portions had been conducted as one.
The postwar constitution that specifies separation of religion and
state was written by the United States.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita said Hirohito ``ardently wished
for world peace and the well-being of the Japanese people, and he
always remained at one with them in the effort to overcome the
nation's difficulties.''
   Many stores, offices, factories and entertainment centers were
closed Friday, which was declared a national holiday, but trains to
ski resorts were reported full.
   ``We respect the emperor, but a holiday is a holiday,'' said
Hiroshi Hazama, 37. He said he watched early funeral rites on TV
before catching the train.
</TEXT>
