<FIRST>u a PM-MurderArrest 1stLd-Writethru a0583 02-24 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Murder Arrest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0583,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputy Arrested in Connection with Prostitute Murders</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with deputy named in three slayings,
police saying gun linked to at least three deaths; Picks up 6th graf, `At
least ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff's deputy was arrested in the murder
of three prostitutes and is being investigated in the slayings of
six others who traded sex for drugs, police said today.
   A ballistics test has linked a gun found in the deputy's car to
at least three of the killings, police Chief Daryl Gates said.
   Deputy Rickey Ross, 40, a narcotics investigator who has been
with the Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department for 18 years, was
spotted at 1:30 a.m. Thursday by police officers patrolling South
Central Los Angeles, Gates said.
   Ross had been driving with a woman in an area where several of
the women had been killed, Gates said.
   Ross was arrested by investigators who had accompanied him to his
home in the San Bernardino County city of Rialto, about 55 miles
northeast of downtown Los Angeles.
   He was arrested for investigation of murdering three women, but
police were trying to determine whether Ross was linked to the other
recent slayings, Gates said.
   ``We have ballistic matches on three homicides and three only,''
Gates said.
   Gates said there is no indication the deputy is linked to any of
another series of prostitute killings that terrorized South Central
Los Angeles earlier this decade and became known colllectively as
the South Side slayings.
   The name of the woman in the car with Ross was not released.
Gates said she told officers that she was getting scared before they
arrived because she had been ``well briefed'' by police on the
area's killings.
   The woman told investigators ``simply that he (Ross) wanted to go
to the trunk of his vehicle,'' Gates said.
   The gun that was recovered was in the trunk, although the woman
didn't know that.
   At least nine women known in the streets as ``strawberries'' have
been shot to death since 1985. The body of the last victim was found
in November 1988. The same small-caliber handgun was used in all of
the killings, authorities said.
   This is the second string of murders committed in recent years in
the area south of downtown Los Angeles.
   As many as 18 women, mostly black prostitutes, were believed to
be slain in the Southside Slayer murders, committed from September
1983 to July 1986. One man has been convicted in one of those
deaths, and two other alleged assailants have been charged
separately in seven of the slayings.
</TEXT>
