<FIRST>r i AM-AIDSPardon     02-24 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Pardon,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Prisoner Pardoned by Norway's King</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prisoner infected with the AIDS virus was
granted a royal pardon Friday because he was ostracized after other
inmates learned of his illness.
   The pardon by King Olav V to prisoner Johannes Schwartzman
reversed the Justice Ministry's late 1988 rejection of the inmate's
plea for an early release, the national news agency NTB reported.
   ``I'd given up all hope when I received word of the pardon. I'd
like to forget these last few months in prison. It was a nightmare
that I wouldn't wish on anyone,'' said Schwartzman, 34.
   Word that Schwartzman had the AIDS virus spread quickly through
Ila Prison after guards were informed that he had tested positive in
August 1987.
   Inmates boycotted the prison church and wrote to the Justice
Ministry demanding Schwartzman's removal as a church officer. As
sexton, he handled bread and wine for communion and might accidently
spread the virus, prisoners said.
   The Justice Ministry rejected the demand but confirmed in a
letter posted in the prison that Schwartzman had the virus, which
his attorney said caused the inmate to be isolated.
   ``Leaking word of Schwartzman's infection was a breach of
professional secrecy by doctors,'' said Arne H. Husdal, chairman of
Pluss, Norway's AIDS victims lobby. He said he applauded the
decision and that it set an important precedent, according to the
report.
   Schwartzman, who is Dutch, had served three years of a seven year
sentence and will be expelled from Norway at once, according to the
Oslo newspaper Verdens Gang. His offense was not reported, and
neither prison nor Justice Ministry officials would say why he had
been jailed.
   The pardon was made on the recommendation of the Labor Party
government.
</TEXT>
