<FIRST>r a AM-People-Newman     02-24 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Newman,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>What Keeps Paul Young? Fast Driving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The best way to keep yourself young is to scare
yourself silly _ or so Paul Newman says.
   ``To be behind the wheel of a car doing over 100 mph is one of
the most exhilarating things I know,'' said Newman in the spring
1989 issue of ``Men's Health.'' ``Racing is a way of being a happy
child again.''
   Newman, 64, who races sports cars about six months a year,
dismisses people who would say an actor driving race cars is
unbalanced.
   ``You have to keep things off-balance or it's all over,'' Newman
told the magazine.
   Newman, the star of films such as ``The Hustler'' and ``Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid,'' also is the president of Newman's
Own Inc., a $40 million-a-year food business.
</TEXT>
