<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev Bjt   02-24 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev, Bjt,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Writers Say Gorbachev Supports their Views</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIEV, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev met Friday
with Ukrainian writers pressing for cultural, economic and
environmental reforms, and participants said he expressed support
for their efforts.
   Hours after Gorbachev left, police dragged away people who
gathered near a downtown square where rallies against the Ukrainian
Communist Party chief had been allowed nightly since Sunday, the eve
of Gorbachev's arrival.
   They hauled off anyone who stopped at October Revolution Square
and put them in vans. It was not clear what happened to those who
were detained.
   Dmitro Pavlychko, head of the newly formed Ukrainian Language
Society, which seeks to make Ukrainian the republic's official
language, said the group had a ``beautiful discussion'' with
Gorbachev in party leader Vladimir V. Shcherbitsky's office.
   ``He completely supports all of our national, economic and
ecological thoughts,'' Pavlychko said.
   Shcherbitsky is the only remaining member of the party's ruling
Politburo to have been appointed under Leonid Brezhnev, whose
18-year rule is now regarded as a period of stagnation and
corruption. There have been persistent reports since Gorbachev took
power four years ago that he has tried to oust Shcherbitsky.
   The evening TV news program ``Vremya'' said only that Gorbachev
urged the writers to support his reform efforts.
   It said he also met with top Ukrainian government and party
officials as well as local party leaders before his departure for
Moscow. In what likely was criticism aimed at Shcherbitsky, the Tass
news agency said Gorbachev told the officials that in some cases,
the Communist Party still was avoiding involvement in reform efforts.
   ``It is necessary to raise the intellectual level of party work,
to free it from functions outside its purview,'' he said.
   Gorbachev did not directly criticize Shcherbitsky in the meeting,
said Ivan Drach, head of the Kiev branch of the Ukrainian Writers
Union.
   ``He had to be very gentle, very delicate,'' Drach said. ``He
tried to advance a line of understanding between the writers and the
party.''
   Drach himself called for Shcherbitsky's ouster during the
meeting, he said.
   Russian increasingly has become the language of commerce and
education since Shcherbitsky assumed leadership of the Ukraine in
1972. He replaced Petro Shelest, who was ousted on charges of
encouraging Ukrainian nationalism.
   According to Drach, the writers told Gorbachev they seek an
accounting of economic performance and problems, an end to massive
atomic power and industrial projects they say have devastated the
environment, a truthful history of the Ukraine, and a revival of the
Ukrainian language and culture.
   Drach also is the leader of the fledging Ukrainian Popular
Movement, patterned after the unofficial political organizations
that have drawn more than 100,000 members in the Baltic republics.
   ``We decided concrete things,'' Pavlychko said in an inteview
hours after the meeting with Gorbachev. He declined to elaborate.
   ``There was a palpable difference between Shcherbitsky and
Gorbachev,'' Drach said. ``We could sense from Gorbachev an aura of
good will.''
   Gorbachev told the writers ``he would do everthing to encourage
the Ukrainian language and culture'' and specifically supported
calls to make Ukrainian the official language, Drach said.
   During the meeting, Gorbachev won friends by quoting Taras
Shevchenko and other Ukrainian poets, Pavlychko said.
   He also asked writers for patience, ``to understand the
complexities of the entire situation,'' Pavlychko said. ``We
shouldn't whip our horses,'' he quoted Gorbachev as saying.
   ``It is important that for the first time, the writers were in
the office of Shcherbitsky,'' Drach said. ``We had to wait for the
visit of Gorbachev to get it.''
</TEXT>
