<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--WarOrphans     02-24 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--War Orphans,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>60 Chinese War Orphans Arrive To Search For Japanese Relatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty Chinese ``war orphans'' on Friday began their
search for their real Japanese families who fled China without them
at the end of World War II.
   The 27 men and 33 women arrived in Japan at the start of a 15-day
search for kin. Officials from the Health and Welfare Ministry were
on hand to greet the group at Narita Airport outside Tokyo.
   Since 1981, more than 1,600 Japanese raised by Chinese foster
parents have visited Japan under a government program, and about 570
of them have been reunited with their Japanese relatives.
   The majority were infants when they were left behind by their
families, settlers in northern China, at the end of the war.
   Under a 1988 Japan-China agreement, 100 orphans are scheduled to
visit Japan this year, with all costs covered by the Japanese
government.
</TEXT>
