<FIRST>r a AM-YoungSentence     02-24 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Young Sentence,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>14-Year-Old Youngest Sentenced to Nebraska Pen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By J.L. SCHMIDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-year-old boy was sent to the Nebraska
State Penitentiary because he's a smart youngster who wants to be a
criminal when he grows up, the judge who sentenced the youth said
Friday. The youngster is the youngest person ever held at the prison.
   Buffalo County Judge DeWayne Wolf decided Thursday to send
Richard Boswell to the penitentiary after he was convicted as an
adult of auto theft and of escaping from a state institution.
   ``I feel very vacant,'' Wolf said in a telephone interview.
   ``I sat and stared at this kid. He's a smart person. He knows
what he wants, and, unfortunately, what he apparently wants is to be
a criminal,'' he said.
   Public Defender Gary Hogg, who represented Boswell, said the
judge's only choices were to send Boswell to the Youth Development
Center in Kearney, from which the boy escaped at least twice, or the
state penitentiary. The state does not have a maximum-security
facility for juvenile offenders.
   ``This is no normal kid,'' Wolf said. ``He's 14, but he's not the
average kid from your neighborhood. He's a very dangerous young
man.''
   Wolf sent Boswell to the center in central Nebraska Dec. 19 after
the boy was convicted of escaping from the institution.
   ``I gave him a lecture at that time, that he's too young to go to
the penitentiary, and all that stuff,'' Wolf said.
   The next day, Boswell ran away from the center, which has no
fences.
   After that escape, Wolf and Hogg said, Boswell broke into some
cars and stole a knife, a gun and a set of brass knuckles.
   The officer sent to arrest Boswell in a garage asked for help,
fearing for his safety, Wolf said, adding that Boswell was later
overheard to say that he would have shot the officer if he had come
into the garage.
   Boswell was sentenced to up to three years for escape and one to
four years for auto theft. Wolf said Boswell should be eligible for
parole in about nine months.
   Assistant Corrections Director Larry Tewes said Boswell was held
in a hospital room at the prison.
   ``We could keep him there until he's 16 if we had to, but we'd
rather not. We'll be looking to transfer him to another state which
can handle juvenile offenders,'' said Tewes, who added that Boswell
is the youngest person ever held at the prison.
   Boswell was first sent to the youth center in November 1987 for
robbery, assault and burglary.
   ``The sad part of this real issue is what do you do with the
young criminal,'' Wolf said. ``We have only two choices, YDC or
corrections. We really don't have a secure facility. We need one.''
   State Sen. Jerry Chizek, chairman of the Legislature's Judiciary
Committee, agreed.
   ``We have to recognize that there are juveniles who are real
problems, and we must deal with that,'' he said. ``We don't have an
answer right now, but I do know that sending a 14-year-old to prison
is definitely not going to correct the problem.''
   The problem, Wolf said, stems from the changing nature of
juvenile offenders.
   ``Twenty years ago they were runaways. Today they are doing the
same things as adult criminals,'' Wolf said.
   ``Our failure with this particular youth was some time ago,
probably before he was 8. This just didn't happen overnight,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
