<FIRST>r a AM-CorneaSentencing     02-24 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cornea Sentencing,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cornea Theft Nets Men Six Years Probation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Friday sentenced two men to six
years probation and 1,200 hours community service for stealing
donated eye tissues and selling them abroad.
   Hillsborough Circuit Judge Dennis Alvarez also fined each man
$4,500 to cover restitution and court costs, but said Robert Grant
and Robert Fisher will have a clean record if they successfully
complete probation.
   Grant and Fisher were convicted last month of conspiracy and
grand theft by a jury that acquitted their wives, Gailya Grant and
Irene Fisher.
   They could have been sent to prison for one year on the
conspiracy charge and five on the grand theft count.
   Prosecutors accused them of misrepresenting themselves as members
of a non-profit eye bank in order to gain access to cadavers in
medical examiners' offices, hospitals and funeral homes.
   Grant, 45, and Fisher, 40, sent corneas taken from the corpses to
research facilities in the United States and abroad to Argentina and
Saudia Arabia, authorities said. Many went to a Saudi Arabian
hospital for a processing fee as high as $1,300 a pair, Assistant
Hillsborough State Attorney Judy Hoyer said during trial.
   Medical examiners supplying the corneas _ the transparent tissues
that cover and protect the eyeball _ assumed the tissues were going
to Florida Regional Bone and Tissue Bank Inc., but they were sold by
another eye bank, University Ophthalmic Services Inc.
   Grant and Fisher were former employees of Florida Regional.
   Ms. Hoyer said University Ophthalmic was set up in 1986 by Mrs.
Grant and Mrs. Fisher.
   It was closed a year later after Florida Regional discovered
Grant and Fisher were removing corneas and keeping the fees for
delivering them.
   Defense attorneys maintained their clients simply recognized a
loophole in the law, set up a legitimate eye bank, retrieved corneas
that likely would have been discarded, and capitalized on the need
for eye tissue in foreign countries.
</TEXT>
