<FIRST>r a AM-BurnedOut     02-24 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burned Out,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Foster Mother Burned Out Of Her Home In White Neighborhood</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORDELE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black foster mother saw her dream go up in
flames when a cross was burned in her front yard and fire later
gutted her house in an all-white neighborhood.
   Mae Lester, 27, said it's difficult for her to trust any whites
after the fires earlier this month.
   ``You cut my heart out and burn it up, knowing you can't live
where you want to live,'' she said.
   But Crisp County Sheriff Donnie Haralson said the burning of Ms.
Lester's house isn't indicative of the community's racial climate.
   ``The majority of Crisp County residents don't condone'' what
happened to Ms. Lester, the sheriff said.
   Ms. Lester had moved into the house in a subdivision just north
of Cordele Feb. 12, having signed a $315-a-month lease with an
option to buy at $28,000. She receives about $1,100 a month in state
assistance for caring for five foster children. She has one child of
her own.
   But before she could spend a night in her dream house, someone
burned an 8-foot-high cross on the lawn.
   ``The cross meant they were going to burn me down,'' Ms. Lester
said. So, she repacked and moved in with her sister.
   Two days later, authorities said, fire gutted the house.
   No arrests have been made.
   Jack White, special agent in charge of the Georgia Bureau of
Investigation's regional office in Perry, said Friday that
authorities did not believe the Ku Klux Klan was involved.
   ``We're looking at some individuals,'' White said, declining to
comment on whether any were residents of the subdivision.
   ``There's been nothing to suggest'' that the Klan was involved
``other than the fact that a wooden cross was burned,'' he said.
   James Harris, a vice president of the Crisp County NAACP chapter,
said the organization has not become involved in the incident and is
awaiting the outcome of the investigation.
   ``This is the first incident of this nature in several years,''
he said. ``That's what's so upsetting about it.''
   Jimmy Amerson, 31, and his wife and 9-year-old son live across
the street from Ms. Lester's former house. His fence company, he
said, does business with blacks and he doesn't object to blacks
living in the neighborhood.
   ``I don't care where they live, but I don't want to eat with
them,'' Amerson said.
   H.M. Turton Jr., who leased the house to Ms. Lester, declined to
discuss the fire. Ms. Lester is leasing another house from Turton in
a mixed neighborhood.
</TEXT>
