<FIRST>u a AM-ProstituteMurders Bjt   02-24 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prostitute Murders, Bjt,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Veteran Cop Charged in Three Killings of Prostitutes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A veteran sheriff's deputy who allegedly was
smoking cocaine with a prostitute was arrested for investigation of
murdering three hookers in an area where at least nine prostitutes
have been killed, police said Friday.
   Rickey Ross, 40, a narcotics investigator who has been with the
Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department for 18 years, was spotted
with the woman in his car early Thursday by police officers
patrolling south-central Los Angeles, Police Chief Daryl Gates said
at a news conference.
   Police have been investigating the slayings in the area of at
least nine and possibly as many as a dozen ``strawberries,'' women
who trade sex for drugs, since August 1985.
   Police were investigating whether Ross was linked to the other
recent slayings, Gates said. But he said there was no indication the
deputy was linked to any of another series of prostitute killings in
the area earlier this decade that became known collectively as the
South Side slayings.
   Ross was arrested after a gun found in his car was linked by a
ballistics test to the three killings, police said.
   Gates said the woman in the car did not know Ross was a deputy.
   ``He did not stop her using his badge,'' Gates said. ``He only
identified himself (as a deputy) after the officers stopped him.''
   The name of the woman in the car with Ross was not released.
Gates said officers determined that she was a prostitute, but he
would not characterize her as a ``strawberry.''
   Gates said she told officers that she was getting scared before
the officers stopped them because she had been ``well briefed'' by
police on the killings.
   The woman told investigators ``simply that he (Ross) wanted to go
to the trunk of his vehicle,'' Gates said. The gun was found in the
trunk. The gun was not described but Gates said it was not the
deputy's service weapon.
   Gates said Ross waived his rights and spoke to investigators, but
the chief would only reveal a little bit of what was said.
   ``He was not able to explain all of this,'' Gates said. ``He
admitted he picked up the young woman but he did not believe she was
a prostitute.''
   Los Angeles County Sheriff Sherman Block said Ross, married with
two children ages 20 and 5, had been assigned to a unit at Los
Angeles International Airport.
   ``He has a very fine record,'' Block said. ``He has been a very
effective investigator in the narcotics bureau.''
   Police on routine patrol spotted Ross' car parked, but said it
pulled away from the curb in an ``erratic'' manner when they
approached and the officers made a traffic stop, the chief said.
   The officers believed Ross was under the influence of an
intoxicating substance. Gates said the woman told investigators they
had been smoking cocaine, but he noted that tests were still being
conducted to confirm the type of substance.
   Ross was initially held for driving under the influence. After
the ballistics report on the three killings was finished, he was
arrested in his home in Rialto, about 55 miles east of downtown Los
Angeles.
   A search warrant was obtained and the home was searched but Gates
would not reveal what was recovered there.
   ``We have ballistic matches on three homicides and three only,''
Gates said. Those three victims were found on Oct. 14, Nov. 18 and
Dec. 11.
</TEXT>
