<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Mosbacher     02-24 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mosbacher,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mosbacher Says Europe 1992 Should Be Good for U.S. Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said Friday
that Western Europe's plan to create a unified economy by 1992 is
expected to expand markets for U.S. companies rather than create a
``fortress Europe'' that shuns American goods.
   Mosbacher, in his first major address since joining the Cabinet,
said that while there are sure to be a few European ``strongholds''
against U.S. goods, the initiative generally is likely to improve
business opportunities for Americans.
   The 12 countries in the European Economic Community are trying to
forge a single market, almost as integrated as the United States, by
the end of 1992.
   ``In a sense, 1992 marks a shift in majority view away from
protection and toward openness _ a willingness to gamble that this
openness will work,'' Mosbacher said at a congressionally sponsored
conference on Europe 1992.
   He said government analysts and business executives also are
concerned that some benefits of the unified market may be denied to
non-EEC countries, but the full impact of the initiative won't be
known until the plan actually is implemented.
   ``The reality is that many Europeans are not completely in favor
of more open markets,'' Mosbacher said. ``Some European companies
have been accustomed to having their inefficiency shielded by their
governments.''
   Mosbacher said that while free-trade advocates cannot expect to
win every dispute, U.S. officials will work to eliminate any
inequities.
   ``All of us in the administration will forcefully advocate vital
U.S. business interests through regular meetings with our EC
counterparts,'' he said.
   Speaking about efforts to shrink the U.S. trade deficit,
Mosbacher said he had a message for countries that think they can
continue to sell to the United States while refusing to buy American
products: ``Those days are over.''
   ``An open America is best for us and for the world,'' he said.
``But the world must be open to America as well.''
   In addition, Mosbacher said, American industry must redouble its
investment, research and pursuit of quality in order to better
compete with foreign producers.
   ``American industry must learn to do what others do, and pull out
all stops to win and hold foreign customers,'' he said.
</TEXT>
