<DOCNO> AP890224-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel     02-24 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Soldier Killed, Nine Palestinians Reported Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli reserve soldier was killed in the
West Bank on Friday when Palestinians dropped a cement block on his
head from the roof of a building, the army said.
   The soldier, identified as Binyamin Meisner, 24, was the sixth
member of Israel's armed forces to be killed since the uprising
began in December 1987. A total of 17 Israelis and at least 385
Palestinians have been killed.
   Israel radio and television said Palestinians provoked soldiers
by throwing stones and lured them into one of the narrow alleys of
the city's open air market.
   The large block was then dropped and hit Meisner, who was wearing
a steel helmet. After Meisner was hit, troops opened fire, said a
Nablus army commander who was not identified further.
   The army imposed a curfew on Nablus' 120,000 residents and began
house-to-house searches, and sporadic gunfire was heard, Arab
reports said.
   In the Gaza Strip, nine Palestinians were wounded in clashes with
troops, Arab hospital officials said. The army said it was checking
the reports.
   The hospital officials said the wounded included a 30-year-old
woman who was nine months pregnant. Doctors said she was shot in the
back but was not in serious condition. They said a 4-year-old boy
was shot in the right arm.
   Bassam Abu Sharif, PLO chief Yasser Arafat's political adviser,
said in an interview published Friday he was trying to arrange a
meeting with Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin in London.
   Abu Sharif, speaking in an interview with the Israeli newspaper
Yediot Ahronot in London, said he was ``working through British
political figures in the Conservative Party to arrange a meeting
with Rabin who will visit London.''
   ``If I meet him I will ask him `Why do you shoot children'?'' Abu
Sharif said. ``He will of course ask me, `Why are you rioting'?''
   Rabin has met extensively with Palestinian officials in the
occupied lands, but, in line with government policy, has said he
would not negotiate with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Rabin has left for a fund-raising tour in Switzerland and was
scheduled to go to London before returning to Israel next week, said
a Defense Ministry official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Recent polls have indicated the majority of Israelis support
negotiations with the PLO under certain conditions.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on Friday reiterated his opposition
to talks with the PLO, saying the organization was still intent on
destroying Israel.
   Shamir also rejected a demand by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze that Israel agree to talks with the PLO and an
international Middle East peace conference as the price of renewing
diplomatic ties.
   ``We will not accept any conditions for the resumption of
relations,'' Shamir told a news conference after a three-day visit
to France. ``As long as the Soviet Union doesn't renew ties with
Israel, from our view it cannot be involved in any way in the peace
process in the region.''
   The statement appeared to contradict an earlier one by Foreign
Minister Moshe Arens who said after a meeting with Shevardnadze he
believed the Soviets could play a role in Middle East peacemaking
even without diplomatic ties with Israel.
</TEXT>
