<DOCNO> AP890224-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2051EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Politics     02-24 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Politics,0594</SECOND>
<HEAD>Narrow Conservative Victory Points to Thatcher Disapproval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Conservative Party narrowly retained
one of its safest parliamentary seats Friday against a strong show
of voter disapproval of Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's policies.
   The special election in the wealthy Richmond district in northern
England saw the Tory majority tumble from nearly 20,000 votes to
2,600, saved from defeat only by a split centrist vote.
   It was the biggest collapse of Conservative support since Mrs.
Thatcher came to power in 1979.
   The main opposition Labor Party, which earlier Friday kept its
seat at Pontypridd in South Wales in another by-election, was beaten
into fourth place in Richmond.
   The elections to fill vacant seats in the 650-seat House of
Commons came midway through Mrs. Thatcher's third term, with polls
showing a sharp dro in Tory support and increased backing for Labor.
   Richmond voters appeared to reflect the widespread hostility to
government plans to reform the state-funded National Health Service
and privatize the country's water companies, and to the recent
upsurge in inflation.
   ``There has been something of a protest vote against the
government,'' said William Hague, 27, the victorious Conservative
candidate in Richmond. ``We have had problems on the issue of health
reforms and on the proposed privatization of water. We still have a
lot of convincing to do.''
   The Richmond election had been watched closely to see which of
Britain's two feuding centrist parties _ David Owen's splinter
Social Democrats or Paddy Ashdown's larger, newly merged Social and
Liberal Democrats _ would poll more votes.
   The Social Democrats did by a wide margin, and Owen called it ``a
stunning result ... (which) shows that sticking with your beliefs
pays off in British politics.''
   The results gave Hague 19,543 votes; Social Democrat Michael
Potter 16,909; Social Liberal Democrat Barbara Pearce 11,589; and
Labor's Frank Robson 2,591.
   Potter and Pearce said the results showed their parties should
try to unite behind a single candidate before the next general
election, which Mrs. Thatcher must call by June 1992.
   In Pontypridd, Labor candidate Kim Howells, 42, a research
officer with the left-led National Union of Mineworkers, won 20,549
votes or 53.3 percent.
   Second-place went to the Plaid Cymru Welsh nationalist candidate,
Syd Morgan, with 9,755 votes or 25.3 percent. Plaid Cymru, with
three seats in the 650-seat House of Commons, seeks independence for
Wales. Tory Nigel Evans trailed with 5,212 votes or 13.5 percent.
   Pontypridd is a Labor stronghold in the once thriving but now
largely neglected industrial heartland of South Wales, and Howells'
victory was predictable.
   Labor has lost three consecutive general elections to Mrs.
Thatcher since 1979. Party leader Neil Kinnock is trying to edge
Labor away from some of its hard-line socialist doctrines and soften
its advocacy of unilateral nuclear disarmament.
   Labor has gained in the polls because of discontent with Thatcher
policies, especially the government's plans for the National Health
Service, which many voters see as a first step toward a mainly
private system.
   The service will remain free to patients but hospitals will
compete with each other for fees of state-funded patients and for
private patients. The elderly will get tax breaks for buying private
health insurance.
   The Pontypridd election was caused by the death of local Labor
legislator Brynmor John. The Richmond election was called following
the appointment of the Conservative incumbent, Sir Leon Brittan, to
the European Economic Community's executive commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
