<FIRST>r i AM-Shevardnadze     02-24 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shevardnadze,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Meets With Iraqi President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviets-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Saddam Hussein conferred Friday
with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze on the deadlocked
Iran-Iraq peace talks and the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said the talks were held at
Hussein's resort home in the southern city of Basra, which was
devastated by Iranian attacks during the eight-year Iran-Iraq war.
   Shevardnadze handed Hussein a message from Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev during the three-hour meeting, the agency reported. It
did not disclose the contents.
   Iraqi Defense Minister Adnan Khairallah and Foreign Minister
Tariq Aziz also attended the meeting.
   Hussein, the agency said, told Shevardnadze that Iraq ``was
opposed to efforts to freeze the Iran-Iraq conflict and maintain the
present no-war, no-peace situation.''
   Shevarnadze told Hussein that Moscow ``respects the Iraqi stand
and its determination to work for a settlement of the conflict,''
the agency said.
   A U.N.-mediated cease-fire halted the war Aug. 20. But peace
talks that began five days later have been deadlocked over troop
withdrawals.
   Upon arriving Thursday in Baghdad, the fourth stop on his Middle
East tour, Shevardnadze said he was concerned about lack of progress
in the peace negotiations.
   He will be in Tehran on Saturday, where he has been granted a
rare audience with Iranain leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Eastern diplomats here said Shevardnadze would press Iraqi and
Iranian leaders to work toward a peace treaty in the negotiations
being conducted under United Nations auspices.
   The Soviet Union, Iraq's major weapons supplier and one of its
key trade partners, is believed to have supplied Iraq with billions
of dollars worth of goods on credit during the gulf war.
   Shevardnadze and Hussein also touched on the Arab-Israeli
conflict, the Iraqi news agency said.
   The two hailed the PLO's peace overtures and agreed to work to
``activate a serious initiative that would lead to peace in the
Middle East,'' the news agency reported.
   Shevardnadze arrived in Baghdad from Cairo, where he said
Thursday that Israel must agree to talk with the PLO and accept an
international peace conference as the price of resuming full
diplomatic relations with the Kremlin.
   Israel has said relations must come before an expanded Soviet
role in peace negotiations.
   Shevardnadze met separately with PLO chairman Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Foreign Minister Moshe Arens in Cairo on Wednesday.
   Israel opposes a U.N.-organized peace conference but has said it
would go to one under the auspices of the United States and the
Soviet Union. The Israelis, however, vow never to talk with the PLO,
which they accuse of being a terrorist organization.
</TEXT>
