<FIRST>r w AM-Businessman-Exports     02-24 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Businessman-Exports,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Loses Export Privileges for 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German businessman who was convicted of
illegally re-exporting a chemical warfare ingredient to Iran has
been denied all U.S. export privileges for 10 years, the Commerce
Department said Friday.
   Peter Walaschek was convicted in U.S. District Court in Baltimore
last August after pleading guilty to illegally re-exporting
U.S.-made thiodiglycol from Singapore to Iran in violation of the
Export Administration Act, the department said. The substance is an
ingredient of mustard gas, which is used in chemical warfare.
   Between January 1987 and April 1988, Walaschek purchased more
than 210 tons of the substance in the United States for shipment to
Singapore and Greece, then re-exported the chemical from Singapore
to Iran without approval from the Commerce Department, the agency
said.
   Commerce Undersecretary Paul Freedenberg said the department's
action ``demonstrates the importance the United States places on
prevention of the further spread of chemicals used for warfare.''
   Freedenberg said that Walaschek deliberately tried to hide the
true destination of the chemicals he purchased and that the
transactions highlight ``what countries such as Iran will do to
acquire the chemicals they need to wage chemical warfare.''
</TEXT>
