<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica     02-24 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third Associate Of Winnie Mandela Linked To Youth's Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third associate of Winnie
Mandela appeared in court Friday in connection with the slaying of a
14-year-old activist who allegedly was assaulted at Mrs. Mandela's
house.
   John Morgan, 61, appeared briefly in Johannesburg Magistrate's
Court. Authorities have identified him as the bus driver for Mrs.
Mandela's unofficial bodyguards, known as the Mandela United soccer
club.
   On Tuesday, the self-described coach of Mandela United, Jerry
Richardson, and a 17-year-old club member were arraigned in court on
charges of murdering activist Stompie Seipei, 14. They were arrested
Sunday at Mrs. Mandela's home in Soweto, outside Johannesburg.
   Mrs. Mandela is the wife of Nelson Mandela, the jailed chief of
the African National Congress, the largest group fighting the
white-dominated government.
   Last week, major anti-apartheid groups accused Mandela United
members of conducting a ``reign of terror'' in Soweto and said Mrs.
Mandela should be ostracized. The groups stressed that they remained
loyal to Nelson Mandela.
   Morgan's appearance in court Friday was procedural and did not
deal with the substance of the case against him, officials said.
News of the appearance was the first disclosure Morgan had been
arrested.
   Seipei, whose funeral is scheduled for Saturday, allegedly was
abducted in late December along with three other young men, taken to
Mrs. Mandela's home and assaulted.
   Seipei's decomposed body was found in a field on Jan. 7 and was
identified by forensic experts two weeks ago.
   Mandela summoned three prominent anti-apartheid lawyers for a
four-hour meeting Thursday at Victor Verster prison farm near Cape
Town, but details of the discussions have not been disclosed.
   Seipei's murder is one of four recent killings involving people
connected directly or indirectly to Mrs. Mandela and her bodyguards.
   On Wednesday, a 13-year-old Soweto girl was killed when gunmen
fired on her house with AK-47 rifles and set the dwelling on fire
with a firebomb. Police said the attack might have been in revenge
for the killing last week of Maxwell Madondo, a member of Mandela
United.
   Last month, Dr. Abu Baker Asvat, a physician and activist, was
shot and killed at his Soweto clinic. A suspect has confessed to
shooting Asvat during a robbery attempt, and police say the case is
non-political. But Mrs. Mandela has suggested that Asvat may have
been killed because he had examined Seipei and other youths she said
were sexually molested by a Methodist minister.
   Methodist leaders have denied the sex allegations and accused
Mrs. Mandela of falsely implying that the church conspired with
police to discredit her.
   The African National Congress and a committee of Soweto activists
have suggested that Mandela United was infiltrated by police agents,
but these groups have criticized Mrs. Mandela for poor judgment and
lack of discipline.
   In another development, anti-apartheid leaders criticized the
government for not releasing more detainees following negotiations
to end a hunger strike.
   Nearly 300 black detainees in Johannesburg and Port Elizabeth
suspended a three-week hunger strike last week after Law and Order
Minister Adriaan Vlok told anti-apartheid church leaders that a
``substantial number'' of detainees would be released within two
weeks.
   Mary Burton, president of the Black Sash civil rights group, told
a news conference held by several activists that only 17 detainees
had been released.
   ``This is not a substantial number of detainees, and does not
enable us to report to the hunger strikers that their suffering and
their agreement to suspend the strike have been vindicated,'' she
said.
   Many of the detainees have been held for more than two years
without charges, and they are demanding that they either be charged
or released.
</TEXT>
