<DOCNO> AP890224-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-CannibalTrial     02-24 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cannibal Trial,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Captain Reprimande for Not Picking up Boatload of Vietnamese</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUBIC NAVAL BASE, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military jury reprimanded
a U.S. Navy captain Friday for not giving enough help to a boatload
of Vietnamese refugees who resorted to cannibalism to survive.
   The jury of six Navy captains could have jailed Alexander Balian,
a decorated Vietnam war veteran, for 90 days and made him forfeit
two-thirds of his pay for three months.
   It said he erred in handling the situation that arose last June 9
while his ship was in the South China Sea but deserved no further
punishment than being relieved of command, as he was in August.
   He was acquitted of the more serious charge of ordering one
refugee shaken off ropes as the man tried to climb aboard the
amphibious landing ship USS Dubuque.
   Balian, 48, claimed he was made a scapegoat and said, ``Heroes
like me are hung out to dry when they get in trouble.''
   He was charged with failing to render adequate assistance to more
than 80 Vietnamese refugees in a leaky boat the Dubuque encountered
about 250 miles north of the Philippine island of Palawan.
   U.N. officials said 31 refugees later died and survivors said
they had eaten the flesh of the dead before Filipino fishermen
rescued them June 27.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
