<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     02-24 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright And Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Council gave approval to a ribs
festival, but only after it was assured some racing pigs would be
living high on the hog.
   The ``World Series of Ribs'' on Memorial Day weekend will include
fireworks, entertainment, magicians and a pig race.
   Would the pigs be treated cruelly in the race, Council member
Janice Rettman wanted to know.
   Council member Kiki Sonnen said an animal-rights activist, after
checking with the Humane Society, said the critters are well cared
for and allowed to run free.
   That prompted Council member Roger Goswitz to ask jokingly: ``Is
it true the contest losers are used later on for the ribs?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KENOSHA, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four state lawmakers hope they can lure
President Bush to the waters of Wisconsin with a free fishing permit.
   The lawmakers said they'll buy the 15-day non-resident fishing
permit for $15.10 which Bush can redeem if he takes a Wisconsin
vacation.
   When the Legislature reconvenes next month, they plan to
introduce a resolution, which says, in part:
   ``Whereas President Bush is an avid fisherman who has fished
fresh and salt water from New England to the Gulf of Mexico;
   ``And whereas our well-schooled president has angled his way to
the nation's premier perch at 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue, Washington,
D.C.;
   ``And whereas the Wisconsin Legislature desires to open the
waters of the kinder, gentler Badger State for the president to
legally fish.''
   The resolution closes with an invitation to Bush to fish in
Wisconsin and the offer of a free fishing permit.
</TEXT>
