<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     02-24 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Say Army Attaced Rebel Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas made the
second charge in as many days Friday that the army attacked one of
their field hospitals. The report said one person was killed and
another wounded.
   The armed forces denied both allegations.
   Venceremos, the clandestine rebel radio, said soldiers used light
artillery and small arms in an attack Feb. 18 on a field hospital
near Santa Clara in San Vicente province, about 40 miles east of San
Salvador.
   On Thursday, the Legal Aid Office of the Roman Catholic church
said 10 people were slain in an army attack Feb. 13 on a rebel field
hospital.
   A ``brigadista'' was killed in the attack last Saturday and a
patient was wounded, Venceremos said, adding that soldiers ``stole
and destroyed all hospital supplies and medicines.''
   The report did not identify the ``brigadista,'' a term often used
for armed paramedics.
   Col. Galileo Torres, director of the Armed Forces Press Office,
denied the Radio Venceremos report.
   ``What's happening is that the rebels are trying to continue with
the line that we are violators of human rights and of the Geneva
Convention'' on human rights, he said in a telephone interview.
   Torres said ``there normally aren't hospitals'' in the area of
the alleged attack ``because there is constant combat and military
units constantly force the guerrillas to move on.''
   The Legal Aid Office said Thursday two of those killed in the
Feb. 13 attack in the northern province of Chalatenango _ a woman
doctor and a 14-year-old girl _ may have been raped.
   Venceremos claimed Feb. 15 that soldiers of the Atlacatl
Battalion attacked and destroyed the field hospital two days
earlier. It said three medical workers and three guerrilla patients
were killed.
   Both the Legal Aid Office and rebel radio identified the possible
rape victims as Alejandra Bravo Betancourt, a 35-year-old Mexican
doctor, and Rosibel Dubon, a paramedic's aide. Their bodies were
exhumed and examined Feb. 17 by the representatives of the Legal Aid
Office, a respected human rights organization.
   Legal Aid said five wounded guerrillas and three other medical
aides also were killed at the hospital outside Los Encuentros
village near the Sumpul River, which forms El Salvador's border with
Honduras.
   Col. Ciro Lopez Roque, military commander of Chalatenango
province, told reporters Thursday there was no field hospital near
Los Encuentros. He said Atlacatl soldiers killed several guerrillas,
including the Mexican doctor, in combat Feb. 13.
   Legal Aid concluded that a field hospital was set up near Los
Encuentros and Atlacatl troops ``attacked and destroyed the field
hospital and killed war wounded and the medical personnel present.''
   It called the attack ``a flagrant violation'' of El Salvador's
constitution and the 1949 Geneva Conventions, to which El Salvador
is a signatory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
