<DOCNO> AP890224-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ThirdWorldDebt     02-24 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Third World Debt,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Reject Charge that Policies Discourage Third World Debt
Forgiveness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal bank regulators, in a report to
Congress released Friday, rejected charges that their policies
discourage banks from forgiving part of the huge debt owed by Third
World countries.
   ``Current regulatory policy and accounting policies have not
prevented banks, that were otherwise inclined to do so, from
participating in a wide range of negotiated debt reduction
transactions with borrowing countries,'' three regulatory agencies
said in a report to the Senate Banking Committee.
   Critics of current policy say banks are discouraged from
realistically recognizing losses on Third World debt. They say banks
should be permitted to spread the effects of recognizing losses over
several years. Currently, they must reduce their profit by the full
amount of any addition to loss reserves.
   However, the Federal Reserve Board, Office of the Comptroller of
the Currency and the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said accounting
standards are designed to present a true picture of banks' financial
condition, adding, ``accounting policies ... are not intended to
encourage or discourage any actions that management considers to be
in the best interest of the institution.''
   They cited World Bank estimates showing that $20 billion in
developing country debt has been eliminated in the past two years.
   The three agencies also said that banks' exposure to developing
country debt had improved considerably since the crisis first
emerged in 1982 but was still large for the nation's 10 biggest
banks.
   At the end of September, the 10 largest banks were on the hook to
developing countries for loans representing 95 percent of the banks'
capital and loss reserves.
   And, the report endorsed the continuation of the so-called Baker
plan, which rejects taxpayer contributions toward solving the
problem and encourages case-by-case negotiations for additional
lending rather than any coordinated plan of debt forgiveness.
   The approach is named after Secretary of State James A. Baker
III, who developed while serving as Ronald Reagan's Treasury
secretary.
   ``The bank regulatory agencies continue to believe the
case-by-case negotiated approach is the best method,'' the report
said.
   President Bush has said his administration will take a new look
at the approach, but has advocated no specific changes.
   On another point, the report said the secondary market for
selling and swapping Third World loans is a poor indicator of the
loans' true value. Many analysts say they are worried because the
loans are now worth about 40 percent of their original value, down
from 60 percent in mid-1987. The regulators said secondary market
prices may reflect short-term supply and demand rather than the
long-term value of the loans.
   The regulators' report is the first installment toward meeting
the requirements of a section of last year's trade act. A second
report, due by May 31, will examine the effects of Third World
lending on bank profits between 1977 and 1987.
   The Treasury Department was supposed to deliver another report
this week on new approaches for solving the debt crisis, but was
given a three-week extension.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1713EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Yugoslavia     02-24 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests In Southern Province Spread Despite Official Warnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SLOBODAN LEKIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians
refused to work on Friday to protest ethnic discrimination and to
demand the resignation of a provincial Communist Party chief.
   Yugoslav Communist Party leader Stipe Suvar descended a mine
shaft to meet with miners who began the strike Monday, but they
reportedly told another official that ``you can have us out only in
our coffins.''
   The state-run media said 40,000 people have staged sympathy
strikes across Kosovo, a province of Serbia, one of six Yugoslav
republics.
   Schools, universities and most businesses closed Friday, and the
Tanjug news agency described the province as ``on the verge of a
general strike and total paralysis.''
   Suvar and Serbian party boss Slobodan Milosevic rushed to
Pristina, the provincial capital, to prevent possible ethnic clashes
between Kosovo's Albanian majority and the Slav minority.
   ``The crisis has reached critical point,'' Suvar said at a
meeting in Pristina, the provincial capital. ``We must stop at all
cost the worsening of the situation.''
   The protesters condemn Serbia's drive to secure greater control
over Kosovo by changing the current constitution, fearing they would
lose wide autonomy granted to them in 1974. They also demand the
resignation of provincial party leader Rahman Morina, who they
consider an ally of Serbian party boss Slobodan Milosevic.
   Serbian leaders have asserted that they must have more control in
Kosovo to protect the mainly Christian Slav minority allegedly
persecuted by predominantly Moslem ethnic Albanians, who make up 85
percent of the province's population.
   President Raif Dizdarevic said he would ``take all measures under
the constitution and laws'' to prevent ``violations of order and
peace and thhreats to the constitutional system.''
   Foreigners traveling to Kosovo noticed an unuusally large number
of police, an indication that units were sent to Kosovo from Serbia.
There was no official confirmation.
   More than 1,300 ethnic Albanian miners, some on a hunger strike,
have refused to leave their pits at the Trepca mines.
   Later Friday, Suvar met with the Trepca mine's management and
said that ``nobody, not even the miners, have a right to issue
political ultimatums to the country.''
   Suvar, who spent three hours with the striking miners, left the
Trepca mine without any apparent result. He would not comment on the
meeting.
   Suvar was told by Aziz Abrasi, the director of the mine, that the
miners have told him ``you can have us out only in our coffins.''
   About 250 miners have asked for medical aid, said Dr. Nedjmi
Zeciri, the mine's medical officer. Six were hospitalized for
exhaustion, while the rest received treatement at the makeshift
first aid station outside the mine, he said.
   Milosevic on Friday reiterated his stand by saying in Pristina
that ``Albanian nationalism'' has caused ''physical, political and
cultural violence over'' Slavs in the province, ''which is
unprecedented in Europe today.''
   In November, up to 100,000 ethnic Albanians demonstrated in
Pristina for five days to protest the dismissal of senior provincial
officials as demanded by Serbia's leaders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
