<FIRST>u i AM-Estonia 1stLd-Writethru a0605 02-24 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Estonia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0605,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Estonians Hail Independence Day, Raise National Flag</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with ``many thousands'' attending,
celebration details. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Estonians celebrated their
Independence Day Friday by hoisting their national flag over the
highest castle tower in the capital of Tallinn after relegating the
flag of Soviet Estonia to a museum.
   The Soviet government newspaper Izvestia said ``many thousands''
of people attended, including the republic's Communist Party chief
Vaino Vyalyas. Soviet television showed crowds in the cobble-stoned
Old Town of the Baltic port.
   Estonia was a province of the czarist Russian empire, but it
proclaimed itself independent on Feb. 24, 1918, after the 1917
Bolshevik revolution. The small Baltic republic was absorbed by the
Soviet Union in 1940 under a secret protocol between Nazi Germany
and Moscow that divided East Europe into spheres of influence.
   The blue, black and white banner hoisted on Friday was the flag
of independent Estonia between the world wars.
   The flag of Soviet Estonia that flew for decades when displaying
the tricolor banner was illegal was taken down Thursday night before
and given to a local Communist historical museum, the official
Soviet news agency Tass said.
   ``The decision to proclaim Feb. 24 as the day of Estonia's
independence and to raise the blue, black and white national flag on
the Gherman tower on that day is an important step toward restoring
the Estonian people's dignity and recognizing their genuine
history,'' said a statement issued by the Estonian Communist Party.
   The flag-raising ceremony also was attended by clergymen and
representatives of the People's Front unofficial political movement.
   The People's Front has led the drive during the past year to
wrest more cultural and economic autonomy from Moscow. Party and
government leaders have been replaced by those sympathetic to the
organization's goals. In November the republic's Supreme Soviet, or
parliament, declared sovereignty in all areas except foreign and
military affairs.
   The Kremlin declared that move invalid, but Estonia has not
backed down.
   Arnold Ruitel, president of the presidium of the republic's
Supreme Soviet, told a rally outside the tower, ``it should be
clearly realized that dates of national history and national symbols
should not be regarded as something hostile to socialism.''
   Soviet officials last summer eased restrictions on the drive for
more autonomy in the nearby republics of Latvia and Lithuania as
well as in Estonia.
   The local parliaments moved quickly to make ethnic languages
official and permit use of national flags on holidays, sporting
events and cultural rallies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     02-24 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government, Opposition Agree On Union Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition and government negotiators
agreed on a proposal Friday that would allow new trade unions to
form and legalize the Solidarity independent union movement,
officials said.
   The proposal was reached by a working group that is part of the
broad talks between the government and opposition on political and
economic reforms.
   The proposed labor law is the result of a Feb. 16 agreement by
the sides to amend the current labor act. The proposal would have to
be passed by the Sejm, or parliament, to become law.
   The proposal would allow trade unions to organize nationally. The
current law that took effect in 1982 restricted how quickly a
nationwide union could form.
   ``The whole nationwide union will be allowed to shape its
internal organizations freely. The draft was not questioned and was
accepted,'' said Tadeusz Mazowiecki, the leader of the opposition
delegation to the talks.
   At a meeting with students at the Gdansk Polytechnic on Friday,
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said that ``Until now I am satisfied
with the discussions and with the fact that all (sides) agree about
the necessity of reforms. But I feel a lack of political decisions.''
   Walesa said he has asked his advisers and Solidarity negotiators
to provide a ``point by point'' list of the biggest stumbling blocks
that would require political decisions.
   Mazowiecki said more talks were needed on how to resolve
conflicts when rival unions form at the same enterprise.
   The official trade union alliance, OPZZ, proposed that disputes
between trade unions be the subject of a worker referendum, said the
leader of the OPZZ delegation, Romuald Sosnowski, on state
television.
   At a news conference, Mazowiecki said only the most important
issues should be put to a referendum and that the OPZZ proposal
seemed ``demagogic.''
   ``Let's hope that despite everything, it's only the difficult
beginning of trade union pluralism and that we will push forward at
the next meeting,'' Mazowiecki said.
   Th government has made it clear that Solidarity will be legalized
only if the opposition accepts a whole package of political and
eocnomic reforms.
   The talks began Feb. 6 and are expected to last six weeks.
   Solidarity was born in the labor turmoil of 1980, the first free
union in the Soviet bloc, then suppressed and outlawed after the
declaration of martial law in December 1981.
   Also Friday, at least 25 people were arrested during in Warsaw
and the southern city of Krakow.
   Several hundred people gathered in Krakow's market square to
protest the beating of demonstrators during a Feb. 17 rally against
political indoctrination in schools, said rally spokesman Adam
Slomka.
   Police used water cannons and tear gas to break up the protest,
he said.
   Ten people were arrested, he said. Two people were taken away in
an ambulance and several others were beaten, said a student activist
who declined identification.
   In Warsaw, police arrested at least 15 supporters of the ``Orange
Alternative,'' an independent group founded in the southwestern city
of Wroclaw that has attracted attention for its satirical street
events mocking authority.
   A crowd of several hundred people watched as members painted
store windows and the street with bright orange paint.
</TEXT>
