<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CamerasInCourt     02-24 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cameras In Court,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recording Done on Trial Basis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television cameras, normally barred from
federal courtrooms, have been used to record U.S. Court of Military
Appeals proceedings in what a group of news organizations hopes will
be the start of a trend.
   The TV cameras and sound equipment were operating for two hours
Thursday as lawyers argued the constitutionality of drug tests for
military personnel.
   The almost unprecedented presence of the equipment was authorized
by the three-judge court on a request by 13 news organizations,
including the four major television networks.
   Timothy Dyk, a lawyer representing the organizations, said the
results were encouraging.
   ``Everybody was very excited about it and pleased with the
results and the quality of the pictures,'' he said.
   Dyk said the filming, which will be broadcast at a later date,
was done without enhanced lighting and using the court's own sound
system.
   Dyk said he believed it was the first time TV cameras have been
used to record proceedings in any federal court. But some years ago
a federal judge in Roanoke, Va., permitted cameras in his courtroom.
   A demonstration of television cameras in court was conducted by
Dyk last November for three Supreme Court justices. That was a trial
run _ not a live court proceeding _ aimed at winning support from
the high court for the idea.
   While nearly all states allow some televised state court
coverage, the federal courts have remained adamant in banning
cameras from the courtroom.
   Dyk said the military appeals court is not covered by those
rules, adopted by the U.S. Judicial Conference, which helps
administer the federal court system.
   The U.S. Court of Military Appeals is a civilian appellate court
with jurisdiction over the military justice system.
   Two cameras were used to record Thursday's proceedings. One was
focused on the three judges hearing the case and was manned by a
cameraman. The second camera was unmanned and was placed at the side
of the judges' bench to focus on the lawyers.
   Dyk said there are no plans for the next step in the campaign to
change the policy against televised federal court proceedings.
   But he said those present Thursday felt there was no disruption.
   ``We talked to the judges and counsel afterward and they say they
saw no problem with it,'' Dyk said. ``One lawyer said he was
nervous, but because his wife was there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
