<FIRST>r w AM-DefenseProbe     02-24 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Probe,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three More Suspended in Pentagon Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy on Friday suspended three men from
doing business with the federal government in a move stemming from
the long-running investigation of defense contract fraud.
   Two of the men, Robert D. Barrett and Joseph E. Hill, were
suspended as a result of their guilty pleas on Jan. 27 to making
illegal campaign contributions to members of Congress.
   The third man, Wilborn J. Sanda, was suspended ``based upon
previously released affidavit information pertaining to his conduct
as a consultant to defense contractors,'' the Navy said.
   Barrett, a former executive at Unisys Corp., a giant computer
company that does work for the Defense Department, and Hill, a
consultant paid by Unisys, have agreed to cooperate with prosecutors
as part of a plea arrangement.
   The pleas were part of the federal government's two-year-old
investigation into the Pentagon's $150-billion-a-year procurement
practices. The case includes allegations that private consultants,
hired by defense contractors, bribed Pentagon officials to obtain
inside information that gave companies an edge in securing contracts.
