<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2139EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Medicare-Budget     02-24 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicare-Budget,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medicare Plan by Bush in Trouble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's proposal for a $5
billion reduction in Medicare next fiscal year appeared Friday to be
going nowhere.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said he wouldn't support the proposed reduction, which
was also turned down by the House Ways and Means Committee the day
before.
   ``The idea that we can save some $5 billion, I think, is
unacceptable,'' said Bentsen, whose committee has jurisdiction on
the Senate side over the federal health insurance program for the
elderly.
   Medicare costs have been growing rapidly as the number of elderly
Americans increases and as the prices of medical services rise
faster than the general rate of inflation.
   This year's Medicare costs of $84.5 billion would grow to $97.5
next year without restraints. Bush, however, proposed to hold the
program to $92.5 billion in fiscal 1990 by limiting payments to
hospitals and doctors who treat Medicare patients and by trimming
supplementary payments to teaching hospitals.
   Bentsen, however, said the financial strain on many hospitals
would not withstand the proposed cut, which would shave more than
$3.5 billion from Medicare payments to hospitals.
   ``The numbers we're looking at now ... (indicate) many are at the
break-even point and this is further complicated by the substantial
number of hospitals that have had to close their doors and haven't
been able to make ends meet,'' Bentsen said.
   ``A reduction of that amount is excessive and we'd be going too
far,'' he said.
   The chairman declined to say how much of a savings he would be
willing to support.
   The Ways and Means Committee, which has jurisdiction over the
program on the House side, said in a report Thursday that ``it is
not reasonable to expect providers or beneficiaries to absorb the
level of reductions proposed by the administration in the Medicare
program for fiscal year 1990.''
</TEXT>
