<FIRST>r a AM-ChicagoMayoral     02-24 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP's Write-In Renegade Puts Party In Spotlight At Last</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor's office has been held by Democrats for
half a century and that's unlikely to change this year, but a GOP
write-in candidate may throw a small monkey wrench into the
opposition works in Tuesday's primary.
   At the very least, the outnumbered Republicans got a moment in
the spotlight when, with less than a week to go, flashy former
Democrat Edward Vrdolyak made his write-in bid official Wednesday.
   Democratic frontrunner Richard M. Daley, the Cook County
prosecutor and son of the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, and acting
Mayor Eugene Sawyer say they expect little impact on their contest,
though some observers say Vrdolyak's bid on the GOP side could
siphon off some of Daley's white ethnic votes.
   Herbert Sohn, the GOP candidate endorsed by the Cook County
party, says he'll whip Vrdolyak hands down.
   Alderman Timothy Evans, who like Sawyer is black, will take on
the Democratic and GOP primary winners as a third-party candidate in
the April 4 special general election.
   Analysts say Vrdolyak is a long-shot for the GOP nomination, and
that odds are even worse for a Republican winner in April. The
party's last mayor, William Hale ``Big Bill'' Thompson, lost his
1931 re-election bid.
   In a radio-show recording session, Vrdolyak said he hopes to win
10,000 votes; that amount could guarantee him the nomination in this
Democratic stronghold and is half what he got from his ward in a
failed 1987 mayoral bid.
   His big challenge Tuesday will be to get people to properly write
in votes with punch-card voting machines, said Paul Green, a
professor at Governors State University in suburban University Park
who follows city politics.
   ``It's physically very difficult to have legal write-ins on a
punch-card system,'' Green said.
   But Vrdolyak showed he can still draw a crowd at Wednesday's
rally, where a multiracial crowd cheered him on and supporters said
they had more than 50,000 signatures on petitions drafting him for
the race.
   Vrdolyak switched parties after resigning from City Council and
giving up his post as chairman of the powerful Cook County
Democratic Party to mount his third-party challenge to Harold
Washington, the city's first black mayor, two years ago.
   Sohn, 61, shares the Republican ballot with former GOP
committeeman Kenneth Hurst, 62, and a businessman who has been
accused of writing an anti-Semitic and racist tract, William J.
Grutzmacher, 58.
</TEXT>
