<SECOND>AM-GOP-Duke, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0687,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>National GOP Leaders Formally Denounce Duke</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts new 2nd graf and one graf after 4th graf pvs bgng: After
Duke's ... to UPDATE with comment from Duke. Picks up 6th graf pvs bgng:
The opposition ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Party leaders completed action
Friday on a resolution denouncing former Ku Klux Klansman David Duke
and denying him any financial or technical assistance from the
national party.
   ``What makes a Republican is not the approval of some backroom
committee, but the approval of the voters who elected me,'' Duke
said when told of the action.
   The resolution was adopted unanimously by a telephone vote of the
11 members of the party's executive committee.
   Duke was elected as a Republican to the Louisiana House of
Representatives Saturday despite appeals by President Bush and
former President Reagan on behalf of his GOP opponent, John Treen.
   After Duke's election, he was denounced by Republican Party
Chairman Lee Atwater and Bush indicated his only regret about
opposing Duke was that it might have helped him.
   ``Mr. Atwater cannot take away me being a Republican nor can this
committee,'' said Duke. ``As far as not giving me any money or
technical assistance, I didn't need any money or technical
assistance to win this race and I won't need any money or technical
assistance to win any future races I may be involved in.''
   The opposition of national party leaders had little impact on
Republican legislators in Louisiana, who welcomed Duke into their
ranks when he was sworn in on Wednesday.
   Leslie Goodman, a spokesman for the national party, said the vote
was conducted over the last two days.
   She said a copy of the resolution was not available because party
lawyers were refining its language.
   However, a proposed resolution, made public late last week,
denounced the former Klan leader, saying that Duke ``may be a
Republican in party registration but he is not a Republican in
gesture, deed or belief.''
   The resolution described Duke as a former ``grand dragon of the
White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan and the founder of the National
Association for the Advancement of White People, which embraces
views antithetical to the Republican Party;
   ``Secondly, Duke and these groups preach doctrines of racial,
religious and ethnic hatred, bigotry and discrimination against
American citizens which are abhorrent to the American tradition and
have no place in the Republican Party.''
