<HEAD>Police Kille 12, Wound 40 In Protest Against Book</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police opened fire Friday during violent
protests against ``The Satanic Verses'' in author Salman Rushdie's
native city, killing up to 12 people and injuring 40, according to
news reports.
   At least 5,000 Moslems chanting ``Allahu Akbar!'' (God is Great)
gathered in central Bombay after midday prayers. Mobs set fire to
buses and other vehicles and attacked several officers, said a
policeman on duty at Bombay headquarters.
   He said police arrested 300 protesters. The news agency Press
Trust of India said at least 11 policemen were injured.
   Other protests of the novel, which Moslems say blasphemes their
religion, occurred in New Delhi, Calcutta and four other Indian
cities, United News of India and Press Trust reported.
   Reports on the number of deaths in Bombay conflicted. Press Trust
of India said 12 people were killed, United News of India said 10
and Police Commissioner S.M. Shangari put the total at eight.
Shangari said two deaths initially attributed to the violence were
caused by road accidents during the protests.
   New Delhi's 32,000-member police force was put on alert, a
spokesman said, because ``the Bombay incidents have forced us to
think that it may be the real beginning of a problem.''
   More than 90 million Moslems live in India, a predominantly Hindu
country of 880 million.
   Protesters in Bombay ignored a police ban on the assembly of more
than five people in public place Friday, the Moslem Sabbath. The ban
was imposed after some Moslems announced plans to protest the book.
   Rushdie was born into a Moslem family in Bombay in 1947. He now
lives in London.
   At least one person was killed in India during a similar
demonstration Feb. 13, the day after six were killed Feb. 12 in
neighboring Pakistan, where police fired on protesters who tried to
set the U.S. Information Agency office in Islamabad ablaze to
protest publication of the book in the United States.
