<FIRST>u i AM-Hirohito-Protest 1stLd-Writethru   02-24 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hirohito-Protest, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0694,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Not Everybody Mourned Hirohito's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with palace statement on Philip's
bow to Hirohito; CORRECTS that Payne made comments before church service
and that Smith made comments at church service; CLARIFIES that Dunstan
made comments at church; picks up 14th pvs: In Seoul...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of World War II veterans gathered across
Britain _ some in prayer services, some in pubs _ to remember
comrades killed by Japanese soldiers in the name of Emperor Hirohito.
   In meetings and protests that stretched from Britain to Hong
Kong, South Korea and Japan, some vented their anger at Japan's
wartime leader, and others even celebrated his death.
   Protesters in South Korea burned Japanese flags in two cities,
North Korea denounced Hirohito as an ``inveterate enemy of the
Korean people'' and British veterans in Hong Kong marched with
placards saying ``Hirohito was a war criminal'' and ``Down with
Japanese imperialism.''
   In Britain, elderly ex-soldiers and former prisoners of war held
more than 25 services at war memorials and in churches to coincide
with the emperor's grand state funeral.
   ``Our purpose is to remember those of our colleagues who suffered
as a result of Hirohito's army,'' said Harold Payne, president of
the Far East Prisoner of War Association, whose 68 chapters
organized the services.
   Some veterans were angry that Queen Elizabeth II's husband,
Prince Philip, joined world leaders at ceremonies in Tokyo and that
he made a slight bow of the head at the emperor's coffin and to the
new emperor, Akihito.
   A spokesman for Buckingham Palace said the bow was ``a formal and
entirely usual act of courtesy to a reigning sovereign.''
   But Payne said before a London church service that drew 1,000
people, ``It's also in our minds ... that by all these dignitaries
going to the Far East, the Japanese will think they're exonerated
from blame.''
   At the service, Payne refused to speak to a reporter from the
Japanese Communist Party's newspaper, Akahata, and said he asked the
reporter to leave.
   Many of those taking part were among the 52,000 British and
Australian prisoners held under brutal conditions after the fall of
Singapore in 1942. Many had worked on the ``Death Railway,'' the
supply line between Burma and Thailand whose construction cost
16,000 lives.
   During the service at London's Church of St.
Martin-in-the-Fields, one ex-POW spoke of forgiveness.
   ``If we ... allow bitterness and hatred to dominate our lives it
will lead to self-destruction,'' Maj. Lawrence Smith said.
   But Peter Dunstan, a 68-year-old former Royal Marine who had been
captured in Singapore, said in an interview at the church, ``We're
going to the local pub to celebrate putting that so-and-so six foot
under where he should have been long ago.''
   In Seoul, South Korea, riot police with shields dispersed about
70 protesters who tried to march to the Japanese protests. Police
took 10 marchers into custody. Protesters denounced Hirohito as
``mankind's biggest war criminal'' and burned Japanese flags in
rallies in Seoul and Pusan.
   During 36 years of Japanese rule, allegiance to the emperor was
demanded of all Koreans, who also were ordered to adopt Japanese
names and speak Japanese.
   ``The arch crimes Hirohito had committed against our nation have
not yet been paid off,'' the North Korean government newspaper Minju
Chosun said.
   In Japan, about 5,190 people turned out for 71 anti-emperor
demonstrations across the country, and 12 people were arrested,
National Police Agency spokesman Hiroshi Arakawa said.
   The bitterness comes despite a view generally held by historians
that Hirohito was only a titular leader with little political power.
   Others, while bitter, did not want to think about the emperor
anymore.
   ``No way was this funeral going to overshadow the memory of the
lads,'' said Reginald Dunne, vice president of the national ex-POW
association and organizer of a service attended by 600 in the
northern England city of Blackpool.
</TEXT>
