<FIRST>r w AM-DetroitNewspapers 1stLd-Writethru a0688 02-24 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0688,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Refuses New Hearing in Detroit Newspapers' Partial
Merger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To update, subs graf 2 pvs, bgng ``The decision,'' with vote;
subs graf 6 pvs, bgng ``Attorneys for,'' with opponents' comment; inserts
new grafs 11-14, bgng ``The majority,'' with quotes from opinions; last
2 grafs sub for last graf pvs with Knight-Ridder comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court on Friday refused to
grant a new hearing in the partial merger of two Detroit newspapers
but continued to block the transaction to give opponents a chance
for further appeal.
   The 5-4 decision left the Supreme Court as the only avenue of
appeal for a coalition of newspaper readers and advertisers who have
sought to halt the joint operating agreement between The Detroit
News and the Detroit Free Press.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia rejected a
petition, filed by the 500-member Michigan Citizens for an
Independent Press, for a hearing by the full court.
   A three-judge appeals panel in January had said the newspapers
were entitled to a partial exemption from federal antitrust laws and
could merge business and production departments.
   The court said its stay delaying the partial merger ``shall
remain in effect until 5 p.m. EST on March 6, 1989, to afford
appellants an opportunity to apply to the Supreme Court for a stay
beyond that date.''
   The Washington-based advocacy group Public Citizen, which is
handling the legal work for Michigan Citizens, said opponents would
decide by Wednesday whether to ask the Supreme Court to take the
case. Attorney Bill Schultz said: ``I think the fact that it was 5-4
shows we were right, we had a strong shot.''
   The News, owned by Gannett Co. Inc., and the Free Press, owned by
Knight-Ridder Inc., in 1986 asked permission for the partial merger
in order to keep the Free Press from going out of business.
   Then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III approved the application
last year, and opponents began appeals.
   Under the proposed agreement, Gannett would initially take 55
percent of the joint operation's profits or losses, and after six
years the split would become 50-50 for the next 94 years.
   The newspapers would retain separate news and editorial
departments.
   The majority opinion opposing a rehearing, written by Judge
Laurence Silberman, argued that cost-cutting by the newspapers was
irrelevant to the case.
   ``Congress authorized the attorney general to prevent a city
newspaper editorial monopoly _ even at the risk of a shared economic
monopoly _ because it thought the unusual economics of the newspaper
industry compelled that exception to the antitrust laws,'' Silberman
wrote. ``Otherwise, one newspaper may achieve a stunning fusion of
economic and editorial _ political _ power due to the loss of actual
and potential competition.''
   The dissenting opinion, written by Chief Judge Patricia Wald,
said the attorney general had accepted the premise that one of the
newspapers cut prices to eliminate a rival.
   ``Where ... two independent papers can compete legally and stay
alive, condoning resort by one to pricing which on the record is
hard to distinguish from illegal predatory pricing in order to
secure a monopoly protected by a JOA will, ironically, make it even
more probable that newspapers will disappear,'' Wald wrote.
   ``We have taken another vital step toward knowing there will be a
strong future for this newspaper,'' said Free Press Publisher David
Lawrence. ``We are getting there, but after almost three years of
this process, we will not breathe comfortably until all of this is
finally behind us.
   ``It is time for everybody's lives to go on. I would hope that
everyone, including opponents, would agree enough is enough.''
   ``We are gratified by the decision of the U.S. Court of Appeals
not to rehear the Detroit JOA case,'' James K. Batten, president of
Miami-based Knight-Ridder, said in a statement released in Detroit.
``We will be consulting as soon as possible with our attorneys and
officials at Gannett to plan our next moves.''
   Officials of Arlington, Va.-based Gannett declined to comment on
the court's decision.
</TEXT>
