<FIRST>r a AM-LottoAmerica 1stLd-Writethru a0649 02-24 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lotto America, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0649,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winner Of Record Jackpot Found, But Not Identified</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with winner to be announced Sunday, other
details.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a week after the number for a $16
million lottery was picked, the winner of the multistate contest's
largest jackpot has come forward, lottery officials said Friday.
   The winner, whose name was not disclosed, will appear Sunday at a
news conference in the District of Columbia with the director of the
D.C. lottery, Lotto America officials said.
   The lone winning ticket for the game's largest prize, picked in
the Feb. 18 drawing, was sold at a mini-mart in Washington.
   There was no indication why the winner waited almost a week to
claim the prize.
   It's the first time that anyone outside of Iowa or Kansas has won
the multistate lottery game, which began about a year ago. The
previous record jackpot, $13.6 million, was claimed by a Norwalk,
Iowa, couple in December.
   The winner has one year from the date of the drawing to claim the
prize, said Charles Strutt, executive director of the Multi-State
Lottery Association, which oversees the game. If the $16 million had
remained unclaimed, it would have been divided among the states in
the Lotto America game, according to the percentage of sales in each
place for that jackpot, Strutt said.
   Other states participating in Lotto America are Missouri, Oregon,
West Virginia and Rhode Island.
   The winning numbers were 9, 17, 20, 28, 46 and 50.
   After taxes are withheld, the winner will receive about $600,000
per year for 20 years.
   The estimated jackpot for Saturday night's Lotto America drawing
is $3 million.
</TEXT>
