<FIRST>u a AM-BadBirth     02-24 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bad Birth,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Clear Hospital In Treatment Of 11-Year-Old Pregnant
Girl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital that transferred an
11-year-old girl who was five months pregnant with twins to another
hospital violated no federal or state law, officials said Friday.
   One of the fetuses was stillborn, the other, which weighed 9
ounces, died shortly after it was delivered later that day.
   The case came under investigation when Tallahassee Memorial
Medical Center filed a report, as required by the new state law,
about the transfer.
   Tallahassee Memorial and Tallahassee Community Hospital, which
transfered the girl, disagreed on whether the girl was in labor at
the time.
   Rheb Harbison, a spokesman for Tallahassee Community, said the
case was a ``classic medical nightmare.''
   ``But once you look beyond the shock of it and ask yourself
whether or not appropriate medical care was delivered you would have
to conclude, as both the federal and the state governments have,
that it was,'' he said Friday.
   The child walked into Tallahassee Community on Jan. 9,
accompanied by her grandmother and complaining of indigestion,
Harbison said.
   A doctor determined she was five months pregnant with twins, and
that one of the babies was in a breech position, Harbison said.
   ``She was not in labor when she presented at the hospital but she
was clearly having problems with her pregnancy,'' he said.
   The doctor decided to transfer the child by ambulance to nearby
Tallahassee Memorial. Unlike Tallahassee Community, Tallahassee
Memorial has a specialist in premature births on duty around the
clock, Harbison said.
   The child was upset and did not follow directions to keep her
legs together to prevent her amniotic sac from dropping further, he
said. The doctor put two strips of tape on top of the girl's thighs
to remind her.
   ``In no way whatsoever were her legs immobilized or bound or
wrapped or any other of the descriptions that have been floating
about,'' said Harbison.
   Harbison said his hospital received notification Thursday from
the Health Care Financing Administration that federal investigators
found no evidence that the hospital had violated regulations
prohibiting hospitals from transferring indigent people to other
hospitals for emergency care.
   Federal rules specifically bar hospitals from tranferring women
or girls to another hospital if they are in labor.
   The state Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services also
found no evidence that Tallahassee Community violated a state law
prohibiting hospitals from questionning patients needing emergency
care before deciding treatment, according to Steve Konicki, an HRS
spokesman.
   Ron Brafford, senior vice president at Tallahassee Memorial, said
Friday that officials at his hospital thought the girl was in labor
when she arrived and ``that's what constituted a violation.''
   Community officials acknowledged that the girl should not have
been sent alone in the ambulance for the two-mile trip, and said a
nurse will accompany any patients transferred in the future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
