<FIRST>r i AM-Cuba-HumanRights     02-24 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cuba-Human Rights,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuban Inmates Tell U.N. They Were Tortured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first U.N. human rights report on Cuba,
released Friday, said Cuban prisoners complained of torture but that
Fidel Castro's government denied mistreating them.
   A six-member team that spent 10 days in Cuba in September
compiled the 400-page report and the U.N. Human Rights Commission,
which includes 43 nations, will begin discussing it Tuesday.
   In their report, the investigators said they received more than
1,600 complaints of human rights violations, including 137 of
torture or cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment.
   The torture allegations were in a letter signed by 22 political
prisoners and handed to two U.N. representatives who visited
Combinado del Este prison in Havana.
   It said: ``The Cuban tormentors, advised by experts in political
repression, mainly Russians and Czechs, inflict all kinds of
torture.''
   Gen. Jose Abrantes, Cuba's interior minister, told the U.N.
representatives ``a number of detainees or prisoners had in the past
been beaten'' but those responsible had been punished, their report
said.
   ``He said there are no cases of torture,'' the report said.
   Most of the complaints _ 1,183 _ were from Cubans who declared it
``difficult to leave the country either temporarily or
permanently,'' the investigators reported.
   Cuba has said 20,000 Cubans could leave for the United States
each year under an agreement with Washington. During the first nine
months of 1988 only 5,932 had gone, however, and the report quoted
Vice President Carlos Rafael Rodriguez as blaming U.S.
``non-compliance.''
   Much of the report was devoted to statistics suggesting a great
improvement in education and health care since Castro's revolution
in 1959. It also quoted cultural figures as praising his literacy
campaign and promotion of cultural life.
   Ambassador Alioune Sene of Senegal led the U.N. team, whose other
members were from Bulgaria, Colombia, Ireland, Nigeria and the
Philippines.
   Washington says Cuba and North Korea are the world's worst human
rights offenders, and the United Nations should send investigators
to Cuba once a year as it does with such other countries as Chile,
South Africa and El Salvador.
   Castro's government has said it will not allow another visit.
</TEXT>
