<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Blaze     02-24 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Blaze,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Destroys Half Of Remaining Brazilian Coastal Forest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firemen and volunteers on Friday
battled a 20-day fire that has destroyed tens of thousands of acres
of one of the country's most important wildlife preserves, officials
said.
   Firefighters have been unable to check the blaze, which began as
a series of brush fires throughout the northeastern coastal state of
Bahia, said Leonardo Martins da Rocha of the Brazilian Forestry
Institute. He spoke in a telephone interview from the rural town of
Eunapolis, about 651 miles northeast of Rio.
   ``The situation is extremely serious and worsening,'' said da
Rocha. ``The various fires are joining each other and are burning
day and night.''
   He said the fire, which has destroyed half of Brazil's Atlantic
Forest, has swept through more than 75,000 acres of the virgin
wilderness.
   The cause of the fire is not known. But local farmers often set
fire to their land at this time of the year to renew their pastures
or burn garbage, da Costa said.
   He blamed a two-month drought in the region and a lack of funds
from the Bahia state government for making the task of fighting the
blaze ``more than impossible.''
   ``I just saw two large plantations go up in smoke in a couple of
hours,'' da Costa said. ``We have teams of four trying to contain
the fire in spots because we have no money to work with. What fire
can you stop with four men?''
   Just 3 percent of the once-vast Atlantic Forest, which in the
16th century covered about 170,000 square miles along a 3,000-mile
coastal strip, remains standing today.
   Some of the forest's rare monkeys, birds and trees, many found
nowhere else in the world, face extinction. Among them is the
Pau-Brasil, the tree that gave the country its name.
   Fires also have broken out recently and raged uncontrolled in the
northern Amazon jungle.
   Environmentalists and some scientists have warned that the smoke
is increasing world pollution and contributing to the ``greenhouse
effect,'' or warming of the earth's atmosphere.
</TEXT>
