<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Strike     02-24 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Strike,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon's Central Bank Governor Threatens to Resign, Employees Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central Bank's estimated 750 employees
declared a 24-hour strike Friday in Beirut and other cities to
protest a reported order by Premier Michel Aoun to prosecute bank
Gov. Edmond Naim for misuse of power.
   They threatened to extend the strike indefinitely unless charges
were dropped.
   Naim threatened to resign on Friday over the incident.
   Gen. Aoun, like Naim a Maronite Christian, is head of the
nation's Christian Cabinet.
   Lebanon's official radio said Naim faces charges that include
``misuse of authority, mismanagement and failure to control
manipulation in certain financial institutions.''
   The Central Bank handles the accounts of Lebanon's dual
governments, one headed by Aoun in Christian east Beirut and the
other by Salim Hoss in Moslem west Beirut. The bank was the only
government institution not divided by nearly 14 years of civil
strife.
   Naim told The Associated Press his resignation and those of two
of his deputies would be submitted to the two cabinets ``when the
time comes.''
   ``I don't know why they want to prosecute me. I'm ready to submit
my resignation,'' he said.
   The bank depends on cash flow on whatever income tax, excise and
customs duties the two governments can collect in Lebanon's
war-ravaged economy. Other sources of income include revenue from
government-owned properties, trade in foreign exchange and deposits
by commercial banks.
   Aoun was appointed to head an interim military Cabinet by
outgoing President Amin Gemayel last Sept. 22 after Parliament
failed to elect a new president. Syrian-backed Moslems rejected
Aoun's appointment and declared recognition only of Hoss' incumbent
Cabinet.
</TEXT>
