<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Robbery     02-24 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Robbery,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank Robbed; Caller Claims Leftist Group Responsible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORDOBA, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen robbed a bank of $37,000 on
Friday and wounded a police officer, officials said. A telephone
caller said the robbers were part of a leftist radical group that
attacked an army base last month.
   About six to eight well-dressed men with machine guns burst into
the Bank of Galicia and Buenos Aires in this central Argentine city,
said Luis Ibarra Garcia, a bank spokesmen.
   The robbers made off with about 1 million Argentine australs, he
said.
   The independent news agency Diarios y Noticias said one policeman
was shot and wounded and that one of the assailants was struck on
the head by a guard, then carried away by his companions.
   A man who identified himself as ``Commander Victor'' called the
news agency and said the robbers were part of a group that attacked
an army base last month.
   ``This is the start of the expropriation of funds for the fight
to the final victory,'' the caller was quoted as saying.
   A man who identified himself as ``Victor'' later told Radio
General Paz by telephone the assailants were part of the Popular
Resistance Front, a previously unknown group that claimed
responsibility for the Jan. 23 attack on the La Tablada infantry
regiment outside Buenos Aires.
   Eleven soldiers and police died in retaking the base, along with
28 armed civilians. Thirteen young men and women were arrested at
the scene and are being held in jail with seven others arrested
afterward pending formal presentation of charges, and trial.
   The caller said the group also engaged soldiers in a brief
firefight at an army base in Rio Cuarto, south of Cordoba, earlier
this month, and planned ``to continue the fight until final
victory.''
</TEXT>
