<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Namibia     02-24 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Namibia,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>African Objections Delay Funding of Namibia Peacekeepers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Funding for the Namibia independence plan
was delayed Friday by a last-minute dispute between black African
nations and Western allies over whether the United Nations may buy
goods from South Africa.
   The General Assembly had been scheduled to approve $416 million
for the U.N. peacekeeping force that will guide Namibia to
independence after 74 years of South African rule.
   But the African front-line states insisted on inserting language
into the funding resolution referring to U.N. embargos on buying
military equipment, oil or other goods from South Africa.
   The United States, Britain and France opposed the language,
noting that Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar's report to
the Security Council on Namibia said it would be necessary to
purchase goods and services in southern Africa to keep down the cost
of the mission.
   A key sticking point appeared to be where the United Nations
would purchase $10.2 million worth of gasoline and aviation fuel,
diplomats said.
   The two major sources for such refined products in the region are
South Africa and Angola. Overland supply from South Africa would be
easier and less expensive.
   Since 1984, however, the General Assembly has asked the Security
Council to impose a mandatory oil embargo on South Africa, a measure
that Britain and the United States have vetoed.
   General Assembly resolutions against South Africa are only
advisory; Security Council resolutions are enforceable.
   In 1984, the Security Council passed a resolution calling on all
states not to buy military equipment from South Africa, which by
then had developed a flourishing arms industry with export capacity.
   The African front-line diplomats were also debating Friday
whether the U.N. plan to lease 40 mine-resistant vehicles for a year
at $656,000 would violate the embargo. Some contended that other
purchases, such as trucks, radios and construction materials for the
U.N. peacekeepers' barracks, also should be barred.
   The General Assembly's budgetary committee had not resolved the
issue by late Friday, a necessary step before the whole General
Assembly can vote for funds for the Namibia peacekeeping force.
   On April 1, the United Nations intends to begin implementing a
one-year plan for Namibia's independence under the supervision of
the U.N. Transition Assistance Group.
   The mission will send 4,650 military peacekeepers, 500 police
supervisors, more than 760 civilian U.N. staff, 820 locally hired
staff and 620 election monitors to Namibia, which is also called
South-West Africa.
   If necessary, Perez de Cuellar may dispatch a total of 7,500
troops, but the initial deployment was limited as a cost-cutting
measure at the insistence of the United States, Soviet Union,
Britain, France and China, who together pay 57 percent of all
peacekeeping costs.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since it captured the colony from
Germany during World War I.
   In December, South Africa signed accords with Angola and Cuba
agreeing to free Namibia if 50,000 Cuban troops stationed in Angola
are sent home by mid-1991.
   Angola asked Cuba to send troops to help protect the Marxist
government from cross-border raids by South African troops based in
Namibia, and from a rebellion by the U.S.-backed rebels of UNITA,
the National Union for the Total Liberation of Angola.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
