<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Peacekeeper Killed by Militia; Ireland Protests To Israel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Irish foreign minister telling
Israel saying the killing could damage bilateral ties. Pick up 5th pvs,
``U.N. spokesman...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish U.N. soldier was machine-gunned to
death by the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army on Friday, and
Ireland's foreign minister told an Israeli diplomat the kiling could
damage Israeli-Irish ties.
   In New York, Israeli U.N. Ambassador Johanan Bein ``expressed
regret for the unnecessary death,'' said Israel was investigating
and stressed that the shooting involved only the SLA and not Israeli
troops, Barukh Binah, the Israeli U.N. Mission spokesman, told The
Associated Press.
   Timur Goksel, spokesman for the U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon,
said Pvt. Michael McNeela, 21, was shot in the chest by machine-gun
fire from an SLA position overlooking an Irish post in the southern
Lebanese village of Hadatta.
   ``Death was instantaneous,'' said Goksel. ``The fire was not
provoked.''
   In Dublin, Foreign Minister Brian Lenihan called in the Israeli
charge d'affaires and strongly protested what he called the
``unprovoked killing.''
   ``Mr. Lenihan insisted the incident could not but have a negative
effect on relations with Israel,'' said a spokesman for the Foreign
Affairs Department, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``The Israeli representative expressed regret and undertook to
convey the views of the Irish government to the Israeli
authorities,'' the spokesman said. The Israeli diplomat was not
identified by name.
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said at U.N. Headquarters In New
York that Undersecretary-General Marrack Goulding, in charge of
peacekeeping, summoned Bein ``and protested strongly this incident.''
   Goulding, in a verbal protest, repeated the U.N. position ``that
Israel is responsible for the South Lebanon Army, and we do not
accept the view that the SLA is acting independently.''
   It was a rarely publicized U.N. diplomatic complaint. The United
Nations seldom makes timely announcements of its protests.
   Diplomatic sources at the United Nations, speaking on condition
of anonymity, said the incident appeared to be a mistake and that
the SLA militiaman apparently fired without authorization of his own
superior officer.
   But a statement read by Giuliani said, ``The recent upsurge of
SLA's deliberate and unprovoked firing to UNIFIL positions, mostly
to Irish, has been persistently protested with the Israeli army, but
nothing had come out of these protests.''
   McNeela was on his second tour of duty in Lebanon with the
700-man Irish battalion in the 5,800-member UNIFIL force. He had
planned to marry soon.
   Lars-Eric Wahlgren, commander of the U.N. force, visited the
village later and told reporters: ``I condemn the senseless killing
of one of my soldiers.''
   Most SLA members are Christians. Israel trains and finances the
militia, which helps 1,000 Israeli troops patrol the Jewish state's
self-designated ``security zone'' in southern Lebanon.
   Israel established the eight-to-10 mile zone in 1985 after
withdrawing most of its troops from Lebanon.
   Since the U.N. force was deployed in southern Lebanon in 1978
under a U.N. peacekeeping mandate, 160 peacekeepers have been killed
_ 27 of them Irishmen.
</TEXT>
