<FIRST>r a AM-Nazi-Casino     02-24 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nazi-Casino,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>$1.5 Million Penalty In Imperial Palace Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A casino owner was fined $1.5 million Friday for
displaying Nazi memorabilia and throwing parties on Hitler's
birthday, state gaming officials said.
   The Nevada Gaming Control Board also placed nine conditions on
Imperial Palace owner Ralph Engelstad's gaming license, including
provisions prohibiting such parties and any displays that would
glorify Hitler or Nazi Germany.
   The agency filed a two-count complaint against Engelstad Dec. 8
citing the collection and parties. He also was cited for allegedly
destroying records pertaining to a pending civil lawsuit.
   Engelstad had faced possible license revocation on the various
charges, but gaming officials said they worked out a compromise to
get the controversial issue settled. The agreement included an
apology by Engelstad.
   He refused comment after a two-hour hearing before the state
Gaming Commission.
   Engelstad's attorney, George Dickerson, defended his client's
actions and said they were done in private. But Gaming Control Board
attorney Scott Shearer contended the fine was appropriate because
Engelstad had damaged the reputation of Nevada and its gaming
industry.
   Shearer said the action should be a warning that the gaming board
``cares about Nevada's image and will take swift action,'' including
license revocation if similar circumstances arise with other
licensees.
   The agreement capped weeks of negotiations between Engelstad's
attorneys and the attorney general's office.
   Dickerson defended the Hitler birthday parties on April 20 in
1986 and 1988, saying they were conducted for crews who worked on
the restoration of Nazi-era cars that were to be used in one of
Engelstad's automobile displays.
   He said his case, if it had proceeded before the commission,
would have involved the issues of free speech and right to privacy.
   Engelstad has said previously his actions were in poor taste and
apologized at the time the incidents were made public
   The parties took place in a private room at the Strip resort,
near a collection of antigue cars that is open to the public daily.
   He said he planned to put the multimillion-dollar collection of
Nazi-era memorabilia on public display, and believed it represented
an important chapter in history.
