<FIRST>u a AM-Woolworth'sGuns 1stLd-Writethru a0713 02-24 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Woolworth's Guns, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Officials Wants Woolworth to Stop Gun Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The high ..., to CORRECT spelling of Scondras,
sted Scoundras; SUBS 10th graf, `The M-1 ..., to CORRECT that carbine is
smaller, lighter version of M-1 rifle, sted official rifle of World War
II army.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At F.W. Woolworth Co. in downtown Boston, the
sweaters are on sale, jelly beans are two bags for a dollar and the
gun of the month is an M-1 semi-automatic carbine.
   It's no toy, and City Councilor David Scondras wants the
department store and other stores to stop selling assault weapons.
   ``Woolworth's is viewed as a wholesome American store, every kid
in America knows about Woolworth's,'' Scondras said Friday. ``When
you say it's OK to sell something at Woolworth's then it sends a
message ... It sanctions the buying and selling of assault
weapons,'' he said.
   The high number of gun-related deaths in Boston's neighborhoods
along with the easy availability of assault weapons has led Scondras
and nine other council members to introduce a measure that would
outlaw the sale of assault weapons in the city. The council has 13
members.
   ``It'll be brought to a vote before the end of March. By April
they won't be selling them,'' he said. The measure would not ban
standard handguns.
   Los Angeles and Stockton, Calif., have banned military-style,
semi-automatic assault weapons recently in the aftermath of the
killing of five elementary students in Stockton. Last month, a man
used an assault rifle to spray a schoolyard with 100 bullets within
two minutes.
   Ordinances banning the weapons have also been introduced in New
York, New Orleans and Cleveland, as well as Maryland, Florida and
Wisconsin.
   Robert Giroux, manager of the downtown store who refused to
comment on Scondras' complaints, said several other Woolworth's
stores sell firearms. Telephone calls to the company's New York
headquarters were not returned Friday.
   ``Gun of the Month'' has long been a feature in the Woolworth's
sporting goods department, located across from the children's
section and upstairs from the pet shop, where finches were marked
down below half-price Friday.
   The M-1 carbine, a smaller, lighter version of the .30-caliber
rifle of the U.S. Army in World War II, was on sale for $199.99.
   Scondras also was disturbed by a bolt-action rifle with a bayonet
on display at the store.
   ``You're not going to tell me that when you're selling a bayonet
and a military weapon, and all this military imagery, you're selling
(hunting gear),'' he said. ``You're pushing a fantasy for Rambo.''
   Giroux said the bayonet was removed after the councilor's
complaints were publicized.
   Woolworth's sports department sells fishing gear, bows and
arrows, bowie knives, shotguns and a limited variety of other
rifles, but no handguns.
   Assault weapons ``aren't appealing to recreational sports,
they're appealing to Rambo,'' Scondras said. ``We've been sending
this wrong message for a long time, that you deal with your problems
by blowing away your enemies.''
</TEXT>
