<FIRST>u i AM-Plane-BombThreat 2ndLd-Writethru a0759 02-24 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane-Bomb Threat, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0759,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede HONOLULU</HEAD>
<HEAD>Radio Station Received Airplane Bomb Threat, Japan Discounts Theory</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Plane Emergency</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Japanese police discounting possibility
Japanese group was involved, background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man called a Honolulu radio station last month
threatening to bomb an American plane unless a jailed member of the
Japanese Red Army was released by Friday, a station spokesman said.
Japanese police said the terrorist group probably would not attack
an American target.
   Danny Oshita, general manager of the radio station KOHO, said the
caller on Jan. 23 demanded the freedom of Osamu Maruoka and asked
that the message be relayed to the Japanese Consulate in Honolulu.
The caller, who spoke in Japanese, hung up without identifying
himself.
   Oshita said he relayed the message to the consulate and later was
interviewed by the FBI.
   U.S. investigators said there was no indication that a bomb
caused the hole in the fuselage of United Airlines Flight 811, which
made an emergency landing in Honolulu after nine people were sucked
out of the plane and killed.
   In Tokyo, a senior National Police Agency official said Saturday
it was ``not realistic to assume the Japanese Red Army was
responsible'' for the incident.
   Police here said last month they feared the Lebanon-based
Japanese Red Army might attack Japanese embassies abroad to disrupt
the funeral Friday of Emperor Hirohito or to press for the release
of Maruoka and Hiroshi Sensui, another Red Army member detained in
Japan.
   Maruoka was arrested last November. He was wanted in connection
with a 1972 attack at Israel's Lod Airport in which 26 people were
killed, and the hijacking of a jetliner over India in 1977.
   The Japanese official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
that if the Japanese Red Army wanted to pressure the Tokyo
government, it probably would have chosen a target more closely
related to Japan and the Japanese people than an American aircraft
flying from Hawaii to New Zealand.
   He also said that if the plane was bombed, ``I don't think (the
Japanese Red Army) would actually explode the bomb so easily. ...
Once it explodes, they can't use it for bargaining any more.''
   He said Japanese authorities were aware of the threat to the
Hawaiian radio station.
