<FIRST>u n AM-Son-ParentalShooting     02-24 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Son-Parental Shooting,2nd Ld-Writethru, a0809, a0822,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with additonal detail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASPEN HILL, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old boy was in custody Friday
night in connection with the fatal shooting of his mother and the
wounding of his father in their home, police said.
   The boy, Matthew Nupp, had apparently gotten into trouble earlier
in the day at school in this Washington, D,C., suburb and argued
with his mother, Evelyn, before she was shot three times with a .22
caliber rifle, police said.
   Moments later, the boy's father, James T. Nupp, returned home
early from his job as a medical researcher and was also shot, police
said. He managed to call police before staggering outside and
collapsing, they said. Nupp was shot three times and was listed in
fair condition at Suburban Hospital.
   When James Nupp entered the home through the back door, he was
unaware that his wife had been shot, said police spokesman Harry
Geehreng. Nupp then saw his wife's body on the kitchen floor and his
son, holding the rifle and standing in a nearby basement stairwell.
   The boy opened fire from the stairwell and continued shooting as
he followed his father through the kitchen and outside on the back
porch, Geehreng said.
   Mrs. Nupp was apparently cooking dinner when the shooting
occurred.
   Two other Nupp children, a 7-year-old boy and a 3-year-old, were
in the home at the time of the shooting, police said.
   When police arrived, Matthew Nupp was in the basement, but he
came out the back door without the gun and surrendered, police said.
   Matthew Nupp was being questioned, but had not yet been charged.
One unanswered question was whether he would be charged an adult
with murder or handled as a juvenile.
   The family kept three guns in the house, but James Nupp told
police he believed all the weapons had been locked in the attic.
