<HEAD>Six Americans Among Those Missing From Flight 811</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nine passengers identified as missing after a hole opened in
a United Airlines jumbo jet over the Pacific Ocean on Friday
included six Americans, the airline said.
   Two of the missing, Susan and Harry Craig of Morristown, N.J.,
were on their way to New Zealand for a vacation, said their daughter
Carolyn Craig.
   ``It was like a second honeymoon for them,'' she said. The couple
had been married 23 years.
   Craig, 42, and his wife, 41, were managers for AT&amp;T, their
daughter said. She added that United was flying her and two other
relatives to Hawaii on Saturday.
   Also among the missing was Mary T. Handley of Bay City, Mich.,
owner of Handley and Associates Inc., which offered the Dale
Carnegie personal improvement course.
   The other Americans missing were Anthony Fallon and Barbara
Fallon of Long Beach, Calif., and Rose Harley of Hackensack, N.J.
