<FIRST>u i AM-BushRdp 5thLd-Writethru a0831 02-24 1210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush Rdp, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0831,1,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Wraps Up Tokyo Visit; Looks Forward to Stop in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with Bush departure from Tokyo.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, his visit to Asia distracted by the
imperiled nomination of Defense Secretary-designate John Tower, bade
farewell to Japan's new emperor Saturday and said his introductory
talks with foreign leaders ``laid some good groundwork'' for
maintaining global peace.
   Bush and his wife, Barbara, left Tokyo's Haneda Airport aboard
Air Force One, on a more than four-hour flight to Beijing, at
midday. A heavy rain fell as the Boeing-707 jet took off. Bush was
looking forward to a nostalgic return to his former diplomatic post
in China. But first he grappled with questions concerning Tower and
summed up his two days in Japan.
   ``Throughout all of our disscussions ... I found a shared sense
of satisfaction ... that East-West relations are now clearly
proceeding on the basis of an agenda favorable to the United States,
its allies, its friends,'' Bush told reporters.
   In discussions with Middle Eastern and European leaders, as well
as leaders of third-world nations such as Pakistan, Bush said,
``We've laid some good groundwork here.. ... and that will help us
as we go down the road.''
   Bush also said that during his trip to China, he will bring up
human rights, but said he has no specific cases to press with his
hosts. The president revealed that he will will meet in Beijing, as
well, with Cambodian resistance leader Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   Bush said the United States believes that Sihanouk should head an
interim government once Vietnamese troops complete their pullout of
forces from Cambodia later this year. He also reiterated American
opposition to a return to power by the Chinese-supported Khmer Rouge.
   He defended Tower again in his session with reporters, saying he
had no ``fallback'' planned except to lobby strongly with ``whoever
has an open mind on the subject.'' The Senate will take up the Tower
nomination shortly after Bush's return from Asia next week.
   Bush was arriving in China at mid-day Beijing time, 3:30 a.m. EST
Washington time.
   ``Both countries have come so far since my stay in China,'' Bush
said in written responses to questions posed by Xinhua, the Chinese
news agency. The remarks were released by the White House as Bush
prepared to leave for Beijing.
   Bush said the world remained ``a tumultuous, dangerous place,''
but said he was optimistic. ``I would say that any man with 11
grandchildren is a cautious optimist by definition. He has a big
stake in the future.''
   On China, Bush conceded that the United States ``has some big
differences'' with Beijing on some issues, but said he wanted to
travel there to show the Chinese leaders that he will never take
them for granted.
   Bush also said that ``we've passed the day'' of confining
Sino-American relations to discussions limited to America's security
interests alone. ``The relationship's strong and I'd like to
strengthen it,'' he said.
   Although Bush's Asian tour so far has been distracted by the
burgeoning battle with Congress over Tower, the president earlier
sought to stress the primary reason for his visit to Japan _ Emperor
Hirohito's funeral.
   During his nearly half-hour exchange with reporters gathered in
the U.S. ambassador's residence here, the president also:
   _He and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan have ``a little
difference of interpretation'' of economic indicators relating to
inflation. Bush said that he does not like seeing interest rates
raised _ as the Fed did in Washington Friday _ and said he believes
there will be less pressure on interest rates if he and Congress
agree on a fiscal 1990 budget that meets the $100 billion
deficit-reduction target.
   _Said that in his talks with Mideast leaders, he ``made clear the
continuing readiness'' of the United States to ``facilitate this
process'' in a way is consistent with Israel's security interests
and ``positive developments'' in the Arab world. Bush has kept open
the low-level contacts that then-President Ronald Reagan established
with the Palestine Liberation Organization late last year.
   _Admitted that while attending the funeral services for Emperor
Hirohito, he had thoughts of his shooting down over the Pacific by
the Japanese during World War II, but said that he ``didn't dwell on
that at all.''
   `` ... Perhaps having been in combat in World War II, maybe the
decision (to come to Tokyo) was more correct,'' he said. ``Maybe it
was more profound to be here. I'm representing the United States of
America. We're talking about a friend. We're talking about an ally.''
   He said the Hirohito funeral was ``beautifully staged and
beautifully carried out.''
   Bush met briefly at the Imperial Palace with Japan's new emperor,
Akihito, before sitting down separately with Presidents Jose Sarney
of Brazil and Ibrahim Babangida of Nigeria, bringing to 20 the
number of foreign leaders he has met with in two days of fast-paced
diplomacy here.
   In his remarks to the Chinese news agency, Bush declared that
``the one constant in today's world is change. For the most part,
the direction of change is positive from the standpoint of America's
values and interests.''
   ``Let me say that I certainly agree that the current state of our
relationship is healthy,'' he said.
   He vowed to work for increased trade with China and pledged ``to
keep up the dialogue between our two governments on political issues
of mutual concern,'' which Bush listed as global peace, easing of
regional conflicts, arms control, and combating drugs, terrorism and
threats to the environment.
   He said the United States hoped that a recent easing of tensions
between Taiwan and China could be accelerated. But he said the
United States remains committed to keeping troops in South Korea,
which he will visit on Monday on his way home to Washington.
   ``It would be far too optimistic, at this point, where the
deterrence provided by U.S. forces in Korea is no longer needed,''
he said.
   During his two days in Beijing, Bush is slated to hold one-on-one
sessions with the nation's top four leaders, discuss matters ranging
from Taiwan to trade, and even host a Texas-style barbecue.
   In Bush's meeting with Philippine President Aquino, he vowed
continued strong support for a proposed $200 million in aid to the
Pacific nation contained in budgets submitted by both himself and
former President Reagan, Fitzwater said.
   Bush also ``reiterated U.S. support for her government and for
democracy in that country,'' Fitzwater said.
   Bush also met with Singapore Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew, Belgian
King Baudouin, Turkish Prime Minister Turgut Ozal, Pakistani Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto, Italian President Francesco Cossiga.
   In addition, the president and his wife had dinner with King Juan
Carlos of Spain and his queen, Sophia.
   Meanwhile, Baker held a separate session Friday with Japanese
Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno that included a discussion of a
controversial proposed joint venture to build the FSX jet aircraft.
   Although the Reagan administration approved the agreement for
Japanese-U.S. construction on a new version of the F-16 fighter, the
Bush administration is reassessing the proposal.
   According to Yukio Okamato, an official with the Japanese foreign
ministry, Uno voiced hope ``for a smooth implementation of the
agreement as soon as possible.''
</TEXT>
