<DOCNO> AP890224-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0849EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:SingleSpies Adv07   02-24 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Single Spies, Adv 07,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, March 7 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Singularly Royal Appeal of ``Single Spies''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Midway through ``A Question of Attribution,'' a
sudden hush falls over the audience. The unthinkable, it seems, has
happened: Queen Elizabeth II has walked on stage.
   In fact, Her Majesty is actress Prunella Scales. But given the
public awe in which the queen is held, turning her into a stage
character is a daring ploy, unprecedented in mainstream British
theater.
   ``A Question of Attribution,'' with ``An Englishman Abroad,'' are
two plays by Alan Bennett which, under the combined title ``Single
Spies,'' have been a sellout since opening Dec. 1 at the
government-subsidized National Theater. The show reopens Feb. 28 for
a commercial run at, appropriately enough, the Queen's Theater.
   Bennett plays Anthony Blunt, the erstwhile spy who worked as
Surveyor of the Queen's Pictures, and he is seen rearranging
paintings in the Queen's Gallery at Buckingham Palace when the
monarch unexpectedly appears.
   ``If you don't believe it's her, you can't suspend your
disbelief,'' said Scales, 56. ``It gives one an extraordinary sense
of power on stage because of the way they (the audience) listen.''
   For there, capturing the queen's diction, bearing and demeanor,
is the diminutive actress best-known as long-suffering Sybil Fawlty
opposite John Cleese on the TV's wonderful ``Fawlty Towers,'' and
the conniving Miss Mapp in ``Mapp and Lucia,'' based on the E.F.
Benson novels.
   Scales admires Bennett's ``very cheeky bit of writing,'' but said
she was determined not to caricature the queen.
   ``There are lots of people jolly good at imitating the queen
rather better than me,'' she said. ``I thought it frightfully
important that (the portrayal) be as real as possible.''
   This Elizabeth is drily and slyly witty, every bit the softspoken
match for the singular spy in her midst.
   Blunt was unmasked in 1964 as a spy, the so-called ``fourth man''
alongside Kim Philby, Guy Burgess and Donald Maclean, all Cambridge
University classmates in the 1930s. In return for making a secret
confession to his interrogators, he was spared punishment and public
exposure, kept his job as the queen's art adviser and retired
honorably in 1972. In 1979, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
publicly named him a spy, whereupon he was stripped of his
knighthood. He died in 1983.
   It's not known whether the queen ever knew she was employing a
traitor, but Bennett's play subtly hints that she can detect human
forgeries as cannily as Blunt detects fake pictures.
   After ``40 Years On,'' with John Gielgud as a schoolmaster, and
the screenplays for two low-budget triumphs, ``A Private Function''
and ``Prick Up Your Ears,'' ``Single Spies'' confirms Bennett's
stature in the top rank of British writers.
   Meanwhile, TV viewers are being treated to a rerun of his
``Talking Heads,'' a remarkable series of monologues including
Maggie Smith playing an alcoholic wife of a vicar, and Bennett's own
devastating portrayal of a mentally disturbed middle-aged man.
   Bennett has used treason before to explore the English psyche in
``The Old Country,'' which cast Alec Guinness as an English defector
living in Moscow. ``An Englishman Abroad'' was first seen as a 1984
teleplay portraying the wretched life of another traitor, Guy
Burgess, in exile in Moscow.
   It depicts an episode in which Coral Browne, playing in
``Hamlet'' in Moscow, is visited backstage by Burgess, the drunk and
maudlin ``Englishman Abroad.''
   In the latest production, Scales plays Browne, while Simon Callow
is Burgess.
   Scales said both plays were ``about martyrdom, about people who
suffer for their convictions,'' and stressed that playing Coral
Browne offered distinct, but equal, challenges to playing the queen.
   ``With the Queen, you've got the tapes, the broadcasts and
everything,'' said Scales. ``I wish Coral Browne were as
well-documented.''
   Browne, 75, who starred most recently in the movie
``Dreamchild,'' saw ``Single Spies'' on its opening night. The
queen, to date, has no plans for a visit.
   Felicity Murgo-Smith, a Palace spokeswoman, said: ``I can't
possibly tell you whether she's seen it; we have no notes of her
private visits. The queen takes a great interest in what's going on
in this country.''
   Murgo-Smith said no permission was necessary for Bennett, or
anyone else, to put the Royal Family on-stage: ``Stage censorship in
this country finished some time back,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
