<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-24 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0904</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major banks said they were raising their
prime rate half a percentage point to 11.5 percent, the second
increase in two weeks, lifting the benchmark interest rate to its
highest level since November 1984.
   Chase Manhattan Corp. announced first Thursday and was quickly
followed by Republic National Bank of New York. Economists said they
expected other major banks to follow suit Friday.
   The increases are effective Friday. The prime rate is a benchmark
for a wide range of business and consumer loan rates, including car
loans and adjustable-rate home mortgages.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to factories for ``big ticket'' durable
goods dropped 3 percent in January, the government said in a report
that some analysts said could portend a welcome slowdown in economic
growth.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that total orders fell $4
billion to a seasonally adjusted $128.06 billion last month, pulled
down by sharp declines in the volatile transportation and defense
sectors.
   Virtually all other major industrial categories were down as well.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan,
saying a separately regulated thrift industry may not be needed in
the future, told Congress that the Fed will make it easier for bank
holding companies to buy troubled savings and loans.
   Greenspan also said Thursday that the central bank and the
Treasury Department have arranged to support the Federal Home Loan
Bank system in the event of runs on S&amp;Ls.
   The Fed chairman's comments came as opposition to President
Bush's S&amp;L proposal grew among members of Congress fighting to
preserve a separate S&amp;L industry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farley Inc. won a four-month battle for West
Point-Pepperell Inc. as the textile giant accepted a sweetened $3
billion buyout offer from the Chicago-based conglomerate.
   Pepperell and Farley said Thursday that Farley would pay $58 a
share in cash for Pepperell's outstanding stock and refinance
Pepperell's debt. The entire transaction would cost Farley $3
billion.
   Farley will contribute about $300 million in equity, with the
remainder being financed by $1.6 billion in high-risk, high-yield
``junk'' bonds and $1.2 billion in bank loans.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said it plans to replace an aging
Detroit assembly plant with a new $1 billion factory that will make
a new sport-utility vehicle beginning in 1992, betting that demand
for such vehicles will continue growing into the next decade.
   The vehicle, code-named the ``ZJ,'' will be available from Jeep
and Dodge dealers and will be the first sport-utility vehicle
carrying the Dodge nameplate, Chrysler said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mid-February sales of U.S.-based companies' cars
and light trucks rose 1.7 percent from year-earlier levels as the
effects of sales incentives available in early 1988 began to wear
off, the automakers reported.
   The eight automakers said Thursday that they sold cars and light
trucks at an average daily rate of 36,769 during the Feb. 11-20
period this year, compared with a daily rate of 35,158 during the
same time last year.
   The overall sales rate during the period was bolstered by a 5.4
percent increase in truck sales, which offset a 0.3 percent decline
in car sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor leaders staged a rowdy show of support for
Machinists planning to strike Eastern Airlines, receiving a boost
from the airline's pilots while predicting President Bush would
intervene to stop a walkout.
   The AFL-CIO Executive Council joined members of the Machinists
and other unions at the rally Thursday at Eastern's headquarters.
   The labor leaders predicted they would mount a unified front and
stall air travel and cargo if the 8,500 machinists and ground
personnel strike Eastern as planned March 4.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. announced it is ready to
implement the cornerstone of its restructuring plans with a rollback
of prices on more than 1.5 billion pieces of merchandise.
   The nation's largest retailer said Thursday it would close its
825 Sears stores for 42 hours next week _ from 6 p.m. Monday until
noon Wednesday _ to change the prices marked on clothes, hardware,
appliances, furniture and other items to conform with its new
``everyday low price'' strategy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Those soulful, animated dancing raisins have been
taking their bows for the California raisin industry for about 2{
years, but television viewers apparently still love them.
   The California raisin commercials led Video Storyboard Tests
Inc.'s annual list of most popular ad campaigns in 1988 for the
second consecutive year.
   The campaigns for Pepsi and Diet Pepsi, including a four-part ad
starring singer Michael Jackson and an ad with actor Michael J. Fox
trying to avoid a watchdog blocking the way to the soda machine,
placed second.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market eked out a small gain Thursday, steadying after
Wednesday's sharp drop. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
gained 5.53 points at 2,289.46.
   The dollar slipped lower as pessimism about the U.S. budget and
trade deficits weighed on the foreign-exchange markets. Gold prices
rose.
   Bond prices fell and short-term interest rates jumped.
   Renewed fears of inflation gave gold futures prices another lift.
Grain, livestock and energy futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
