<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0232EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PopularAds Bjt   02-24 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Popular Ads, Bjt,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Rates California Raisin Ads As Most Popular Of 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television viewers rated the California raisin
industry's soulful animated commercials the best TV ads of 1988 for
the second consecutive year, but failed to spot any advertising
breakthroughs, a survey found.
   Dave Vadehra, president of the research firm Video Storyboard
Tests Inc., said Thursday that the most popular ads last year also
demonstrated a heavy reliance on safe standbys such as children and
dogs.
   Video Storyboard's 11th annual list of outstanding ad campaigns
put in second place the commercials for Pepsi and Diet Pepsi,
including a four-part ad starring singer Michael Jackson and an ad
with actor Michael J. Fox trying to avoid a watchdog blocking the
way to the soda machine.
   Ads for McDonald's restaurants ranked third. McDonald's spent an
estimated $386 million airing its commercials compared with $6.8
million spent by the California raisin industry.
   Vadehra blamed the lack of advertising breakthroughs on the
merger mania that has seen huge advertisers swallowed up in takeover
deals and advertising agencies consolidate after a massive
restructuring within that business.
   ``Nobody is taking any risks. Everybody is trying to play it
safe,'' Vadehra said.
   Richard Karp, director of creative services at Grey Advertising,
agreed that mergers unsettled the ad business last year, distracting
some advertisers while some ad agency people ``focused less on work
than on their security.''
   In a telephone interview from Los Angeles where he is judging
entries in an ad awards show, Karp said he found ``there were a lot
of safe hits and not a lot of home runs last year.''
   Video Storyboards compiled its ranking based on responses from
24,000 people who were asked periodically over the past year to name
the most outstanding television commercial they have seen in the
past four weeks.
   The California Raisin Advisory Board aired its first commercials
that use clay models of raisins, which appear to dance and sing to
``Heard It Through the Grapevine,'' in September 1986.
   The ads helped boost raisin sales and created a market for
licensed products ranging from raisin shirts to a raisin board game.
   Robert Phinney of the raisin board said sales of products
licensed to use the raisin characters amounted to $500 million last
year, just short of the industry's $600 million in sales of the real
thing.
   In 1988, the board aired a commercial featuring an animated Ray
Charles singing with the raisins. New spots are planned for this
fall.
   Phinney said the raisin ads remain popular because the characters
are depicted as entertainers rather than pitchmen. ``We have been
very conscious of not making them salesmen,'' he said.
   Vadehra said the California raisin industry also got credit from
some consumers for ads others did using the raisin characters.
   He said some consumers thought ads for Post Raisin Bran cereal
and Hardee's fast-food restuarants, which each have been licensed to
use the characters in their ads, were commercials for California
raisins.
   Ranked fourth behind the California raisins, Pepsi and McDonald's
campaigns were Bud Light beer ads. Vadehra said consumers cited ads
featuring the Bud Light spokesdog Spuds MacKenzie three times as
often as the ads that show amazing things that can happen when you
order a ``light'' beer.
   In fifth place were ads for Isuzu cars and light trucks featuring
the fictional lying pitchman Joe Isuzu, another campaign introduced
in 1986 and steadily gaining popularity.
   Miller Lite beer ads ranked sixth, followed by Coca-Cola soft
drinks, Stroh's beer spots featuring Alex the dog, Wendy's fast food
restaurants and Levi's jeans.
   Ads by the Partnership for a Drug-Free America, the industry's
volunteer anti-drug campaign, placed 11th. The group's trademark ad
is a raw egg dropped into a sizzling frying pan, meant to symbolize
the effect of drugs on the brain.
   Falling out of the top 10 campaigns were ads for Bartles &amp; Jaymes
wine coolers and DuPont Stainmaster carpets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Pepperell-Glance     02-24 0124</FIRST>
