<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Pepperell Bjt   02-24 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pepperell, Bjt,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farley Promises No Production Layoffs At Pepperell</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Farley promises no production layoffs and
a reinvigorated company when he assumes control of textile giant
West Point-Pepperell Inc. within the next few weeks after a bitter
takeover fight.
   Farley, chairman of Farley Inc. of Chicago, won the company
Thursday when the Pepperell board of directors unanimously agreed to
his $58-per-share tender offer. The deal, when combined with
required refinancing of Pepperell debt, totals about $3 billion.
   The buyout will be financed with $300 million in equity from
Farley, $1.6 billion in high-yield, or ``junk,'' bonds sold by
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., and $1.2 billion in bank loans.
   Farley Inc. is one of the nation's largest privately controled
conglomerates. Its holdings include Fruit of the Loom Inc., the
nation's No. 1 underwear manufacturer; Acme Boot Co., which sell
Dingo and Acmes boots; and Doehler-Jarvis, which makes die-cast
metal products for the automotive industry.
   William Farley predicted that Pepperell, with increased
advertising and tighter management, could match Fruit of the Loom's
25 percent growth in the three years he has owned the company.
   Farley went out of his way Thursday to compliment Pepperell
employees.
   ``We know we cannot build a first-rate company without first-rate
employees, and I want to commend the men and women who work for West
Point-Pepperell,'' he said in a statement.
   The businessman has been the target of much criticism in the west
Georgia and east Alabama communities where Pepperell is the
principal employer.
   However, Farley told reporters in Atlanta he held no bitterness
toward the employees or management, including Chairman Joseph L.
Lanier Jr., who led the at-times bitter fight against Farley.
   ``I think Joe Lanier did not want Bill Farley to run West
Point-Pepperell and I understand that. He's fourth generation,''
Farley said, referring to Lanier's family ties to the West Point,
Ga.-based company.
   But Farley noted that Lanier apparently joined in a unanimous
decision by Pepperell's board to accept the offer.
   Farley said Lanier and President Donald Keller will leave the
company once the merger is complete, in about 30 days.
   Pepperell officials did not return phone calls Thursday, but
issued a joint statement with Farley saying directors ``determined
that the terms of the offer and the merger are fair'' to
shareholders.
   One of management's criticisms of Farley's offer was a fear he
would sell parts of the company to pay down the debt.
   Farley said Thursday, ``I love all the company and I haven't made
any decision on what part, if any, I would sell.''
   However, he later identified Saturday's, a high-fashion line
produced by Pepperell subsidiary Cluett-Peabody, as a likely
candidate to be sold.
   The companies said they agreed to cancel a special shareholders
meeting set for March 2. The meeting had been called at Farley's
request in a bid to unseat the Pepperell directors and replace them
with a board more sympathetic to the conglomerate's bid.
   Farley said his bid beat out ``two or three'' competing offers,
including one from management. He said he did not know the size of
the management offer.
   Farley fired the first shot in the battle for Pepperell last May,
when it notified the Pepperell it was seeking to buy up to 25
percent of its stock.
   However, Farley never reached that level, stopping at 9.8
percent, or 2.9 million shares, in order to prevent management from
activating so-called ``poison pills'' that would make a takeover
much more expensive. Those options do not become available until a
bidder acquires 10 percent of Pepperell stock.
   Instead, on Oct. 24, Farley initiated a hostile tender offer that
resulted in lawsuits and countersuits, as actions by state
legislators and U.S. congressmen, and television and newspaper
advertisements highly critical of the combatants.
   Farley's initial offer, $48 per share, later was increased to $52
per share. Farley said Thursday he had upped the ante to $56 after
the board put the company up for sale in an attempt to avoid a
Farley takeover.
   Pepperell, founded in 1886, became the nation's largest publicly
traded textile company last year through its $1.22 billion
acquisition of most of J.P. Stevens &amp; Co. Inc. Its latest quarterly
financial statement said the company had $994.6 million in long-term
debt.
   Pepperell has 41,000 employees and 22,000 stockholders.
   For the fiscal year ended Sept. 24, the company reported a profit
of $84.4 million on revenue of $2.15 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
