<DOCNO> AP890224-0236 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0738EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PublicistOnslaught     02-24 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Publicist Onslaught,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>From Mortuaries To Yogi Bear, Publicists Take All Comers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't hang up so fast! This will make a
fabulous story _ I promise. We're gonna give you an exclusive
one-on-one interview with the new voice for Yogi Bear. Hey, you
still there?
   Journalists nationwide are bracing for calls like this. It seems
everybody has a publicist these days _ and bold press agents are
frantically working phones and fax machines to give their clients an
edge over the competition.
   Plastic surgeons, a mortuary, the Bulgarian film industry, a
psychologist, a doughnut shop and even Yogi's new voice now claim
publicists.
   In Los Angeles, the nation's second-largest media market,
publicity is proving to be as important and often more economical
than normal promotions.
   Public relations wiz Michael Levine finds that ``for every ad
inch, an editorial inch is worth about 10 times the amount.''
   ``Public relations no longer belongs to just the big people,''
said publicist Debra Gold, who promotes local community-involvement
stories on behalf of Burbank's Valley Funeral Home. ``For small
businesses, public relations is so much more cost-efficient than
advertising.''
   The boom in smaller, regional publicity operations reflects a
national trend. Industry giant Hill and Knowlton collected fees of
$114.5 million in 1987, up 14.3 percent from 1986. Rival firm
Burson-Marsteller claimed revenue of $148.7 million in 1988, up 17.6
percent from 1987 billings of $126.4 million.
   Press releases and announcements herald the successes of the
Venetian blind, the California Raisins, law firms, hospitals and the
Beverly Hills High School.
   Joe Molina, whose JMPR firm stumps for Budget Rent-A-Car of
Beverly Hills, which specializes in exotic vehicles, estimates that
on annual public relations billings of $70,000, JMPR has delivered
up to $7 million worth of promotion for the rental agency.
   ``The media has generated constant word of mouth'' for the
franchise, Molina said, claiming story placement in Forbes, Newsweek
and the television shows ``PM Magazine,'' ``Today'' and ``Good
Morning America.''
   ``We built them (Budget) into something they wouldn't be
otherwise,'' Molina said.
   Charging from a few hundred to several thousand dollars a month,
press agents try to build a specific image for a customer, which
some clients believe advertisements can't always do.
   ``You can't be credible today without being visible,'' said
Levine, whose firm plugs the likes of Charlton Heston, Designer
Donuts and Tommy Tang, a local Thai restaurateur. ``With Tommy,
we're trying to establish a chef as a star ... in the (renowned Los
Angeles chef) Wolfgang Puck-type situation.''
   Publicist Levine himself has a publicist _ who promotes Levine's
``The Address Book,'' an index to help the star-struck find the
stars.
   Then there's mansion seller Mike Silverman and his publicist,
Jane Harman.
   Harman boasts that Silverman, one of Beverly Hills' most
successful and visible real estate brokers, has been featured on
``60 Minutes,'' ``USA Today: The TV Show,'' the Cable News Network
and in the Los Angeles Times, The New York Times, USA Today,
Interview magazine and The Associated Press.
   The media exposure, she said, is aimed at making Silverman as
large a star as his bigwig home buyers, who include Zsa Zsa Gabor
and Kenny Rogers.
   ``A celebrity name is a very important commodity to people who
have the money to buy these kinds of houses,'' Harman said. ``My
primary goal ... is that he be seen as the ultimate realtor to the
celebrities.''
   News stories establish ``a mystique (and) the glamor. I think
we've been terribly successful with him _ but Mike has really made
his reputation on his own,'' Harman said.
   Some publicists can be a nuisance, but others can be invaluable,
especially when Hollywood celebrities land in the hospital.
   Ron Wise, a former entertainment critic for Daily Variety, heads
public relations and marketing at the 1,120-bed Cedars-Sinai Medical
Center. The hospital is where most of the city's movers and shakers
go for hospitalization _ for instance, Debra Winger and Diana Ross
delivered children there.
   Gary Busey, injured in a motorcycle accident in December, became
Wise's responsibility as soon the actor was wheeled into
Cedars-Sinai. For three days, Wise didn't sleep, fielding more than
50 calls about Busey and conducting several live radio interviews
each day.
   Wise also uses public relations, not advertising, to stress that
Cedars-Sinai is ``not a medical country club for the rich and
famous.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales     02-24 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Truck Performance Push Up Vehicle Sales by 1.7 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong truck sales by U.S.-based automakers pushed
mid-February sales of cars and light trucks up 1.7 percent over a
year ago as comparisons of sales figures became less clouded by
incentives.
   Cars and light trucks made by the eight companies sold at an
average daily rate of 36,769 during the Feb. 11-20 period this year,
compared with a rate of 35,158 the same time last year, the
automakers reported Thursday.
   There were eight selling days during the period this year and
nine last year.
   ``There's nothing alarming one way or another,'' said Jeannette
Garretty, an auto analyst with Bank of America in San Francisco.
``It will probably mean that when the incentives come back, they
will not be drastic ones.''
   Sales early last year were heavily influenced by incentives such
as cash rebates and low financing deals. Incentives are in effect on
some cars and trucks this year, but they are being offered on a
narrower range of vehicles.
   The overall sales rate was bolstered by a 5.4 percent increase in
truck sales, offsetting a 0.3 percent decline in car sales.
   Although truck sales were significantly higher this year over
last year, the ratio of car-to-truck sales stayed virtually the same
during both periods. Light truck sales make up slightly more than 36
percent of all vehicles sold both years.
   For the year, car and truck sales by domestic producers fell 3.2
percent, to a daily rate of 32,334 in 1989, compared with a 33,412
daily rate last year. There were 42 selling days between Jan. 1 and
Feb. 20 this year, one fewer than during the same time last year.
   Cars made by domestic companies were selling at a rate 6.3
percent lower this year than last year, and truck sales have risen
1.5 percent.
   Chrysler Corp. showed a big dip in mid-February car sales,
falling 18.5 percent during the period this year compared with last.
The nation's No. 3 automaker said its average daily sales rate for
cars fell to 2,960 during mid-February this year compared with a
3,630 rate during the same time last year. Car sales for 1989 at
Chrysler were 15.1 percent below the rate through mid-February last
year.
   Chrysler's truck sales rose 7.1 percent during the period this
year compared with last year, going to a daily rate of 3,105
compared with a 2,899 daily rate last year.
   General Motors Corp.'s car sales fell 1.2 percent during
mid-February, dropping to a daily rate of 11,714 this year compared
with an 11,852 rate during the period last year. For the year, the
leading automaker's car sales are 11.8 percent lower this year than
last year.
   GM reported a 3.3 percent gain in truck sales during the period
this year over last year, rising to a daily rate of 5,169 from a
rate of 5,006.
   Ford Motor Co. said its car sales rose 1.6 percent in
mid-February this year over last year, going to a daily rate of
6,833 compared with a rate of 6,727 last year. The No. 2 automaker's
annual car sales are running 0.4 percent ahead of car sales to date
last year, rising to a daily average of 6,441 from 6,415.
   Ford said it sold an average of 4,798 trucks during the period
this year, up 4.2 percent from its daily rate of 4,604 last year.
</TEXT>
