<DOCNO> AP890224-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1020EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Emhart-Topper 1stLd-Writethru f0053 02-24 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emhart-Topper, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0053,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>Partnership Makes $2.4 Billion Bid For Emhart</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, ``We have ..., with two grafs to UPDATE with
latest Emhart statement. Picks up 4th graf pvs, Topper offered ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group that includes oil
tycoon Gordon P. Getty says its $2.4 billion cash bid for Emhart
Corp. is friendly and it wants to meet with management soon to
discuss the proposal.
   But Emhart officials have said little since late Thursday's
surprise offer from New York-based Topper Acquisition Corp.
   ``Emhart's board of directors will carefully study the offer in
consultation with its outside legal and financial advisers,'' said
Peter L. Scott, Emhart chairman and chief executive officer.
   ``After completing this evaluation, the board will promptly
announce its conclusion and recommendation,'' he said. ``Prior to
that time, we strongly urge Emhart shareholders not to take any
action with respect to the offer.'' Topper offered $35 per share in
cash for all outstanding common shares of Emhart, which manufactures
a wide range of consumer and industrial products, including lawn and
garden equipment, hardware and materials used to make footwear.
   The Topper partnership includes Getty and New York real estate
developers Lawrence Fisher, 78, and brother Zachary Fisher, 77. The
deadline for the tender offer is midnight March 23.
   Emhart's stock closed at $32.75 a share, down 25 cents, on the
New York Stock Exchange Thursday. Topper's offer was disclosed after
the market closed. Emhart's stock, though, has risen almost $10 a
share in the past month amid takeover rumors.
   One industry analyst said Topper's bid appears too good to refuse.
   ``The way their press release reads, they are making a tender
offer and they don't care what management thinks,'' said Rod Cerny,
chief investment officer at Kirkpatrick, Pettis, Smith, Polian Inc.
of Omaha, Neb.
   ``But if you take into consideration that the stock one month ago
was selling at about $23 to $24, this is a premium of about 50
percent,'' said Cerny, who is a shareholder. ``We could hardly
imagine management feeling that this is some kind of undervalued bid.
   ``Our contention all along was that the company's value is in the
mid-30s,'' Cerny said.
   Cerny said Emhart, which has about 1,000 employees, is made up of
numerous subsidiaries that operate separately, making it ideal for a
traditional buy-and-bust-up takeover strategy.
   Such a strategy would allow the acquirers to borrow money to
complete the deal and then pay some of that money back by selling
off subsidiaries. He added that he didn't know whether Topper was
planning to do that.
   Topper, an investment vehicle created for the acquisition of
Emhart, notified Emhart that it would nominate a slate of directors
for the annual meeting scheduled for April 27. Depending upon the
board's response to the offer, it might conduct a proxy contest for
control of the board.
   Topper said in a statement that it would like to keep the
company's headquarters in Farmington and leave Emhart's management
in place.
   ``We strongly desire to negotiate an amicable transaction and we
would like to meet with Emhart management as soon as possible to
discuss our offer,'' Topper said.
   ``We believe our offer represents an opportunity for Emhart
shareholders to realize exceptional value. It represents a 43
percent premium over the market price of Emhart stock on Jan. 23,
1989, before the recent run-up of the company's stock,'' the
partnership said.
   ``Our objective is to acquire, own and operate Emhart, and to
continue to build its manufacturing businesses over the long term,''
they said.
   Topper also said it has lined up financing: Chemical Bank and two
other banks have committed $1.2 billion, and an affiliate of First
Boston Corp. said it would provide $1.1 billion in short-term
financing. The Fishers and Getty also plan to kick in about $300
million of their own money.
   The Fisher brothers are worth at least $800 million, Forbes
magazine has said. Their participation in a never-completed 1984 bid
for Walt Disney Productions, led by financier Saul P. Steinberg,
netted them $30 million.
   Getty, 54, gained his fortune through an inheritance from his
father, Jean Paul Getty, who turned his father's oil company into a
worldwide oil behemoth.
   Getty is worth at least $450 million and perhaps more than $1
billion, according to Forbes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
