<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed lower today, faced with a
barrage of interest-rate increases.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 8.39 to 2,281.07
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by nearly 2 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 314 up, 598 down and
537 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 22.19 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   After the close on Thursday, Chase Manhattan Bank of New York
kicked off the second round of prime rate increases this month,
raising the benchmark rate on variable loans from 11 percent to 11.5
percent.
   As more banks joined in that move today, the Federal Reserve
increased its discount rate, the charge it sets on loans to private
financial institutions, from 6.5 percent to 7 percent.
   The Fed said it acted in response to ``inflationary pressures in
the economy.''
   Open-market interest rates for securities such as bonds and
Treasury bills also climbed today.
   While the rise in rates increased investors' worries about the
business and economic outlook, analysts said, they did not come as
any great surprise, given recent government reports that suggested
inflation was heating up.
   Emhart led the active list, up 6} at 39{. An investment group
known as Topper L.P. said it began a $35-a-share tender offer for
Emhart's stock, and speculation immediately arose among traders that
a higher bid might be in the offing.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .55 to 163.54. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .33 at 322.90.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average finished with a 5.53
gain at 2,289.46.
   Advancing issues slightly outnumbered declines on the NYSE, with
738 up, 684 down and 501 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 150.37 million shares, against 163.14
million in the previous session.
