<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   02-24 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lower Opening On Slack Export Sales; Large Meal Stocks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices fell modestly in
early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting slack
export demand and increased precipitation in major crop growing
areas.
   A Census Bureau report today of larger-than-expected soybean meal
stocks acted as a further drag on the grain markets and the soybean
complex in particular, despite a continued rise in soybean cash
prices.
   The wheat market has resumed its downward trend after rallying
briefly earlier this week on news that the Soviet Union had
purchased 400,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices.
   Agriculture Department Secretary Clayton Yeutter said today that
the return of wintry weather to the Midwest was encouraging for
spring crop conditions because the snow adds moisture to soil
parched by last summer's drought.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.25\ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to { cent lower with March at $2.71{ a bushel; oats were \
cent to 1 cent lower with March at $2.06 a bushel; soybeans were \
cent to 2{ cents lower with March at $7.56{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .05 cent higher with April at
77.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .37 cent lower
with March at 83.50 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent lower to
.07 cent higher with April at 43.50 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .12 cent to .42 cent lower with March at 39.05 cents a
pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Thursday while pork futures
advanced.
</TEXT>
