<FIRST>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   02-24 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feds and Banks Hike Key Rates, Markets Down</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf with Dow Jones index down nearly 28 points</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The powerful Federal Reserve joined in a spree of bank interest
rate hikes today, raising its key lending fee in a move that
underscored a tougher anti-inflation fight and signaled higher
borrowing costs for millions of Americans.
   The Fed's increase in the discount rate to 7 percent from 6.5
percent was the first such rise since Aug. 9, and coincided with
moves by New York banks to hike their prime lending rate to 11.5
percent from 11 percent.
   The steps jolted Wall Street today and sent stock and bond prices
down sharply. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 28
points to the 2,261 level by late morning. The 30-year Treasury bond
fell nearly $7.50 per $1,000 in face amount.
   The discount rate is the Fed's loan fee to member financial
institutions and historically has influenced other interest rates
nationwide. The increase today put the discount rate at its highest
point in three years.
   The prime is a benchmark for a wide range of business and
consumer loan rates, including car loans and adjustable-rate home
mortgages. An increase in the prime means borrowers will have to pay
more to finance their debts.
   The half-percentage point increase in the prime was first
announced late Thursday by Chase Manhattan bank and quickly followed
by rivals. It was the second increase in two weeks and lifted the
rate to 11.5 percent, the highest level since November 1984.
   The prime hike reflects the higher cost of borrowing the banks
face themselves, indicating the Fed is soaking up money in the
banking system, one of its weapons in restraining inflation.
   The interest rate increases came against a background of signs
that inflation is intensifying, a partial result of low unemployment
and strong economic growth. On Wednesday, the Labor Department said
consumer prices rose in January at an annual rate of 7.2 percent,
the highest level in two years.
   Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan called the inflation trend disturbing
and vowed to pressure rates up until he squeezes inflation out of
the economy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0246 </DOCNO>
