<FIRST>r f PM-Yeutter-USDA 1stLd-Writethru f0070 02-24 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yeutter-USDA, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0070,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says No Decisions Yet on Farm Program Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 5 grafs with further Yeutter comments; ADDs byline. A version
moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said
today that no final decision has been made on how to reduce federal
spending on farm programs, but he indicated analysts are looking at
many possibilities.
   ``We'll find a way to do so, because that's a requirement of the
(budget) process,'' Yeutter told reporters. ``Agriculture will have
to play its part in that process.''
   He added: ``We'll look every where, obviously ... it'll have to
be done on the basis of economic analysis. We're not going to do it
in an arbitrary or capricious way, and that means analyzing all the
options and combinations of options.''
   Yeutter said he is scheduled to appear before Congress several
times next week but would not have all the budget work done before
then.
   Budget analysts have estimated that up to $2 billion may have to
be whittled from USDA programs in the fiscal year that begins Oct.
1. Those cuts were not specified in the budget proposals submitted
by the outgoing Reagan administration in January and were left open
to be negotiated with Congress.
   Yeutter was asked if $2 billion would be enough to cut farm
programs, mainly the price support operations for major commodities.
He replied that in the long run he would like to see less reliance
on the ``largesse and generosity'' of the federal government.
   ``In the long term I hope we can bring down the budget, but only
if we have similar reaction from our trading partners around the
world,'' Yeutter said. ``We do not want to individually disarm.''
   Yeutter served for 3{ years as U.S. trade representative in the
Reagan administration before President Bush tapped him to be
secretary of agriculture.
   No aides to Yeutter at the Agriculture Department have yet been
announced by the White House, and key jobs are still being carried
out by holdovers from the Reagan administration.
   However, Yeutter said at a news conference that he was hopeful an
announcement would be made soon on the No. 2 post of deputy
secretary, probably ``within the next few days.''
   Reports circulated last week that Yeutter and some presidential
aides had been bickering over filling the deputy secretary job, with
Yeutter opting in favor of Jack Parnell, the California state
agricultural commissioner, or Sam Hollis, a cotton warehouseman from
Memphis, Tenn.
   But there were claims that White House pressure had developed for
former Kentucky governor Louie Nunn, who told The Associated Press
that he had been interviewed by Yeutter several weeks earlier.
   Yeutter said the reports of him bickering with the White House
were ``completely false'' and that there had been no disagreement
whatsoever with the White House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0247 </DOCNO>
