<FIRST>r f BC-Varian-BOC     02-24 0193</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Varian-BOC,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sale of Varian Division Blocked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Varian Associates said it will not fight
the Federal Trade Commission's decision to block the $65.8 million
sale of its vacuum products division to the BOC Group of Britain.
   The company said on Thursday that it had been notified by the FTC
that the agency would not approve the planned sale and had
authorized its staff to seek a preliminary court injunction against
the deal.
   The FTC said the combination of the Varian division with BOC's
Edwards High Vacuum business would control too large a share of the
market for a specific leak-detection device.
   Varian President Norman Pond said the matter would not be pursued.
   ``This continues to be a viable and valuable business, and Varian
is formulating plans to streamline and strengthen its competitive
position,'' he said.
   Varian's vacuum-products division, based in Lexington, Mass., has
730 employees and accounts for about 6 percent of the company's $1.1
billion in sales. It produces vacuum pumps and hardware used in a
variety of manufacturing and other processes.
   Varian Associates produces systems and components for
communications, defense, scientific, medical and industrial markets.
</TEXT>
