<DOCNO> AP890224-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1328EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Switzerland-DrugMoney     02-24 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Switzerland-Drug Money,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Swiss-based Company Named In Largest U.S. Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. authorities Friday linked a
Swiss-based currency trading company to a large-scale drug money
laundering scandal in the United States.
   The American embassy said a probe has revealed that
Lebanese-controlled Shakarchi Trading A.G. of Zurich may be
connected to what was described as the United States' largest drug
money laundering investigation.
   An embassy statement said the probe in New York has revealed that
a Shakarchi bank account in that city may have been involved in
transactions with targets of the probe.
   The company is headed by Mohammed Shakarchi, a Lebanese. Its vice
president, Hans W. Kopp, resigned last October. His wife, Swiss
Justice Minister Elisabeth Kopp, quit last month after admitting she
tipped him off that the company may come under investigation.
   The company already had been mentioned in connection with a probe
launched by a Swiss prosecutor into the origins of more than $2
billion allegedly transferred to Switzerland by two Lebanese
brothers, Jean and Barkev Magharian. Both men are being held in
Lugano, in southern Switzerland, on suspcision of fraud. Shakarchi,
a business contact of the Magharians, has denied any part in
laundering drug money.
   A Swiss prosecutor's report this month said Shakarchi told
investigators he warned a manager of Credit Suisse, the country's
third largest commercial bank, that funds deposited by the
Magharians with the bank were of suspicious origin.
   Swiss government spokesman Achille Casanova said Friday
authorities were examining whether judicial proceedings can be
opened against the Shakarchi company. He said the company's New York
account contained $500,000 investigators believe is drug money.
   Money laundering is not punishable in Switzerland unless the
funds are used for criminal purposes. Legislation to make it a
criminal offense is being drafted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
