<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AFL-CIO-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0031 02-24 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AFL-CIO-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0031,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>AFL-CIO Leaders Pledge Labor Unity in Event of Eastern Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with meeting ended, details from
morning session; Picks up 5th graf, `There has ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAL HARBOUR, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFL-CIO leaders closed their annual
meeting today confident that organized labor can present a united
front against Eastern Airlines if its mechanics go on strike next
week.
   The Eastern dispute dominated the federation's Executive Council
session this week, and the union leaders as their last major event
went to nearby Miami on Thursday for a noisy rally with the
Machinists outside the airline's headquarters.
   Federation President Lane Kirkland said organized labor would do
``everything possible within the law'' to ground Eastern, sister
carrier Continental Airlines and their parent company, Texas Air
Corp., in the event of a strike.
   The meeting ended after a closing council session today devoted
mostly to internal housekeeping and passage of a few final
resolutions on issues of concern to labor.
   Among those were calls for Congress to pass provisions
restricting private employers from using assets from overfunded
pension plans to initiate or fight takeover attempts.
   The council also condemned the Treasury Department for overruling
a Customs Department classification of imported multi-purpose
vehicles, such as small four-wheel drive vehicles, as light trucks,
which subjected them to a 25 percent tariff.
   ``The Treasury Department has capitulated to foreign political
pressure, pointlessly increasing the U.S. trade deficit and
undermining the jobs of U.S. workers,'' the council said.
   The labor leaders also vowed to be a force in the 1991 national
redistricting that will reshape congressional districts.
   ``It is vital that the labor movement and its allies coordinate a
long-term reapportionment strategy that will assist state
legislative candidates who are committed to programs that benefit
working Americans,'' the resolution said.
   There has been rampant discussion this week about whether labor
could mount a successful boycott of Eastern if there is a strike.
The rally Thursday left the labor officials in an upbeat mood about
those prospects.
   ``This kind of speaks for itself, doesn't it?'' federation
President Lane Kirkland said as he marched in front of Eastern's
complex at the Miami airport.
   Fueling the confidence was the presence of several Eastern pilots
and representatives of their union, whose support would be vital to
any labor hopes of grounding Eastern during a strike.
   Despite the show of solidarity and militant strike talk, the
labor leaders said it was still their hope President Bush would put
off the strike deadline for 60 days by naming an emergency board to
mediate the dispute.
   Kirkland called on the president to intervene ``for the sake of
the future of the airline, for the sake of the communities Eastern
serves, for the sake of the country.''
   The 8,500 machinists and ground personnel, members of the
International Association of Machinists, are scheduled to strike at
12:01 a.m. March 4 unless a settlement is reached during mediation
now under way in Washington, something IAM leaders consider all but
impossible.
   Among the Eastern pilots' union officials at the rally was
Secretary-Treasurer Rick Chapman, who irritated several AFL-CIO
leaders by saying Wednesday the pilots would cross Machinist picket
lines if Eastern management ``makes it worth our while.''
   ``We support the membership of the IAM,'' said Chapman, who
apologized for any trouble his statement had caused and said it was
reported out of context.
   The pilots, according to union policy, will not decide whether to
honor Machinist picket lines until there is a strike. But one, Bob
Breslin, said the ``momentum is growing very rapidly'' to side with
the Machinists.
   Airline pilots traditionally have spoiled labor's hopes of
crippling airlines during strikes by crossing picket lines.
   Eastern management, which has said it plans to operate in the
event of a strike, made its presence felt as well.
   A sign hanging from a company building read: ``Welcome AFL-CIO
delegates. Eastern, your official airline.'' During the rally a
small plane flew overhead toting a banner reading, ``Eastern,
official airline of the AFL-CIO.''
   Most of the federation officials here traveled on Eastern, which
offered a group discount. Federation officials have acknowledged the
irony in that but said they encourage people to fly Eastern because
they want the financially strapped airline to survive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
