<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   02-24 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stocks Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices on the London Stock Exchange held on
to small gains Friday despite a sharp drop prompted by steep early
declines on Wall Street on the back of an increase in the U.S.
discount rate.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended the day
2.9 points, or 0.1 percent, higher at 2,019.5, just 0.3 point above
its lowest level. The index had gained as much as 14.9 points by
early afternoon.
   Volume came to 568 million shares compared with 551.7 million
shares.
   Countering the negative trend, London stocks got some support
from a bit of fresh buying interest at the start of a new two-week
trading account in the afternoon, dealers said.
   ``We've ended the account on a reasonably good note considering
Wall Street was down 32 points,'' when the London market closed, a
dealer said.
   New York share prices sank after the U.S. Federal Reserve Board
increased the discount rate by half a percentage point to 7 percent.
That rate is what the Fed charges on loans to member banks.
   London's Stock Exchange divides trading into two-week and
three-week periods for accounting purposes.
</TEXT>
