<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell sharply today, faced with a
barrage of interest-rate increases.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 31.25 to 2,258.21
by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 4 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 271 up, 1,183
down and 439 unchanged.
   After the close on Thursday, Chase Manhattan Bank of New York
kicked off the second round of prime rate increases this month,
raising the benchmark rate on variable loans from 11 percent to 11.5
percent.
   As more banks joined in that move today, the Federal Reserve
increased its discount rate, the charge it sets on loans to private
financial institutions, from 6.5 percent to 7 percent.
   The Fed said it acted in response to ``inflationary pressures in
the economy.''
   Open-market interest rates on securities such as bonds and
Treasury bills also cimbed today.
   While the rise in rates increased investors' worries about the
business and economic outlook, analysts said, they did not come as
any great surprise, given recent government reports that suggested
inflation was heating up.
   Emhart led the active list, up 7[ at 39~. An investment group
known as Topper L.P. said it began a $35-a-share tender offer for
Emhart's stock, and speculation immediately arose among traders that
a higher bid might be in the offing.
   Losers among the blue chips included General Motors, down 1| at
85[; International Business Machines, down 1| at 121}; General
Electric, down { at 45|, and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down |
at 29~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped 1.93 to 162.16. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down 2.38 at 320.85.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 121.06 million shares with two
hours to go.
