<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     02-24 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished marginally higher in Europe on
Friday as the market reacted without enthusiasm to a hike in the
U.S. discount rate.
   Gold prices fell.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the U.S. Federal Reserve Board's
move to raise the discount rate to 7 percent from 6.5 percent
initially caused the dollar to steam to a session high of 1.8330
West German marks.
   Although dealers had been complaining about the lack of strong
action from the Fed for months, some thought the rate hike was not
strong enough.
   ``It would have been a full point, many people thought, and the
dollar then went down,'' said a trader at a large Frankfurt bank.
   Others said the move came too late and had only a symbolic effect
that wore off. The dollar then traded in quiet ranges.
   Selected late dollar rates, compared with late Thursday: 1.8270
West German marks, up from 1.8215; 1.5602 Swiss francs, up from
1.5535; 6.2265 French francs, up from 6.2125; 2.0630 Dutch guilders,
up from 2.0590; 1,350.00 Italian lire, up from 1,344.50; 1.1990
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1958.
   In London, the dollar strengthened against the British pound. One
pound was trading at $1.7520, cheaper for buyers than $1.7595 late
Thursday.
   The dollar was quoted in London at 126.53 Japanese yen, up from
126.29 yen in Tokyo at Thursday's close.
   Gold traded in London at a late bid price of $390.20 a troy
ounce, down from $391.50 bid late Thursday.
   In Zurich, the late bid price was $389.00 dollars, down from
$391.75 bid late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.18 to close at a bid $390.68.
   Silver bullion was unchanged in London at a bid price of $6.04
dollars a troy ounce, the same bid as late Thursday.
</TEXT>
