<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1452EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Airlines-Antitrust     02-24 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Airlines-Antitrust,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racketeering Claim In Continental Airlines Suit to Go to Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The courts will review a $1 billion
racketeering fraud claim lodged by Continental Airlines, accusing
rival carriers of overcharging travel agents who used the companies'
computers to make reservations, a judge ruled.
   U.S. District Judge Edward Rafeedie on Feb. 17 refused to dismiss
the civil claim brought by Houston-based Continental against rivals
American Airlines and United Airlines. Nearly a dozen other airlines
also were involved in the action.
   Rafeedie also denied motions for summary judgment filed by
American and United. The Continental lawsuit charges the two
airlines with violating the Racketeer Influence and Corrupt
Organizations Act.
   At issue is the price the two airlines charged travel agents for
use of the companies' computer reservation systems. The plaintiffs
are seeking $1 billion in reimbursement of such fees paid from 1981
to 1987.
   American Airlines attorney J. Edd Stepp said the racketeering
allegations stem from the fact that rates appeared higher if travel
agents called up flights on the airlines' computers.
   ``Since everybody knew it was that way, and the airlines knew, to
us it seems incongruous to suggest that what existed was fraudulent
or misleading to anybody,'' Stepp said. ``We don't believe there is
a shred of evidence.''
   That system, which was phased out in 1984, had been investigated
by the Justice Department, which took no action, Stepp said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0258 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Paraguay-Debt     02-24 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay-Debt,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraguay Will Seek to Renegotiate Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government said Friday it will seek
to renegotiate its $2.2 billion foreign debt.
   Treasury Minister Enzo Debernardi said servicing the debt now
amounts to $300 million while the country's central bank has only
$160 million in reserves.
   The provisional government of Gen. Andres Rodriguez won't impose
a unilateral moratorium, Debernardi said, but cannot fully comply
with what is owed.
   The government has been in power since Feb. 3, when Rodriguez
toppled Gen. Alfredo Stroessner in a coup.
   Stroessner usually made good on Paraguay's debt payments, but
economists and foreign observers predicted last year that the
country's faltering economy would create problems in 1989.
   A report by the U.S. Embassy in Asuncion made public last
December said Brazil is Paraguay's major creditor nation and is owed
$400 million. Paraguay also owes the World Bank $410 million and the
Interamerican Development Bank $450 million, according to the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1500EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Pepperell-Community Bjt   02-24 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepperell-Community, Bjt,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepperell Workers Wary About Company's New Owner</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 2nd graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of West Point, Ga., sent a letter Friday
congratulating William Farley on his takeover of West
Point-Pepperell Inc., but many local residents aren't quite as
enthusiastic about the textile giant's new owner.
   ``A year from now, I want to hear how these people like working
for a damn Yankee,'' one angry caller to West Point radio phone-in
program said Thursday, after Pepperell agreed to the buyout. ``I was
born into West Point Manufacturing Co. (a predecessor of Pepperell),
and I sure wanted to die a West Point-Pepperell.''
   But many residents of West Point, where Pepperell for years has
been the main employer, appeared ready to work for Farley even
though Pepperell bitterly had opposed his hostile buyout offers for
months before capitulating.
   Buttons and bumper stickers proclaiming ``Stop Farley'' were on
view Friday, one day after the takeover was announced, with an
altered, handwritten message: ``We Love Farley,'' said Terrell
Whaley, general manager of West Point radio station WCJM-AM.
   ``We have no choice,'' Whaley said. ``He's the man in power now.''
   Pepperell employs about 8,000 people in the area of West Point,
in western Georgia near the Alabama state line. Many were concerned
about their future upon hearing that Farley, chairman of
Chicago-based Farley Inc., had succeeded in his four-month hostile
takeover fight.
   The Pepperell board of directors on Thursday approved Farley's
$58-per-share buyout offer, which will total about $3 billion when
combined with refinancing of Pepperell debt.
   Farley has promised no production layoffs and praised the
Pepperell employees for working hard during the recent months of
uncertainty. But he also has indicated some portions of the company
may be sold.
   ``I just hope they don't shut the mills down,'' Vernon Anderson,
a 20-year Pepperell employee from LaGrange, Ga., told the Valley
Times of nearby Lanett, Ala. ``That's the way these people are
living.''
   West Point Mayor H.E. Steele Jr. said in a telephone interview
Friday that he believes fears of mass layoffs are unfounded.
   ``I never felt it was inevitable that Farley would have mass
layoffs,'' the mayor said. ``He wasn't buying West Point-Pepperell
to go out of business.''
   Steele also said he welcomed Farley's presence in West Point.
   ``I feel it is the end of a tradition but the beginning of a new
era,'' he said. ``I sent a letter of congratulations this morning on
behalf of the city and myself personally.''
   Other holdings of Farley, one of the nation's largest
privately-held conglomerates, include Fruit of the Loom Inc., the
nation's No. 1 underwear manufacturer; Acme Boot Co., which sell
Dingo and Acme boots; and Doehler-Jarvis, which makes die-cast metal
products for the automotive industry.
   Whaley, who spent Friday morning talking to people around town,
said many in the area aren't buying Farley's promises just yet.
   ``I have a lot of apprehension,'' Whaley said in a telephone
interview. ``I wonder if Mr. Farley is sincere when he says he won't
sell off. His immediate plan was to, and now he's twice as much in
debt.''
   But Whaley said most local residents are ``willing to go the
second mile to help him (Farley) make it a success.''
   Whaley said several local residents were disappointed that
Pepperell Chairman Joseph L. Lanier Jr. failed to stop Farley and
that he did not offer more of an explanation once the decision was
made to accept Farley's bid.
   Farley said Lanier, whose family was associated with the company
for four generations, and President Donald Keller will leave
Pepperell once the merger is complete.
   ``Pepperell is the lifeblood of this community,'' Whaley said.
``Over 8,000 people here work for them. They've been a steady oak
for 103 years.
   ``We've leaned on them _ too much,'' he said. ``And now we've
come to the crossroads.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890224-0260 </DOCNO>
