<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   02-24 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Rallies On Technicals, Export Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices closed substantially higher
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade in response to bullish chart
signals and rumors of impending export sales.
   Other grain and soybean futures finished narrowly mixed in light
trading.
   The rally in the wheat market capped four straight days of gains
and may indicate that the market expects export sales to pick up
next week.
   Among the rumors was one that the Agriculture Deparment plans to
extend an offer of more subsidized wheat to China. But analysts
tended to discount those expectations.
   ``The same rumor has been around for weeks,'' said Ted Mao, a
grain specialist in New York with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Speculative buying accelerated after prices for delivery of
new-crop wheat topped the week's previous highs.
   Soybeans for March delivery rose more than 6 cents a bushel on
technical signals but other grain and soybean futures were little
changed.
   At the close, wheat was 5 cents to 6} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.33} a bushel; corn was } cent
lower to 1 cent higher with March at $2.71\ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1\ cents lower with March at $2.06\ a bushel; soybeans
were 3 cents lower to 6\ cents higher with March at $7.63 a bushel.
</TEXT>
