<FIRST>r f AM-KmartSuit     02-24 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-K mart Suit,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>K mart Ordered to Pay Addition $5 Million For Contract Breach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has increased a breach of
contract fine against K mart Corp., the nation's second-largest
retailer, to more than $78 million.
   Attorneys for the Troy, Mich.-based retailer asked U.S. District
Judge Ronald R. Lagueux to reduce a $73.3 million award granted last
month when a jury found K mart in breach of contract with a
now-defunct Pawtucket clothing buyer.
   Instead, Lagueux denied the motion Thursday and ruled that 12
percent interest on the basic damages of $59.3 million could be
calculated over 19 more months than originally included, increasing
the award by about $5 million.
   He also upheld a magistrate's order that K mart must pay $80,870
for refusing to supply some pretrial information to the plantiff,
Fashion House.
   Fashion House charged that K mart ignored an 1983 agreement
requiring the retailer to purchase 85 percent of its name brand and
designer clothes from the wholesaler. K mart maintained Fashion
House was not supplying the styles, sizes and colors it ordered.
   After a 56-day trial, Fashion House won a $73.3 million verdict,
including interest. The jury found K mart, a $28-billion-a-year
retailer, had terminated the contract in 1986 without just cause.
</TEXT>
