<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices suffered a sharp setback Friday at
the hands of rising interest rates, closing out the market's worst
week in more than six months.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials tumbled 43.92 points to
2,245.54, extending its loss for the week to 79.28 points.
   That ranked as the average's biggest weekly decline since it fell
81.61 last Aug. 8-12.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by nearly 4 to 1 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
327 up, 1,191 down and 443 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 160.68 million
shares, up from 150.37 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in those
stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market,
totaled 194.05 million shares.
   After the close on Thursday, Chase Manhattan Bank of New York
kicked off the second round of prime rate increases this month,
raising the benchmark rate on variable loans from 11 percent to 11.5
percent.
   As many more banks joined in that move Friday, the Federal
Reserve increased its discount rate, the charge it sets on loans to
private financial institutions, from 6.5 percent to 7 percent. The
Fed said it acted in response to ``inflationary pressures in the
economy.''
   Open-market interest rates on securities such as bonds and
Treasury bills also climbed.
   The rise in rates did not come as a complete surprise, given
recent government reports suggesting that inflation was heating up.
   Nevertheless, it increased investors' worries about the business
and economic outlook, analysts said.
   Emhart led the active list, up 7[ at 39~. An investment group
known as Topper L.P. said it began a $35-a-share tender offer for
Emhart's stock, and speculation immediately arose among traders that
a higher bid might be in the offing.
   Losers among the blue chips included General Motors, down 2{ at
84\; International Business Machines, down 2\ at 121[; General
Electric, down ~ at 45\; Eastman Kodak, down 1{ at 46|, and American
Telephone &amp; Telegraph, down } at 29}.
   All 30 of the Dow Jones industrial average's component stocks
posted losses.
   California Energy, traded on the American Stock Exchange, plunged
3~ to 16~. A Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. analyst, in his first report on
the stock, gave it a ``sell'' recommendation.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $39.16 billion, or 1.36
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slumped 2.37 to 161.72.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 5.77 to 331.33, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was down 4.92 at 287.13.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dropped 3.11 to 399.96. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 321.49, down 1.74.
