<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     02-24 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose in moderate trading
Friday, led by a rally in the gasoline pits.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, unleaded gasoline for March
delivery rose 0.37 cent to close the day at 50.11 cents a gallon
after trading 79 points higher during the session.
   Crude oil for April ended the day up 24 cents at $18.07 a barrel,
breaking through what analysts said was an important resistant point
at $18.
   March heating oil advanced 1.14 cents to settle at 51.73 cents a
gallon.
   Analysts said crude prices got a boost from a short-covering
rally in the oil-products pits, mainly gasoline, with brokers buying
before the March contracts expire on Tuesday.
   Dealers also continued to scramble to lock in fixed-volume deals
before summer, said Jayne Ball, commodity oil broker and analyst
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``People are worried about gasoline supplies and about (higher
octane) regulations even though they don't take effect until May,''
she said.
   Several Northeastern states, pending approval from the
Environmental Protection Agency, will impose the new rules requiring
refiners to make the higher octane gasoline.
   Once the speculations take effect, lower octane gasoline might be
in short supply for states outside of the region, Ball said.
</TEXT>
