<FIRST>u f AM-Emhart 1stLd-Writethru   02-24 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emhart, 1st Ld-Writethru,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emhart Stock Soars Amid Takeover Attempt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf with closing stock price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FARMINGTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emhart Corp.'s stock soared Friday
following an unsolicited $2.4 billion takeover offer from an
investment group that includes oil heir Gordon P. Getty.
   Emhart, a manufacturer of a wide range of consumer and industrial
products, said it would study the offer, which came about a year
after the company's own unsuccessful hostile bid for Stanadyne Inc.
   Emhart Chairman Peter L. Scott advised stockholders not to take
any immediate action on the $35-per-share offer announced by Getty's
group, Topper Acquisition Corp., after the close of stock trading
Thursday.
   Investors reacted enthusiastically to the offer Friday, but
apparently expected Topper to bid higher. Emhart stock rose $7.12{
to $39.87{ a share in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Emhart stock rose almost $10 in the past month amid takeover
rumors.
   Topper told Scott in a letter it would nominate a slate of
directors for the Emhart annual meeting scheduled for April 27.
Depending upon the board's response to its offer, the group said it
might conduct a proxy contest for control of the board.
   James Paper, who follows Emhart for the investment firm
Kirkpatrick, Pettis, Smith, Polian Inc. in Omaha, Neb., said Topper
would likely increase its bid.
   ``They have the resources to go higher,'' Paper said.
   Paper said Emhart has been undervalued for several months, but
has caught investors' eyes with series of well-planned acquisitions
over the past four years.
   ``They have transformed this company from a machinery company to
a very good multi-industry company,'' he said.
   Among the businesses Emhart acquired recently were GardenAmerica
Corp., a manufacturer of garden watering systems, and Price Pfister
Inc., a maker of faucets and plumbing supplies.
   A year ago, the investment firm Forstmann Little &amp; Co. outbid
Emhart with an $820 million offer for Stanadyne, a maker of plumbing
fixtures, automotive and metal products. Emhart had begun a hostile
$596 million tender offer for Stanadyne after being rebuffed in a
friendly buyout attempt.
   Another Kirkpatrick Pettis analyst, Rob Cerny, said Emhart's
diverse subsidiaries made it ideal for a traditional buy-and-bust-up
takeover strategy.
   Topper, which also includes New York real estate developers
Lawrence Fisher and his brother, Zachary, told Scott it planned to
sell Price Pfister and Emhart's Information and Electronic Systems
division.
   But the group said its objective was to ``acquire, own and
operate Emhart, and to continue to build its manufacturing
businesses over the long term.''
   Topper said it had lined up financing for its offer. The group
said Chemical Bank and two other banks have committed $1.2 billion
and an affiliate of First Boston Corp. said it would provide $1.1
billion in short-term financing.
   Getty, 54, gained his fortune through an inheritance from his
father, Jean Paul Getty, who turned Getty Oil Co. into a worldwide
oil giant.
   The Fisher brothers participated in a 1984 bid for Walt Disney
Co. led by financier Saul P. Steinberg. The bid ended with the
Steinberg-led group selling their shares back to Disney at a premium.
   Emhart earned $126 million during 1988 on sales of $2.76 billion,
up from earnings of $106 million and sales of $2.45 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
