<DOCNO> AP890224-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1752EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Labor     02-24 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Labor,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leaders of Flight Attendants Vote to Support Strike Against Eastern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the union representing flight attendants
at Eastern Airlines voted unanimously Friday to ask members to honor
a strike by Machinists against the company that could begin March 4.
   Officials with the Transport Workers Union Local 553 said they're
confident their 7,000 members will not cross Machinist picket lines.
   In a statement, union president Mary Jane Barry attacked Frank
Lorenzo, chairman of Texas Air Corp., the parent of Miami-based
Eastern.
   ``Frank Lorenzo has the gall to ask flight attendants to cross a
picket line when he is cannibalizing our great airline,'' she said.
   ``He won't promise to stop dismantling Eastern by selling gates,
aircraft and upstreaming money to Continental (Airlines). Yet, he
wants our members to come to work and help him destroy Eastern and
the economies of Eastern cities like Miami.''
   Continental is the other major subsidiary of Texas Air.
   The flight attendants union received formal requests to support a
strike from William Winpisinger, the International Association of
Machinists' international president, and Charles Bryan, leader of
the Machinists at Eastern.
   ``We had no hesitation in supporting our colleagues and fellow
unionists of IAM,'' Ms. Barry said. ``We realize if Lorenzo destroys
the IAM workers' livelihood, we are his next target.''
   An official of the Eastern pilots union said Wednesday the pilots
would cross Machinist picket lines in the event of a strike,
provided Lorenzo guarantees job security for the pilots and meets
their other demands.
   The pilots union official later apologized to Winpisinger and
AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland for any trouble his statement had
caused.
   The Machinists represent about 8,500 mechanics, baggage handlers
and other ground personnel at Eastern. The union has threatened to
strike over contract concessions demanded by Texas Air to save money
at the airline, which has lost hundreds of millions of dollars over
the last several years.
</TEXT>
