<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1755EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     02-24 0696</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lumber Futures Tumble As Loan Rates Rise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Lumber futures fell sharply Friday as traders anticipated higher
mortgage rates and a slowdown in home construction after the Federal
Reserve Board increased its main interest rate.
   On other markets, frozen pork-belly futures plunged the permitted
daily limit of 2 cents a pound; livestock futures were mixed; grains
and soybeans were mixed; energy futures rose; and precious metals
retreated.
   Lumber settled $3.40 to $4 lower on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange with the contract for delivery in March at $182.80 per
1,000 board-feet.
   The decline followed increases in both the prime lending rate,
which is the benchmark on which banks base their loan rates, and the
discount rate, the interest rate that the Fed charges on loans to
its member banks.
   Most major banks raised their prime rates 0.5 percentage point to
11.5 percent while the Fed upped its discount rate to 7 percent from
6.5 percent. The increases were seen as efforts to fight inflation
by slowing down the economy.
   Bud Merrill, a lumber market analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. in Eugene, Ore., said the higher interest rates could lead to a
substantial weakening of the lumber market, which has been in a
two-year upswing.
   ``I tend to believe we're going to be under pressure at least
until the early part of spring,'' Merrill said.
   Futures prices for frozen pork bellies fell steeply on the
Chicago Merc ahead of the Agriculture Department's monthly cold
storage report, which was expected to show record-high supplies of
the unsliced bacon meat in the nation's commercial meat lockers.
   The report, which was released after the close, confirmed those
expectations. It showed 113.4 million pounds of bellies in cold
storage as of Feb. 1, far surpassing both the year-ago figure of 63
million pounds and the previous Feb. 1 record of 90.2 million pounds
set in 1981.
   The report also showed record-high total pork supplies and
suggested that both turkey and ham would be in abundant supply for
Easter.
   Analysts said the massive pork-belly supply could become a major
depressant on the futures market this summer unless retailers
stimulate the movement of bellies out of storage by cutting bacon
prices, which now average about $1.49 a pound.
   ``We need to knock 50 cents off the retail bacon price in a hury
or this market's goose is cooked,'' said Charles Levitt, Shearson's
chief livestock market analyst in Chicago.
   Live cattle settled .12 cent lower to .23 cent higher with April
at 78.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .30 cent
lower with March at 83.62 cents a pound; live hogs were .23 cent
lower to .20 cent higher with April at 43.52 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.32 cents to 2 cents lower with March at 37.42
cents a pound.
   Wheat futures moved substantially higher on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid bullish chart signals and rumors of impending export
sales. Other grain and soybean futures finished narrowly mixed in
light trading.
   Wheat settled 5 cents to 7 cents higher with March at $4.34 a
bushel; corn was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with March at $2.71{
a bushel; oats were unchanged to 1\ cents lower with March at $2.06\
a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents lower to 4\ cents higher with March
at $7.61 a bushel.
   Crude oil spurted above $18 a barrel on the New York Mercantile
Exchange on news that Colombia planned to freeze its oil exports to
help boost prices, a move seen as strengthening OPEC's hand.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 8 cents to 24 cents
higher with April at $18.07 a barrel; heating oil was .40 cent to
1.14 cents higher with March at 51.73 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .30 cent to .50 cent higher with March at 50.11 cents a
gallon.
   Most precious metals futures prices slipped lower on New York's
Commodity Exchange as the dollar strengthened.
   Gold settled $2 lower to 10 cents higher with April at $392.60 a
troy ounce; silver was 0.6 cent to 1 cent lower with March at $5.925
a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
