<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2143EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-NewWorld 1stLd-Writethru   02-24 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New World, 1st Ld-Writethru,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pathe Entertainment to Acquire New World in $263 Million Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Struggling film and television producer New
World Entertainment Ltd. said Friday it has agreed to be acquired by
Pathe Entertainment Inc. in a deal worth $138 million.
   New World sold Marvel Comics earlier this year and its most
recent film releases have been box-office duds, including
``Hellbound: Hellraiser II,'' ``Attack of the Killer Tomatoes'' and
``Telephone.''
   The deal with Pathe, payable in $57.2 million in cash and $80.8
million in non-interest bearing notes, is subject to approval by the
New World board before Tuesday. Each New World shareholder is
expected to receive about $8.20 per share, $3.40 in cash and $4.80
in a note.
   Pathe Entertainment's chairman is Alan Ladd Jr., the former
president of 20th Century Fox Pictures and chairman of
Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures. The company also holds interests in
banking, insurance, real estate and tourism.
   Pathe is owned by Italian businessmen Giancarlo Parretti and
Florio Fiorini, who also hold a controlling interest in the Cannon
Group Inc., a film production and distribution company.
   New World stock rose 75 cents to $5.75 a share on the American
Stock Exchange Friday. The discount below the $8.20-per-share
acquisition price reflected investors' doubts about the value of the
notes.
   New World, which lost $18.5 million in 1987 on revenues of $384.3
million, sold its Marvel Comics unit for $82.5 million.
   The production company posted operating losses of $79.1 million
on revenues of $220.8 million in the first nine months of 1988, and
carries $125 million in debt. New World announced in late January it
was exploring strategic and financial alternatives.
   New World's latest theatrical releases have been greeted by
sluggish box-office revenues. The company stopped reporting grosses
for ``Hellbound: Hellraiser II'' after the film collected just $11.9
million in 45 days of distribution.
   Upcoming New World titles include ``Heathers,'' ``Warlock,''
``The Punisher'' with Dolph Lundgren and ``Brenda Starr'' with
Brooke Shields.
   The company's television division produces the current series
``Tour of Duty,'' ``Murphy's Law,'' ``The Wonder Years'' and ``A
Fine Romance,'' and the soap opera ``Santa Barbara.''
</TEXT>
