<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 2240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AerodyneCharged     02-24 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Aerodyne Charged,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor Charged with Using Scrap in Planes, Tanks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida defense contractor was accused
Friday of illegally using scrap alloy instead of new metal to make
military turbine engine parts, a federal prosecutor said.
   Aerodyne Investment Castings Inc. was charged with a single count
of falsely certifying that the parts for aircraft and the M-1 Abrams
tank were new metal, said U.S. Attorney Robert Genzman.
   The firm has agreed to plead guilty, Genzman said, and will be
placed on five years probation and fined $250,000.
   As part of the agreement, Russell K. Baker, Jr., former
president, has resigned from the board of directors.
   Also, the company has fired certain corporate officers and
supervisors identified by the government in a sealed document,
according to the U.S. Attorney.
   The plea agreement will be presented to a federal judge for
formal acceptance. No date for the presentation has been set.
   Prosecutors alleged that Aerodyne submitted false certificates to
the defense department from 1980 through October 1987. The
certifications pertained to whether the parts met contract
specifications, the government said.
   According to prosecutors' allegations:
   _Aerodyne substituted ``scrap'' or re-used alloy in the
production of turbine engine parts in place of the newly-refined, or
virgin, alloy required under the contract with the Army and Air
Force;
   _Aerodyne certified that the parts provided to those agencies met
certain requirements demonstrated by tests performed on virgin alloy
while the parts were made of a mix of scrap and alloy.
   Aerodyne has agreed to pay $25,000 to the Office of the Inspector
General of the U.S. Department of Defense and $25,000 to the FBI as
reimbursement for investigative costs, Genzman said.
   Aerodyne, which employs about 175 people, has been a defense
contractor for the past decade. By agreeing to terms of the plea
agreement the company has taken a step toward rehabilitating itself
as a corporate entity, Genzman said in an announcement.
</TEXT>
