<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold 1stLd-Writethru f0285 02-24 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0285,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Retreats Slightly</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with yen-dollar rates, SUBS 13th graf, The dollar...
Picks up 14th graf pvs, Other late...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar sagged against the West German mark
and had a mixed showing against other currencies Friday despite
boosts in U.S. interest rates.
   Gold prices paused their recent advance. Republic National Bank
of New York quoted a bid of $389 for a troy ounce of gold at 4 p.m.
EST, down from Thursday's late bid of $390.70.
   In early U.S. trading, the dollar rose during a temporary flurry
of dollar-buying after the Federal Reserve Board announced it was
raising its discount rate by a half-point to 7 percent.
   The buying subsided after currency dealers decided the rate hike
would have little impact.
   An increase in the key rate, which is the interest the Fed
charges on loans to private banking institutions, was widely
anticipated in light of the decision by the nation's private banks
to raise their prime lending rates.
   On Thursday and Friday, a series of major banks drove up the
rates used as benchmarks for variable loan interest charges to 11.5
percent from 11 percent.
   Also, the dollar was sold due to persistent worries that failure
to solve the U.S. trade and budget deficit problems will cause
lasting economic damage.
   Many dealers decided to buy West German marks on the grounds that
interest rates in that country will probably rise soon because
inflationary pressures have been building up due to robust economic
activity.
   In New York, the dollar finished at 1.81875 marks, down from
1.82175 Thursday.
   ``We are expecting some interest rate increases in Germany as the
government acts to get control of inflation,'' said Zlatko
Glamuzina, chief currency dealer at Banco di Sicilia.
   Meanwhile, the dollar strengthened against the British pound. One
pound was trading late in London's day at $1.7520, cheaper for
buyers than $1.7595 on Thursday.
   Later, in New York, a pound cost $1.7530 compared to $1.7605
Thursday.
   The dollar was quoted in London at 126.53 Japanese yen, up from
126.29 yen in Tokyo at Thursday's close. In New York, the dollar
closed at 126.125 yen, down from 126.175 Thursday. Tokyo foreign
exchange markets were closed Friday for a national holiday, because
of Emperor Hirohito's funeral.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's levels, included: 1.55245 Swiss francs, up from 1.5505;
6.194 French francs, down from 6.2160; 1,342.50 Italian lire,
unchanged; and 1.19825 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19485.
   Selected late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Thursday: 1.8270 West German marks, up from 1.8215; 1.5602 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5535; 6.2265 French francs, up from 6.2125; 2.0630
Dutch guilders, up from 2.0590; 1,350.00 Italian lire, up from
1,344.50; 1.1990 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1958.
   Gold bullion prices were mostly lower after rising recently amid
evidence that inflation has accelerated. Investors frequently turn
to precious metals when inflation erodes the value of other assets.
   Gold traded in London at a late bid price of $390.20 a troy
ounce, down from $391.50 bid late Thursday. In Zurich, the late bid
price was $389.00 dollars, down from $391.75 bid late Thursday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
closed at $391.10 a troy ounce, 10 cents higher than Thursday's
settlement price.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $1.18 to close at a bid $390.68.
   Silver bullion prices were little changed. On New York's Comex,
silver for current delivery declined to $5.923 a troy ounce from
$5.931 Thursday.
   Earlier, in London, silver was unchanged at a bid of $6.04
dollars an ounce.
</TEXT>
