<FIRST>r f AM-Texaco-Dividend     02-24 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texaco-Dividend,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco Plans to Pay First Dividend in Cash Instead of Notes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. said Friday that the first of two
special dividends to be paid in late June will be made in cash
rather than notes, as previously announced.
   Texaco spokesman Peter Maneri said the decision to issue the
dividend in cash ``resulted from the expeditious closing of the
Texaco Canada deal along with the rising trend in short-term
interest rates.''
   Texaco completed the sale of its 78 percent share of Texaco
Canada Inc. to Imperial Oil Ltd. for $3.24 billion on Thursday,
Maneri said.
   Texaco announced on Jan. 29 after completing the sale of more
than $7 billion in assets as part of a major restructuring, that it
would pay two special dividends, one of $4 a share in notes and a
second of $3 a share in cash and $1 a share in preferred stock, for
a total of $8 per share, or about $1.95 billion.
   The company also said it plans to buy back $500 million of its
stock by August 1990.
   Maneri said the second dividend will be distributed as announced
with the proposed record date in August.
   Both dividends are subject to shareholder approval at the
company's annual meeting May 9.
</TEXT>
