<FIRST>r f BC-Shamrock-Polaroid     02-24 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Shamrock-Polaroid,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suitor Calls on Polaroid to Extend Stock Buyback Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shamrock Holdings Inc., which is
attempting a hostile takeover of Polaroid Corp., demanded Thursday
that the instant-camera company extend the deadline on an offer to
buy back its own stock.
   Shamrock, an investment company controlled by Roy E. Disney,
nephew of the late animator Walt Disney, said the deadline for
shareholders to accept Polaroid's $50-a-share offer for its own
stock should be pushed past the May 9 date of the company's annual
meeting.
   That would give shareholders a chance to assess the meeting's
outcome, said Shamrock, which itself is offering $45 a share for
stock in Cambridge, Mass.,-based Polaroid.
   Polaroid's offer to buy back 16 million shares, or 22 percent of
its stock, is set to expire March 20.
   In a letter to Polaroid released to the media, Shamrock President
Stanley P. Gold said, ``In its present form and given its present
expiration date, this offer is extremely coercive.''
   A call placed to Polaroid's offices after business hours wasn't
answered.
   The buyback, combined with other moves to put stock in friendly
hands, could give Polaroid management and its allies voting control
of up to 39 percent of the company before the meeting, Gold said.
   At the meeting, shareholders will vote on directors for Polaroid,
including a slate nominated by Shamrock.
</TEXT>
