<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 0042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PSNH-FraudSettlement     02-24 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PSNH-Fraud Settlement,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utility, Investors Settle Fraud Claim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Company of New Hampshire
and its top executives have settled a securities-fraud lawsuit
brought by holders of company stock warrants and bonds that helped
pay for completing the troubled Seabrook nuclear power plant, the
utility announced Thursday.
   ``The company and the officers and directors have denied and
continue to deny any wrongdoing, but they have entered into the
settlement to avoid further inconvenience, disruption, delay,
expense and the uncertainty of further litigation,'' the company
said in a statement.
   In part, the settlement would let the plaintiffs exercise
warrants for purchasing Public Service common stock, the company
statement said. The suspension of the warrants in June 1986, five
years before they were due to expire, prompted the lawsuit.
   ``I don't know whether this will give (the plaintiffs) the same
rights they had originally,'' before the warrants were suspended,
company spokesman Nicholas Ashooh said. He also could not say
whether the warrant and bondholders got anything else in the
settlement.
   ``Full details will be filed in Bankruptcy Court in the near
future,'' Ashooh said.
   The settlement is subject to approval by Public Service's federal
bankruptcy judge and the U.S. District Court in the southern
district of New York, where the case was set for trial next month.
   Public Service suspended the warrants as its finances worsened
because of licensing delays for Seabrook, Ashooh said. Public
Service owns 36 percent of the project, which was completed in July
1986 but remains unlicensed because of emergency-planning and
financial problems.
   Two New York firms, Spear, Leeds &amp; Kellogg and Elliott
Associates, L.P., filed the securities-fraud lawsuit about a month
before Public Service sought bankruptcy protection in January 1988.
Howard Schiffman, a lawyer for Spear, Leeds, said the firm sought to
recover $7 million including punitive damages and lawyers' fees.
   The firms charged that Public Service failed to give adequate
notice that it had suspended the warrants, in an attempt to mislead
investors and stall their attempts to seek relief.
   Public Service issued more than 18 million of the warrants along
with $425 million in 17{ percent debentures in December 1984. The
financing allowed Public Service to pull back from its first trip to
the brink of bankruptcy and to complete Seabrook.
   Holders of the warrants were able to exchange each for one share
of common stock by paying $5 cash or turning in debentures with $5 a
face value.
   The New York firms said in legal briefs that they bought the
warrants and debentures in 1987, unaware that the warrants had been
suspended. The firms alleged that Public Service failed to disclose
the suspension in 1987 filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
   If the settlement wins court approval, holders of the warrants
would be able to exchange lots of 200 warrants and $1,000 worth of
debentures for lots of 200 shares of common stock, the utility said
in its statement. Cash exercise of the warrants would be barred.
   Public Service said it could not predict what the securities
would be worth after the company emerges from bankruptcy protection.
</TEXT>
