<FIRST>r f BC-LeadingEdge     02-24 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Leading Edge,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Purchase Offer For Troubled Computer Maker Withdrawn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida retail computer chain owner has taken
back his offer to buy the name and major assets of Leading Edge
Hardware Products Inc. of Canton, which is under Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection from creditors.
   ``I have taken my offer off the table,'' Stewart Fason, owner of
PC Systems of Riviera Beach, Fla., told The Boston Globe in a story
reported Thursday.
   Fason and Leading Edge founder Michael B. Shane had signed an
agreement for Fason to acquire the name and major computer line of
Leading Edge for $921,000, the amount Leading Edge owed Fason.
   Fason also had agreed to assume responsibility for $11 million
owed to Leading Edge dealers who had paid in advance for computers
they did not get.
   Leading Edge sold low-priced IBM-PC clones made in Asia but
stopped shipping computers last month when it was caught in a cash
squeeze.
   An unrelated legal dispute delayed the sale of Leading Edge to
Fason, and a group of dealers moved last week to force the company
into Chapter 11 bankruptcy. Leading Edge then filed voluntarily for
Chapter 11 protection.
   Steven Gray, a Boston lawyer, was appointed trustee.
   Fason said he wrote to Gray about his plan to buy Leading Edge
and urged him to move quickly to protect Leading Edge's name. Fason
said he told Gray to consider the offer withdrawn unless it was
accepted by 4 p.m. Wednesday.
   Fason said Gray did not call.
   ``Apparently Mr. Gray decided my plan wasn't good enough,'' Fason
said.
</TEXT>
