<FILEID>AP-NR-02-24-89 1904EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Stockbroker     02-24 0403</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Stockbroker,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accused Stockbroker Ordered Held Without Bail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stockbroker accused of bilking clients and banks
of between $2 million and $5 million and then fleeing the country
was ordered held without bail Friday pending trial.
   Walter F. Curran, a former Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. broker, was
arrested last week re-entering the United States at a remote New
York town after two weeks in Canada.
   In denying bail, U.S. Magistrate Joyce L. Alexander said Curran
fled with two passports, an international driver's license, a plane
ticket to Germany, valuable jewelry and the combination to a safe
that has not been located.
   She also noted he carried $132,000 in cash when he was caught at
the border and may have additional assets hidden abroad.
   ``I do not believe...the court has a reasonable assurance that
you will appear'' to face trial if released on bail, Alexander told
Curran.
   ``Notwithstanding family, notwithstanding friends, you might
leave. You have already done it once, and you might do it again,''
she said.
   Curran, 46, allegedly persuaded clients to invest money in his
personal account rather than through the brokerage firm with the
promise of 20 percent interest. Assistant U.S. Attorney Peter Mullin
said Curran converted the money to his own use.
   Mullin said the broker wrote six checks, each for $125,000 to
$500,000, on overdrawn bank accounts. The prosecutor said the
investment and bank frauds involved lossed of between $2 million and
$5 million.
   Curran is charged with one count of bank fraud and one count of
mail fraud. If convicted, he could face up to 10 years in prison and
a $500,000 fine. No trial date was set.
   Defense attorney Thomas Troy said Curran was confused and upset
about his financial problems when he left for Canada but was
overcome with remorse and decided to return to the United States to
``face the music.''
   Troy said he would appeal the magistrate's decision.
   He said Curran's family and friends would stake their houses and
other assets as surety for future court appearances, and offered to
have Troy wear an electronic device that would signal authorities if
he moved 150 feet from his home.
   During a two-day bail hearing, FBI Agent Richard J. Egan
testified that Curran drove to Canada on Feb. 1 after leaving a note
to his wife saying he was going to New York on business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
