<HEAD>Bond Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An increase in the Federal Reserve's key lending
rate drove bond prices lower and short-term interest rates higher
Friday.
   The Fed's anti-inflation action pushed its discount rate, the
interest it charges on loans to member banks, from 6.5 percent to 7
percent _ its highest level in about three years.
   The Treasury's closely watched 30-year bond tumbled about ]
point, or $3.75 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which
moves inversely to its price, jumped to 9.18 percent from 9.14
percent late Thursday, the highest level since September.
   Rates on short-term government bonds came under the most pressure.
   ``The short end got pretty well crushed right after the news'' of
the discount-rate hike, said Steven A. Wood, an economist with
BankAmerica Capital Markets Group in San Francisco.
   ``It was just confirmation that the Fed really means business in
terms of inflation. It confirmed that the Fed has clearly
tightened,'' he said.
   A hike in the discount rate normally drives short-term interest
rates higher as some banks must borrow to meet reserve requirements.
   The discount rate is now at its highest level since April 1986.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
government issues fell [ point to 3-16 point, intermediate
maturities declined \ point to 9-32 point and long-term issues lost
5-16 point, according to figures provided by Telerate Inc., a
financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 2.15 to 1,118.03.
   In corporate trading, industrials also retreated. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price
movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, was down 0.41 at 295.54.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds slipped [ point to 9017-32. The average yield
to maturity edged up to 7.73 percent from 7.72 percent late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 8.94 percent as the
discount climbed 7 basis points to 8.64 percent. Yields on six-month
bills leaped to 9.21 percent as the discount jumped 7 basis points
to 8.70 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 9.50 percent as
the discount advanced 4 basis points to 8.77 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted late in the day at 913-16 percent, up from 911-16
percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
