<HEAD>Eastern Pilots Petition Supreme Court for Review</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: ADDS new 6th graf to UPDATE with National Mediation Board action;
picks up 6th graf pvs bg'ng, Leaders of ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Line Pilots Association on Friday
petitioned the U.S. Supreme Court for a review of Eastern Airlines'
decision last fall to lay off about 4,000 employees and cut back
service.
   The pilots union said its petition ``will have implications for
all Eastern asset transfers,'' including the pending sale of the
airline's Northeast shuttle service to developer Donald Trump for
$365 million in cash.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell in Miami said the airline would
have no comment on the petition because officials had not seen the
documents.
   The pilots' announcement came amid mounting tension as a March 3
strike deadline against Miami-based Eastern set by its militant
machinists union approaches.
   Intensified talks involving Eastern management, the machinists
and federal mediators, which began Wednesday in Washington, have so
far failed to produce a settlement.
   The National Mediation Board recommended Friday that President
Bush intervene and block the planned strike, according to
administration sources. The agency suggested Bush name a
presidential emergency board to investigate the protracted dispute,
the sources said. If the president accepted the recommendation it
would automatically delay the strike by 60 days.
   Leaders of the union representing flight attendants at Eastern,
meanwhile, voted unanimously Friday to ask members to honor a strike
by the machinists.
   The leadership of the Eastern pilots union has polled its members
on the strike issue.
   In its earlier court arguments against the layoffs and reduced
service, the pilots union had asserted it was not an efficiency
move, but part of a ``continuing pattern of anti-labor tactics
designed to intimidate employees in the midst of ongoing labor
negotiations.''
   Last August, a U.S. District Court judge in Washington issued a
restraining order against the Eastern plan. The airline appealed,
and in late September a three-member appeals court panel overturned
the restraining order.
   The pilots union's request to have the case heard by the full
11-member appeals court was rejected in early January.
</TEXT>
